INSERT INTO transcript_chunks (lesson_id, chunk_text, start_time, end_time)
SELECT
    l.id AS lesson_id,
    segment.value->>'text' AS chunk_text,
    (segment.value->>'start')::numeric AS start_time,
    (segment.value->>'end')::numeric AS end_time
FROM lessons l
CROSS JOIN jsonb_array_elements(
    '[{"start":0,"end":5.88,"text":"Welcome to the complete Python Mastery course. In this course, you''re going to learn everything"},{"start":5.88,"end":10.16,"text":"about Python from basics to more advanced concepts. So by the end of the course, you''ll"},{"start":10.16,"end":15.92,"text":"be able to confidently use Python for AI, machine learning, web development and automation."},{"start":15.92,"end":20.4,"text":"If you have been looking for a comprehensive, easy to follow, well-organized and practical"},{"start":20.4,"end":24.76,"text":"course that takes you from zero to hero, this is the right Python course for you. You don''t"},{"start":24.76,"end":28.96,"text":"need any prior knowledge of Python to get started. I will explain everything step by"},{"start":28.96,"end":32.64,"text":"step in simple terms so you can build a solid foundation."},{"start":32.64,"end":37.36,"text":"I''m Mosh Hamadani, a software engineer with over 20 years of experience and I''ve taught"},{"start":37.36,"end":42.16,"text":"millions how to code and become professional software engineers through my YouTube channel"},{"start":42.16,"end":47.52,"text":"and online school code with Mosh.com. If you''re new here, make sure to subscribe as I upload"},{"start":47.52,"end":50.96,"text":"new videos all the time. Now let''s jump in and get started."},{"start":50.96,"end":62.88,"text":"In this course, you''re going to learn everything you need to get started with Python. Just be aware"},{"start":62.88,"end":67.44,"text":"that I''ve designed this course for beginners, so if you have some programming experience, check out"},{"start":67.44,"end":72.64,"text":"my other Python course for developers. You can see the link on the top right corner of this video."},{"start":73.28,"end":79.28,"text":"So, Python is the world''s fastest growing and most popular programming language,"},{"start":79.36,"end":85.92,"text":"not just amongst software developers, but also amongst mathematicians, data analysts,"},{"start":85.92,"end":92.64,"text":"scientists, accountants, network engineers, and even kids. In fact, it''s the ideal programming"},{"start":92.64,"end":99.04,"text":"language to learn first. But what makes Python so special? Here are six reasons. With Python,"},{"start":99.04,"end":105.36,"text":"you can solve complex problems in less time with fewer lines of code than many other languages."},{"start":105.92,"end":113.44,"text":"That''s why huge companies like Google, Spotify, Dropbox, and Facebook have embraced this beautiful"},{"start":113.44,"end":119.28,"text":"and powerful language. Here''s an example. Let''s say we want to extract the first three"},{"start":119.28,"end":124.4,"text":"characters of the text Hello, Warp. This is the code we would have to write in C-sharp."},{"start":125.12,"end":129.84,"text":"This is how we would do this in JavaScript. And here''s how we would do it in Python."},{"start":130.48,"end":134.8,"text":"See how clean and simple the language is? And that''s just the beginning."},{"start":134.8,"end":140,"text":"Python is a multipurpose language, and you can use it for a wide range of jobs, such as data"},{"start":140,"end":146.8,"text":"analysis, AI, and machine learning, writing automation scripts, building web, mobile,"},{"start":146.8,"end":153.36,"text":"and desktop applications, as well as software testing or even hacking. So, if you want a high-paying,"},{"start":153.36,"end":159.84,"text":"long-lasting career in any of these areas, especially AI and machine learning, Python is"},{"start":159.84,"end":166.48,"text":"the language to put those opportunities at your fingertips. In fact, according to Indeed.com,"},{"start":166.48,"end":174.56,"text":"the average salary of a Python developer in the US was over $115,000 in March 2018."},{"start":175.2,"end":181.44,"text":"And here are four more reasons that make Python the most desirable language. Python is a high-level"},{"start":181.44,"end":187.84,"text":"language so you don''t have to worry about complex tasks, such as memory management, as you do in C++."},{"start":188.56,"end":195.44,"text":"It''s cross-platform, which means you can build and run Python apps on Windows, Mac, and Linux."},{"start":195.44,"end":199.92,"text":"It has a huge community, so whenever you get stuck, there is someone out there to help."},{"start":200.48,"end":206.96,"text":"And it has a large ecosystem of libraries, frameworks, and tools. Whatever you want to do,"},{"start":206.96,"end":212.8,"text":"it is likely that someone else has done it before, because Python has been around for over 20 years."},{"start":213.52,"end":218.96,"text":"There are two versions of Python out there. Python 2, which is the legacy version of Python,"},{"start":218.96,"end":225.52,"text":"and is going to be supported until year 2020. And Python 3, which is Python for the future."},{"start":225.52,"end":230.96,"text":"In this course, you''re going to learn Python 3. Hi, my name is Mosh Hamadani, and I''m going to be"},{"start":230.96,"end":236.24,"text":"your instructor in this course. I''m a software engineer with 18 years of experience, and I have"},{"start":236.24,"end":243.44,"text":"taught way over a million people how to code or how to become top professional software engineers."},{"start":243.44,"end":250.08,"text":"To learn more about me and my courses, head over to codewithmosh.com. All right, now let''s get started."},{"start":252.72,"end":258,"text":"All right, the first thing I want you to do is open your browser and head over to python.org."},{"start":258,"end":262.96,"text":"On this page, under Download, you can download the latest version of Python. At the time of"},{"start":262.96,"end":268.48,"text":"this video, the latest version is Python 3.13. Chances are in the future, when you''re watching"},{"start":268.48,"end":272.72,"text":"this video, there is a newer version of Python available. Don''t worry, what I''m going to show"},{"start":272.72,"end":277.68,"text":"you in this tutorial will apply to future versions of Python as well. So go ahead and download the"},{"start":277.68,"end":283.68,"text":"latest version. Now, if you''re on Windows, before you click install, make sure to check this little"},{"start":283.68,"end":289.28,"text":"box here that says Add Python to path. This step is very important, and it will save you a lot of"},{"start":289.28,"end":295.68,"text":"headaches later. So check this box and follow the installation. Now to verify that Python is"},{"start":295.68,"end":303.6,"text":"successfully installed, click this magnifier. And here in this search bar, type terminal. Now here"},{"start":303.6,"end":309.6,"text":"in the terminal window, type Python dash dash version, this verifies that we have successfully"},{"start":309.6,"end":317.04,"text":"installed Python 3.13. Now if you''re on Mac, press command and space to bring up the spotlight"},{"start":317.04,"end":324.4,"text":"search. Here type terminal. Now to verify that we have installed Python correctly, on Mac, we should"},{"start":324.4,"end":333.76,"text":"type Python 3 space dash dash version. So as you can see, I''ve successfully installed Python 3.13 on"},{"start":333.76,"end":346.4,"text":"this machine. So this environment you see here is what we call Python interpreter, which is basically"},{"start":346.4,"end":351.84,"text":"a program that executes Python code. We can type our Python code in a file and give it to this"},{"start":351.84,"end":358.24,"text":"interpreter, or we can type our code directly here in this interactive shell. So here we can write an"},{"start":358.24,"end":365.92,"text":"expression like 2 plus 2. In programming, an expression is a piece of code that produces a value. So here"},{"start":365.92,"end":372.08,"text":"when we add 2 plus 2, we get a value. That is why we refer to this piece of code as an expression."},{"start":372.8,"end":380.32,"text":"So enter, we get 4. Let''s try a different kind of expression. Let''s see if 2 is greater than 1."},{"start":381.12,"end":385.68,"text":"We get true, which is an example of a Boolean value. You''re going to learn about these Boolean"},{"start":385.68,"end":394.32,"text":"values in the next section. Now what if we type 2 is greater than 5? Enter, we get false. So in"},{"start":394.32,"end":401.44,"text":"programming we have true and false, which are similar to yes and no in English. Now what if we type"},{"start":401.52,"end":409.12,"text":"2 is greater than, but we don''t add a second value here. Just press enter. We get a syntax error."},{"start":409.68,"end":415.44,"text":"In programming, syntax means grammar. So just like we have the concept of grammar in the languages"},{"start":415.44,"end":420.96,"text":"that we speak, we have the exact same concept in programming. If we write a sentence that is not"},{"start":420.96,"end":426.8,"text":"grammatically correct, chances are some people may not understand that sentence. So in this example,"},{"start":426.8,"end":432.56,"text":"we have this expression which is incomplete. It doesn''t have the right grammar or syntax. That is"},{"start":432.56,"end":439.12,"text":"why Python interpreter is complaining by returning an error. So this interactive shell is a great"},{"start":439.12,"end":444.16,"text":"way to quickly experiment with a bit of Python code, but that''s not how we build real-world"},{"start":444.16,"end":449.04,"text":"applications. To do that, we need a code editor. And that''s what I''m going to show you in the next"},{"start":449.04,"end":462,"text":"lecture. When it comes to typing Python code, you have two options. You can use a code editor or"},{"start":462,"end":469.12,"text":"an IDE, which is short for integrated development environment. An IDE is basically a code editor"},{"start":469.12,"end":475.12,"text":"with some fancy features like auto completion, which means as you type code, this feature helps"},{"start":475.12,"end":480,"text":"you complete your code. So you don''t have to type every character by hand. It''s a productivity"},{"start":480,"end":485.92,"text":"boosting feature. It also gives you additional features like debugging, which means finding and"},{"start":485.92,"end":492,"text":"fixing bugs in your programs, testing and so on. For both code editors and IDEs, there are so many"},{"start":492,"end":499.12,"text":"options out there. The most popular code editors are VS code, Adam and Sublime. You can use the"},{"start":499.12,"end":504.48,"text":"code editor that you prefer. In terms of the IDEs, again, there are so many options out there,"},{"start":504.56,"end":510.96,"text":"the most popular one is PyCharm. In this course, I''m going to use VS code or Visual Studio code,"},{"start":510.96,"end":515.92,"text":"because that''s my favorite code editor. Later in the course, I will show you how to install a"},{"start":515.92,"end":522.64,"text":"plugin or an extension that will convert VS code to a powerful IDE. So before going any further,"},{"start":522.64,"end":534.32,"text":"head over to code.visualstudio.com and download the latest version of VS code."},{"start":534.96,"end":539.84,"text":"Now with VS code open, on the top, from the file menu, go to open,"},{"start":541.2,"end":547.28,"text":"and somewhere on your desk, create a new folder. Let''s call this folder Hello World."},{"start":549.12,"end":556.96,"text":"And then open it. Beautiful. Now click this icon on the top. This opens up the Explorer panel."},{"start":556.96,"end":562.8,"text":"In this panel, you can see all the files and folders in your project. So let''s add a new file"},{"start":562.8,"end":572.96,"text":"and call that app.py. So all our Python files should have the py extension. Press enter. Now"},{"start":572.96,"end":578.96,"text":"let''s close this and type a bit of Python code. In this lecture, we''re going to use one of the"},{"start":578.96,"end":585.2,"text":"built-in functions in Python called print. So in Python, we have a lot of built-in functions for"},{"start":585.2,"end":590.4,"text":"performing various kinds of tasks. For example, as a metaphor, think of the remote control of your"},{"start":590.4,"end":596.56,"text":"TV. On this remote control, you have a bunch of functions like turn on, turn off, change the channel,"},{"start":596.56,"end":602.64,"text":"change the volume and so on. These are the built-in functions in your TV. We have the same concept"},{"start":602.64,"end":608.16,"text":"in Python and many other programming languages. So one of these built-in functions that comes with"},{"start":608.16,"end":615.76,"text":"Python is print. And we can use this to print something on the screen. Now whenever you want to"},{"start":615.76,"end":623.04,"text":"use a function, you should open and close parentheses. In programming, we say we''re calling the print"},{"start":623.04,"end":629.92,"text":"function. Calling a function means executing it. Now let''s display the hello world message on the"},{"start":629.92,"end":635.52,"text":"screen. Whenever you want to work with text, you should put your text in between quotes,"},{"start":636.08,"end":644.16,"text":"either double quotes or single quotes. Now I''m going to go with double quotes and add hello world."},{"start":645.12,"end":652.32,"text":"And then put a happy Persian cat here. Beautiful. Save the changes with command and s on Mac or"},{"start":652.32,"end":658.96,"text":"control and s on Windows. Now to execute this code, we need to go back to command prompt on Windows"},{"start":658.96,"end":665.28,"text":"or terminal on Mac. But the good news is that we don''t have to switch programs. Here in VS code, we"},{"start":665.28,"end":673.04,"text":"have an integrated terminal. So press control and back tick. That is the key before number one on"},{"start":673.04,"end":680.4,"text":"your keyboard. That is just below the escape button. So this is our integrated terminal. Now if you''re"},{"start":680.4,"end":687.76,"text":"on Windows type Python, if you''re on Mac or Linux type Python 3. And next to that add the name of our"},{"start":687.76,"end":696,"text":"file. That is app.py. And here''s our hello world message in the terminal. Beautiful. Now let''s take"},{"start":696,"end":700.96,"text":"this to the next level and make it a little bit more interesting. Let''s close this terminal window"},{"start":701.52,"end":708.16,"text":"by pressing control and back tick and add a second line of code. So one more time print."},{"start":709.6,"end":716.4,"text":"This time let''s add quotes with a star in between them. Now let''s say we want to repeat this star"},{"start":716.4,"end":725.36,"text":"10 times. So here we can multiply this by 10. Save the changes. Open up the terminal and run our"},{"start":725.36,"end":733.2,"text":"program. And you can see this star is repeated 10 times. So as you see the instructions on our"},{"start":733.2,"end":739.36,"text":"program are executed from top to bottom in order. In the next lecture, I''m going to show you how to"},{"start":739.36,"end":751.12,"text":"convert this VS code to a powerful IDE for building Python applications. In this lecture, I''m going to"},{"start":751.12,"end":758.08,"text":"show you how to convert VS code to a powerful IDE by using an extension called Python. With this"},{"start":758.08,"end":764.32,"text":"extension or plugin, we get a number of features such as linting, which basically means analyzing"},{"start":764.32,"end":771.36,"text":"our code for potential errors. We also get debugging, which involves finding and fixing errors. We''ll"},{"start":771.36,"end":777.12,"text":"look at this later in the course. We also get auto completion, which basically helps us write code"},{"start":777.12,"end":782.8,"text":"faster. So we don''t have to type every character. We get code formatting, which is all about making"},{"start":782.8,"end":789.76,"text":"our code clean and readable, just like how we format our articles, newspapers, books to make them clean"},{"start":789.76,"end":796,"text":"and readable. We get unit testing, which involves writing a bunch of tests for our code. We can"},{"start":796,"end":802.08,"text":"run these tests in an automated fashion to make sure our code is behaving correctly. And finally,"},{"start":802.08,"end":807.92,"text":"we get code snippets, which are reusable code blocks that we can quickly generate. So we don''t"},{"start":807.92,"end":812.88,"text":"have to type them all by hand. Now don''t worry about memorizing any of these. As we go through the"},{"start":812.88,"end":819.2,"text":"course, you''re going to learn about these features. So back to VS code on the left side, click this"},{"start":819.2,"end":825.6,"text":"icon. This opens the extensions panel where we can install additional extensions to enhance VS code"},{"start":825.6,"end":832.32,"text":"up here in the search bar, search for Python. All right, look, we have an official extension"},{"start":832.32,"end":840.16,"text":"for Python from Microsoft. So go ahead and install this. Now you might see a box here saying reload,"},{"start":840.16,"end":845.2,"text":"if you see that, make sure to click it to reload VS code. Now with this extension installed, we have"},{"start":845.2,"end":849.84,"text":"a ton of new functionality in VS code for writing Python code. The first one I''m going to show you"},{"start":849.84,"end":856.4,"text":"in this lesson is the ability to run our code. So back to app.py, look, with this extension"},{"start":856.4,"end":862.08,"text":"installed, now we have this play icon on the top for running our code. So if we click it,"},{"start":862.08,"end":865.12,"text":"we can see the output of our program in the terminal window."},{"start":871.52,"end":876.8,"text":"In this lecture, I''m going to show you linting and action. So let''s start by writing some invalid"},{"start":876.8,"end":885.28,"text":"code like this print space with no parentheses, and then hello, work. Earlier, I told you that print"},{"start":885.28,"end":890.56,"text":"is a built in function. And whenever you want to use or call a function, you should always use"},{"start":890.56,"end":896.16,"text":"parentheses. Now to be more precise, this is actually valid Python to code. But because we''re"},{"start":896.16,"end":902.88,"text":"using Python three here, this is invalid code from Python threes point of view. So now when I save"},{"start":902.88,"end":909.6,"text":"the changes, you can see this red on the line here. Let''s hover our mouse over this underlying."},{"start":910.32,"end":916,"text":"You can see this tooltip. It''s coming from pilot. And here''s the error message missing parentheses"},{"start":916,"end":922.16,"text":"in call to print. Did you mean print with parentheses? So this is the benefit of linting."},{"start":922.16,"end":926.96,"text":"As you''re writing code, you can see potential problems in your code. You don''t have to wait"},{"start":926.96,"end":935.6,"text":"to run your program to see these errors. So now if we put parentheses here and save the changes,"},{"start":935.6,"end":942.96,"text":"you can see that red underlying is gone. Let''s look at another error. Let''s type two plus and"},{"start":942.96,"end":950.24,"text":"then save the changes. Earlier, we ran this code in Python interpreters interactive shell. There,"},{"start":950.24,"end":956.96,"text":"we got a syntax or grammar error. So if you hover your mouse here one more time, you can see"},{"start":956.96,"end":963.68,"text":"pilot is telling us that this is invalid syntax or invalid grammar. It''s like an incomplete sentence."},{"start":964.32,"end":970.16,"text":"So this is linting in action. Now let me show you a couple useful shortcuts here. On the top,"},{"start":970.72,"end":977.76,"text":"look at the view menu. Here we have this problems menu. Look at the shortcut on Mac, it''s shift,"},{"start":977.76,"end":984.16,"text":"command and M. On Windows is probably shift, control M. So as you''re working with VS code,"},{"start":984.16,"end":988.72,"text":"try to memorize these shortcuts, because they really help you write code faster."},{"start":989.6,"end":997.12,"text":"Now let''s take a look at this problems panel. So this problems panel lists all the issues in your"},{"start":997.12,"end":1002.56,"text":"code in one place. So if you have an application with multiple files, this is really useful because"},{"start":1002.56,"end":1009.12,"text":"some of those files may not currently be open. So this linter, pilot will analyze all your files."},{"start":1009.12,"end":1014.4,"text":"And if it finds any issues, it will list them here in the problems panel. Now you can also put this"},{"start":1014.4,"end":1021.36,"text":"on the right side of the screen. So let''s put it here. So as you write code, these problems will"},{"start":1021.36,"end":1027.28,"text":"appear here. Now let''s fix this issue. So I''m going to add three here, save the changes, and you can"},{"start":1027.28,"end":1033.36,"text":"see the problem disappeared. And one last thing before we finish this lecture. Once again on the"},{"start":1033.36,"end":1040.32,"text":"top, let''s go to the view menu. The first item is command palette. This is a very important feature"},{"start":1040.32,"end":1047.2,"text":"in VS code. Once again, look at the shortcut that is shift, command and P on Mac, or shift, control P"},{"start":1047.2,"end":1054.64,"text":"on Windows. With this command palette, you can execute various commands in VS code. If you type"},{"start":1054.64,"end":1061.04,"text":"lint here, you can see all commands related to linting. As you can see, all these commands are"},{"start":1061.04,"end":1067.2,"text":"prefixed with Python, because these commands come with the Python extension that we installed"},{"start":1067.2,"end":1073.68,"text":"earlier. So these are additional features available to us in VS code. The first command here is select"},{"start":1073.68,"end":1080.88,"text":"linter. In this list, you can see various linters available for pilot. So as you''re reading tutorials"},{"start":1080.88,"end":1087.04,"text":"or talking to other people, you will hear about linters such as flake eight, my pi, pep eight,"},{"start":1087.04,"end":1093.68,"text":"and so on. Different developers prefer different linters. I personally prefer pilot, that is the"},{"start":1093.68,"end":1100.24,"text":"most popular one. And that is the default linter set in the Python extension of VS code. If you''re"},{"start":1100.24,"end":1106,"text":"adventurous, you can try using other linters on your own. The difference between these linters is in"},{"start":1106,"end":1112.16,"text":"how they find and report errors. Some error messages are more meaningful or more friendly,"},{"start":1112.16,"end":1118.16,"text":"the others are more ambiguous. So that''s all about linting. In the next lecture, we''ll talk about"},{"start":1118.16,"end":1130.32,"text":"formatting code. In Python community, we have a bunch of documents called Python enhancement"},{"start":1130.32,"end":1138.32,"text":"proposals or peps. Here on Google, if you search for Python peps, you can see the list of all these"},{"start":1138.32,"end":1148.48,"text":"peps under python.org slash dev slash peps. Let''s have a quick look here. So here are the peps."},{"start":1148.48,"end":1154.72,"text":"You can see each pep has a number and a title. The one that is very popular amongst Python"},{"start":1154.72,"end":1161.04,"text":"developers is pep eight, which is a style guide for Python code. A style guide is basically a"},{"start":1161.04,"end":1166.96,"text":"document that defines a bunch of rules for formatting and styling our code. If you follow"},{"start":1166.96,"end":1172,"text":"these conventions, the code that you write will end up being consistent with other people''s code."},{"start":1172.64,"end":1178.24,"text":"If you have time, you can go ahead and read this pep eight documentation. But if not, don''t worry,"},{"start":1178.24,"end":1183.12,"text":"because throughout the course, I''m going to explain the key things in pep eight. In this"},{"start":1183.12,"end":1188.56,"text":"lecture, I''m going to show you a tool that helps you automatically format your code according to pep"},{"start":1188.56,"end":1197.2,"text":"eight. So back in VS code, let''s write some Python code x equals one. Here I''m declaring a variable"},{"start":1197.2,"end":1201.68,"text":"and setting it to one. If you''re not familiar with variables, don''t worry, in the next section,"},{"start":1201.68,"end":1207.28,"text":"you''re going to learn about them. So according to pep eight, this code is considered ugly,"},{"start":1207.28,"end":1213.92,"text":"because by convention, we should add a space around this equal sign or the assignment operator."},{"start":1214.48,"end":1218.64,"text":"Now, since you''re starting out with Python, you probably don''t know these rules. So let me show"},{"start":1218.64,"end":1224.08,"text":"you a tool that helps you automatically format your code. Let''s revert this back to its original"},{"start":1224.08,"end":1230.48,"text":"state. Now we need to go back to the command palette. Remember, so it''s right here under view,"},{"start":1230.48,"end":1238.32,"text":"and the shortcut is shift command and P. Here if you search for format, you can see this command"},{"start":1238.32,"end":1244.08,"text":"format document. The first time you execute this command, you''re going to see this message here."},{"start":1245.04,"end":1250.72,"text":"Formatter auto pep eight is not installed. So there are a bunch of tools for formatting Python"},{"start":1250.72,"end":1256.72,"text":"code. The most popular one is auto pep eight. And this is the tool that this Python extension"},{"start":1256.72,"end":1262.24,"text":"we installed uses to format our code. Now if you don''t see this, you can install auto pep eight"},{"start":1262.24,"end":1268.96,"text":"using the extensions panel. So once again, on the left side, click this icon and search for auto pep"},{"start":1268.96,"end":1278.16,"text":"eight. There it is. Let''s install it. Good. So let''s go ahead and install this."},{"start":1278.32,"end":1287.36,"text":"Good. Now one more time, let''s open up the command palette and execute format document."},{"start":1288.64,"end":1293.6,"text":"See, these two automatically formats our code. Beautiful. Let''s take a look at another example."},{"start":1294.24,"end":1299.92,"text":"I''m going to declare another variable, y and set it to two, and a variable with a long name,"},{"start":1299.92,"end":1306.72,"text":"like unit underlying price. I''m set this to three. Now some developers have this habit of"},{"start":1306.72,"end":1315.6,"text":"formatting their variable declarations like this. So they put all these equal signs in the same column."},{"start":1315.6,"end":1321.36,"text":"According to pep eight, this is considered ugly. So once again, let''s format our code."},{"start":1322.4,"end":1328.24,"text":"That is better. Beautiful. Now let me show you a trick. Opening up this command palette and"},{"start":1328.24,"end":1334,"text":"searching for format document every time is a little bit time consuming. So I''m going to show you"},{"start":1334,"end":1337.92,"text":"how to have your file automatically formatted as soon as you save the changes."},{"start":1338.96,"end":1348.64,"text":"On the top, let''s go to the code menu, preferences and settings. Here in the search box, search for"},{"start":1348.64,"end":1358.32,"text":"format on save. So we have this option editor format on save, tick this. Now back to app.py."},{"start":1359.2,"end":1363.2,"text":"I''m going to change the formatting of these lines, make them really ugly."},{"start":1363.92,"end":1369.92,"text":"Now, as soon as I save the changes, you can see my code is reformatted. Beautiful."},{"start":1376.32,"end":1380.8,"text":"All right, now let''s talk about a few different ways to run Python code. As I told you before,"},{"start":1380.8,"end":1386.4,"text":"one way to run Python code is by opening the terminal window. If you''re on Windows type Python,"},{"start":1386.4,"end":1392.32,"text":"if you''re on Mac type Python three, followed by the name of the file. This approach is useful in"},{"start":1392.32,"end":1397.76,"text":"situations where you don''t have access to a code editor. Okay, now with the Python extension in"},{"start":1397.76,"end":1402.4,"text":"VS code, there is a simpler way to run Python code. We get this play button on the top."},{"start":1402.96,"end":1408.48,"text":"When we click it, we see the output in the terminal. But clicking this button every time we change our"},{"start":1408.48,"end":1413.76,"text":"code is a little bit tedious. So let me show you how to associate a shortcut to this button."},{"start":1413.76,"end":1419.44,"text":"First, we close this. Next, we bring up the command palette. The shortcut on Mac is shift"},{"start":1419.44,"end":1427.36,"text":"command and P on Windows is shift control P. Here we search for open keyboard shortcuts."},{"start":1428.08,"end":1434.08,"text":"Look, we have this command up here. Now on this window, we can see all the commands in VS code"},{"start":1434.08,"end":1440.8,"text":"and the shortcuts associated with them. Here in the search bar, search for run Python file."},{"start":1441.76,"end":1447.2,"text":"Okay, so this is the command that is associated with the play button. As you can see, we don''t"},{"start":1447.2,"end":1453.52,"text":"currently have any key bindings or shortcuts here. So double click in this column. Now here you can"},{"start":1453.52,"end":1460.32,"text":"press any key combination for creating a shortcut. I''m going to press control and R. Okay, now we"},{"start":1460.32,"end":1468.16,"text":"press enter. With this in place, we can go back to app.py and press control R. And here we see the"},{"start":1468.16,"end":1477.28,"text":"output beautiful. Let me talk about Python. We mean two separate things that are closely related."},{"start":1477.28,"end":1483.28,"text":"Python language and a particular implementation. Python as a language is just a specification"},{"start":1483.28,"end":1490.16,"text":"that defines a set of rules and grammar for writing Python code. A Python implementation is"},{"start":1490.16,"end":1496.56,"text":"basically a program that understands those rules and can execute Python code. Earlier in the course,"},{"start":1496.64,"end":1502.48,"text":"we downloaded Python from python.org. This is the default implementation of Python called"},{"start":1502.48,"end":1509.12,"text":"C Python. It''s a program written in C. That''s why it''s called C Python. So here in terminal,"},{"start":1509.12,"end":1515.44,"text":"when we run Python, we get this C Python. This is the default implementation of Python. There are"},{"start":1515.44,"end":1522.88,"text":"a few other implementations out there such as Jython written in Java, Iron Python written in C sharp,"},{"start":1522.88,"end":1529.6,"text":"and PyPy written in a subset of Python itself. As new features are added to the Python language,"},{"start":1529.6,"end":1534.96,"text":"they are first supported by C Python because that''s the default implementation. And then they will"},{"start":1534.96,"end":1541.04,"text":"gradually come to the other implementations. In theory, if we give some Python code to any of"},{"start":1541.04,"end":1546.48,"text":"these implementations, we should get the same result. But in practice, that''s not always the case."},{"start":1547.04,"end":1551.04,"text":"Certain features may be available in one implementation, but not another."},{"start":1551.52,"end":1555.76,"text":"Or they may just behave a little bit differently in a particular implementation."},{"start":1556.32,"end":1561.76,"text":"Now you might ask, what is the point of this? Why do we have several implementations of Python?"},{"start":1561.76,"end":1567.68,"text":"Wouldn''t C Python be enough? Well, it''s for the same reason that we have multiple operating systems"},{"start":1567.68,"end":1573.36,"text":"or multiple browsers or multiple programming languages. After all these years, we programmers"},{"start":1573.36,"end":1578.96,"text":"haven''t agreed on a single programming language. And that''s the same story with Python implementations."},{"start":1579.68,"end":1585.28,"text":"However, there is one technical reason behind these implementations that you should be aware of."},{"start":1585.84,"end":1593.12,"text":"Since Jython is implemented in Java, it allows you to reuse some existing Java code in a Python"},{"start":1593.12,"end":1599.12,"text":"program. So if you''re a Java developer and you want to import some Java code into a Python program,"},{"start":1599.12,"end":1605.36,"text":"you should use Jython instead of C Python. Similarly, Iron Python is written in C sharp,"},{"start":1605.36,"end":1610.24,"text":"so if you''re a C sharp developer and want to bring some C sharp code into a Python program,"},{"start":1610.24,"end":1617.36,"text":"you will have to use Iron Python. Next, we''ll look at how exactly C Python executes Python code."},{"start":1622.64,"end":1629.6,"text":"The programming languages we use, like C, C sharp, Java, Python, these are all simple text-based"},{"start":1629.6,"end":1634.96,"text":"languages that we humans understand. Computers don''t understand them. They only understand"},{"start":1634.96,"end":1640.56,"text":"machine code. So if we have some code written in C, we should convert it to machine code."},{"start":1640.56,"end":1647.76,"text":"And that''s the job of a C compiler. So a C compiler is a program that knows how to convert or compile"},{"start":1647.76,"end":1655.12,"text":"C code into machine code. However, this machine code is specific to the type of CPU of a computer."},{"start":1655.12,"end":1661.2,"text":"So if we compile a C program on a Windows machine, we can''t execute it on a Mac. Because Windows and"},{"start":1661.28,"end":1666.32,"text":"Mac have different machine code, just like how people from different countries speak different"},{"start":1666.32,"end":1673.12,"text":"languages. Java came to solve this problem. Java compiler doesn''t compile Java code into machine"},{"start":1673.12,"end":1680,"text":"code. Instead, it compiles it into a portable language called Java bytecode, which is not"},{"start":1680,"end":1686.8,"text":"specific to a hardware platform like Windows or Mac. Now, we still need to convert Java bytecode to"},{"start":1686.88,"end":1693.76,"text":"machine code. So Java also comes with a program called Java Virtual Machine or JVM for doing this."},{"start":1694.32,"end":1700.88,"text":"When we run a Java program, JVM kicks in, it loads our Java bytecode, and then at runtime,"},{"start":1700.88,"end":1707.04,"text":"it will convert each instruction to machine code. With this model, we can run Java bytecode on any"},{"start":1707.04,"end":1714.56,"text":"platforms that have a JVM. We have JVM implementations for Windows, Mac, and so on. So the JVM"},{"start":1714.56,"end":1721.36,"text":"implementation on Windows knows how to convert Java bytecode into machine code that a Windows machine"},{"start":1721.36,"end":1727.52,"text":"can understand. C-Sharp and Python have also taken the same route, so they are platform independent."},{"start":1728.08,"end":1733.92,"text":"When we run a Python program using C Python, first it will compile our Python code into Python"},{"start":1733.92,"end":1740.32,"text":"bytecode. Then it will pass that bytecode to Python Virtual Machine, which will in turn"},{"start":1740.32,"end":1744.56,"text":"convert it into machine code and execute it. This is how C Python works."},{"start":1745.28,"end":1749.76,"text":"In the last lecture, we talked about various Python implementations. I told you that if you"},{"start":1749.76,"end":1756.88,"text":"want to reuse some Java code in a Python program, you should use Jython. Now, let''s see how Jython"},{"start":1756.88,"end":1763.2,"text":"makes this possible. When you use Jython to run a Python program, instead of compiling your Python"},{"start":1763.2,"end":1770.08,"text":"code into Python bytecode, it will compile it to Java bytecode. So you can take this Java bytecode"},{"start":1770.08,"end":1775.04,"text":"and run it using Java Virtual Machine. And that''s why you can import some Java code"},{"start":1775.04,"end":1779.92,"text":"into a Python program when using Jython, because the end result is Java bytecode,"},{"start":1779.92,"end":1783.44,"text":"which will eventually be executed by Java Virtual Machine."},{"start":1789.12,"end":1792.72,"text":"So I''ve got a few questions for you, because I want to see if you''ve been really paying"},{"start":1792.72,"end":1798.72,"text":"attention to this video or not. You better have. So here''s the first question. For each question,"},{"start":1798.72,"end":1803.2,"text":"I want you to pause the video, think about the answer for a few seconds when you''re ready,"},{"start":1803.2,"end":1807.52,"text":"continue watching. So here''s the first question. What is an expression?"},{"start":1809.2,"end":1815.04,"text":"An expression is a piece of code that produces a value. Here''s an example of an expression."},{"start":1815.6,"end":1822.72,"text":"What do you think is the value of this expression? Well, here we have this string. We''re multiplying"},{"start":1822.72,"end":1831.2,"text":"this by three. So the result will be a string of three asterisks, like this. Here''s another question."},{"start":1831.2,"end":1838.16,"text":"What is a syntax error? A syntax error is a kind of error that is due to bad syntax or"},{"start":1838.16,"end":1843.6,"text":"bad grammar in the code. And finally, the last question. What does a linter do?"},{"start":1844.88,"end":1850.8,"text":"A linter is a tool that checks our code for potential errors, mostly in the category of"},{"start":1850.8,"end":1855.68,"text":"syntactical errors. So if you have grammatical issues in our code, the linter will tell us"},{"start":1855.68,"end":1861.28,"text":"before running our program. Okay, that''s it for now. If you like more quizzes and programming"},{"start":1861.28,"end":1867.2,"text":"exercises, look at the link below this video. And if you have enjoyed this video, I hope you have,"},{"start":1867.2,"end":1872.32,"text":"please support me by giving a thumbs up. Please like this video and share it with others."},{"start":1872.32,"end":1875.6,"text":"In the next section, we''re going to look at the fundamentals of Python."},{"start":1875.6,"end":1882.88,"text":"Hey, guys, I just wanted to let you know that this tutorial is actually the first two hours of my"},{"start":1882.88,"end":1888,"text":"complete Python mastery course. If you''re finding this helpful and want to dive even deeper, the"},{"start":1888,"end":1892.72,"text":"full course covers everything from beginner basics to advanced concepts like machine learning,"},{"start":1892.72,"end":1897.76,"text":"web development and automation. You also get hands-on projects to build your skills step by"},{"start":1897.76,"end":1902.4,"text":"step. I put the link in the description box if you''re ready to take your Python knowledge to the"},{"start":1902.4,"end":1911.36,"text":"next level. Now let''s continue. Let''s start this section by a discussion of variables,"},{"start":1911.36,"end":1917.44,"text":"which are one of the core concepts in programming. We use variables to store data in computer''s"},{"start":1917.44,"end":1923.84,"text":"memory. Here are a few examples. I''m going to define a variable called students underline count"},{"start":1923.84,"end":1930.32,"text":"and setting it to a thousand. When we run this program, Python interpreter will allocate some"},{"start":1930.32,"end":1937.92,"text":"memory and store this number thousand in that memory space. Then it will have this variable"},{"start":1937.92,"end":1944.56,"text":"reference that memory location. So this variable is just like a label for that memory location."},{"start":1944.56,"end":1950.56,"text":"We can use this variable or this label anywhere in our program to get access to that memory location"},{"start":1950.56,"end":1959.36,"text":"and the data stored there. So now if we print students count and run our program, we will get"},{"start":1960,"end":1966.4,"text":"the number thousand. So this is the basic of variables. Now what kind of data can we store"},{"start":1966.4,"end":1972,"text":"in computer''s memory? Well we have several different kinds of data. In this section we''re going to"},{"start":1972,"end":1979.44,"text":"look at the built-in primitive types in Python. Primitive types can be numbers, booleans and"},{"start":1979.44,"end":1986.4,"text":"strings. Let me show you. So here we have a whole number. We refer to this as an integer in programming."},{"start":1987.04,"end":1994.48,"text":"We can also have numbers with a decimal point. Let''s take a look. So rating we set this to 4.99."},{"start":1994.48,"end":2000.72,"text":"This is what we call a float or a floating point number. And this terminology is not specific to"},{"start":2000.72,"end":2005.36,"text":"Python. In the future when you learn a new programming language, you''re going to hear these"},{"start":2005.36,"end":2014.64,"text":"terms again. Now let''s take a look at an example of a boolean. Is published? We set this to true"},{"start":2014.64,"end":2022.56,"text":"or false. These are examples of boolean values in programming. So boolean values can either be true"},{"start":2022.56,"end":2028.8,"text":"or false and these are exactly like yes and no in English. Later in the course you will learn that"},{"start":2028.8,"end":2034.96,"text":"we''ll use these boolean values to make decisions in our programs. For example if the user is an"},{"start":2034.96,"end":2041.2,"text":"admin user, perhaps we want to give them extra permissions. So these are the boolean values."},{"start":2041.28,"end":2047.28,"text":"Now take into account that Python is a case sensitive language which means lowercase and"},{"start":2047.28,"end":2053.28,"text":"uppercase characters have different meanings. So boolean values should always start with a capital"},{"start":2053.28,"end":2060.32,"text":"letter like what you see here. If we type false or false, these are not accepted boolean values in"},{"start":2060.32,"end":2067.36,"text":"Python. Only what you see here is a valid boolean value. So false or true. And finally let''s take"},{"start":2067.36,"end":2074.72,"text":"a look at an example of a string. So of course underline name, we set this to a string like Python"},{"start":2075.28,"end":2081.12,"text":"programming. So a string as I told you before is like text. Whenever you want to work with text in"},{"start":2081.12,"end":2086.88,"text":"your programs, you need to surround your text with quotes. So these are the basics of variables."},{"start":2092.72,"end":2096.96,"text":"So these are the variables from the last lecture. Now I''ve got a question for you."},{"start":2097.04,"end":2101.92,"text":"There are four things that I''ve consistently used in this program. Can you spot them?"},{"start":2102.56,"end":2107.12,"text":"If you want you can pause the video, think about this for a few seconds and then continue watching."},{"start":2108.56,"end":2115.12,"text":"So here are those four things. The first thing is that all my variable names are descriptive and"},{"start":2115.12,"end":2121.44,"text":"meaningful. So students count represents the number of students for a course. Or course name"},{"start":2121.92,"end":2127.68,"text":"clearly explains that this variable holds the name of a course. One of the issues that I see a lot"},{"start":2127.68,"end":2133.6,"text":"amongst beginner programmers is that they use mystical names for their variables. Something"},{"start":2133.6,"end":2140.08,"text":"like this. CN as in short for course name. When someone else reads this code, they have no idea"},{"start":2140.08,"end":2146.88,"text":"what CN stands for. Or they use variable names like C1. When I look at that code, I wonder where is"},{"start":2146.88,"end":2152.64,"text":"C2? And what is the difference between C1 and C2? So these variable names are very mystical."},{"start":2153.2,"end":2158.96,"text":"That''s a bad practice. Make sure your variable names are always descriptive and meaningful"},{"start":2158.96,"end":2164.56,"text":"because this makes your code more maintainable. Now there are times that you can use short variable"},{"start":2164.56,"end":2171.84,"text":"names like X, Y, Z if you''re dealing with things like coordinates. So that''s an exception. Now"},{"start":2172.56,"end":2178.32,"text":"the second thing that I have consistently used in this code is that I have used lowercase letters"},{"start":2178.32,"end":2187.76,"text":"to name my variables. So here we don''t have course name all in capital or in title case. All letters"},{"start":2187.76,"end":2194.72,"text":"are lowercase. Right? Let''s delete this. The third thing that I''ve consistently used here"},{"start":2194.72,"end":2200.32,"text":"is that I have used an underscore to separate multiple words. And I''ve done this to make my"},{"start":2200.32,"end":2206.8,"text":"variable names more readable because in Python we cannot have a space in variable names. So we"},{"start":2206.8,"end":2212.24,"text":"cannot have course name. And if you put these two words together, it''s a little bit hard to read."},{"start":2212.24,"end":2218.16,"text":"That''s why we use an underscore. And the fourth thing that I have used consistently here is that"},{"start":2218.16,"end":2224.16,"text":"I have put a space around this equal sign. Again, that''s one of the issues I see a lot"},{"start":2224.16,"end":2231.84,"text":"amongst beginners. They write code like this. This is a little bit ugly. This is what we call"},{"start":2231.84,"end":2239.04,"text":"dirty code. Dirty, stinky, smelly. You should write code that is clean and beautiful. So other people"},{"start":2239.04,"end":2245.36,"text":"can read it like a story, like a newspaper article. It should be formatted properly. And that''s why"},{"start":2245.36,"end":2251.92,"text":"we have pep8 in Python. Now the good thing is if you forget these rules, when you save the changes,"},{"start":2251.92,"end":2257.76,"text":"auto pep8 kicks in and it automatically reformats your code. But that aside, you should always give"},{"start":2257.76,"end":2263.76,"text":"yourself the habit of writing clean code without relying too much on the tooling. So these are"},{"start":2263.76,"end":2269.52,"text":"all the best practices about naming your variables. Next, we''re going to look at strings in more detail."},{"start":2275.28,"end":2280.16,"text":"So here we have this course variable set to Python programming. As I told you before,"},{"start":2280.16,"end":2285.76,"text":"whenever you work with text, you should surround your text with quotes. You can either use double"},{"start":2285.76,"end":2291.68,"text":"quotes or single quotes. That''s more of a personal preference. But quite often we use double quotes."},{"start":2292.4,"end":2299.36,"text":"We also have triple quotes, and we use them to format a long string. For example, if you have,"},{"start":2299.36,"end":2305.52,"text":"let''s say, a variable message, that is the message we want to include in the body of an email,"},{"start":2305.84,"end":2314.96,"text":"you can use triple quotes to format it like this. Hi, John. This is Marsh from code with"},{"start":2314.96,"end":2322.32,"text":"marsh.com, blah, blah, blah. So that''s when we use triple quotes. Now we don''t need this in this lecture,"},{"start":2322.32,"end":2328.4,"text":"so delete. Let me show you a few useful things you can do with strings. First of all, we have"},{"start":2328.4,"end":2335.2,"text":"this built-in function in Python for getting the length of strings. What is a function?"},{"start":2336.16,"end":2342.32,"text":"A function is basically a reusable piece of code that carries out a task. As a metaphor,"},{"start":2342.32,"end":2347.6,"text":"think of the remote control of your TV. On this remote control, you have buttons for different"},{"start":2347.6,"end":2353.68,"text":"functions, like turn on, turn off, change the channel, and so on. These are the built-in functions"},{"start":2353.68,"end":2360.16,"text":"in your TV. In Python and many other programming languages, we have the exact same concept. So we"},{"start":2360.24,"end":2365.36,"text":"have functions that are built into the language on the platform. You can reuse these functions"},{"start":2365.36,"end":2372.16,"text":"to perform various tasks. So here we can use the built-in LEN function to get the length of a string,"},{"start":2372.16,"end":2377.52,"text":"which means the number of characters in that string. Now whenever you want to use a function,"},{"start":2377.52,"end":2383.84,"text":"you should use por-enthesis. Now we say we''re calling this function, which basically means"},{"start":2383.84,"end":2390.08,"text":"we''re using this function. Now some functions take additional data, which we refer to as"},{"start":2390.08,"end":2397.92,"text":"arguments. These arguments are inputs to these functions. So this LEN function takes an input"},{"start":2397.92,"end":2404.88,"text":"or an argument. Here we pass our course variable, and this will return the number of characters"},{"start":2404.88,"end":2412.48,"text":"in this string. So let''s print that and see what we get. Run the program. We get 18,"},{"start":2413.04,"end":2419.84,"text":"because we have 18 characters here. Let''s look at another example. If you want to get access to a"},{"start":2419.84,"end":2426.08,"text":"specific character in this string, you use the square bracket notation. So here we add course,"},{"start":2426.8,"end":2434.48,"text":"square brackets. To get the first character, you use the index 0. So in Python, like many other"},{"start":2434.48,"end":2441.92,"text":"languages, strings are 0 indexed, which means the index of the first character or the first element"},{"start":2441.92,"end":2453.44,"text":"is 0. So now when we print this, we''ll get p. Now you can also use a negative index,"},{"start":2454.16,"end":2463.2,"text":"like minus 1. What does that mean? Well, if 0 represents the first character here, what do you"},{"start":2463.2,"end":2470.32,"text":"think negative 1 represents? That takes us back to the end of the string. So that returns the first"},{"start":2470.32,"end":2477.6,"text":"character from the end of the string. Let''s run this program. You will see we''ll get g. There you"},{"start":2477.6,"end":2485.6,"text":"go. Using a similar syntax, you can slice strings. Let me show you. So I''m going to duplicate this"},{"start":2485.6,"end":2492.72,"text":"line and remove negative 1. Now let''s say we want to extract the first three characters in this"},{"start":2492.72,"end":2500.56,"text":"string. So here we need two indexes, the start index, colon, the end index. So this will return"},{"start":2500.56,"end":2507.52,"text":"a new string that contains the first three characters in this course variable. That will be"},{"start":2507.52,"end":2515.84,"text":"p, y, and t. So the index of these characters are 0, 1, and 2. So that means the character at the"},{"start":2515.92,"end":2522.72,"text":"end index is not included. Okay. Let''s run the program and make sure we get the right result."},{"start":2522.72,"end":2530.08,"text":"There you go. P, y, t. Now what if we don''t include the end index? What do you think we''re going to get?"},{"start":2530.96,"end":2537.36,"text":"It''s common sense. We start from index 0 and go all the way to the end of the string. So this"},{"start":2537.36,"end":2543.52,"text":"will return a new string that is exactly the same as the original string. Let''s take a look."},{"start":2543.92,"end":2552.56,"text":"So we get Python programming. Now what if we don''t include the start index but include the end index?"},{"start":2552.56,"end":2558.32,"text":"What do you think we''re going to get? Once again, it''s common sense. So by default, Python will put"},{"start":2558.32,"end":2564.48,"text":"0 here. So it will start from the beginning of the string. So when I run this program, we should get"},{"start":2564.48,"end":2572.64,"text":"p, y, t one more time. There you go. And finally, as the last example, if we don''t include the"},{"start":2573.52,"end":2581.92,"text":"start and the end index, this will return a copy of the original string. Let''s look at this. So we get"},{"start":2581.92,"end":2588.48,"text":"Python programming. Now you don''t have to memorize any of these. Just remember, we use the length"},{"start":2588.48,"end":2594.56,"text":"function to get the length of a string. We use bracket notation to get access to a specific element"},{"start":2594.56,"end":2599.36,"text":"or a specific character. And we use this notation to slice a string."},{"start":2605.12,"end":2611.44,"text":"So we have this string here, Python programming. Now let''s say we want to put a double code in"},{"start":2611.44,"end":2618.56,"text":"the middle of this string. There is a problem here. Python interpreter sees this second string"},{"start":2618.56,"end":2625.04,"text":"as the end of the string. So the rest of the code is meaningless and invalid. How do we solve this"},{"start":2625.04,"end":2634.08,"text":"problem? Well, there are two ways. One way is to use single codes for our string. And then we can use"},{"start":2634.08,"end":2639.84,"text":"a double code in the middle of the string. But what if for whatever reason, perhaps for being"},{"start":2639.84,"end":2647.12,"text":"consistent in our code, we decided to use double codes? How can we add another double code in the"},{"start":2647.12,"end":2655.44,"text":"middle of this string? Well, we can prefix this with a backslash. Backslash in Python strings is a"},{"start":2655.44,"end":2661.76,"text":"special character. We have a jargon for that called escape character. We use it to escape"},{"start":2662.32,"end":2670.48,"text":"the character after. Let me show you what I mean. So let''s print this course and run this program."},{"start":2670.96,"end":2676.96,"text":"What''s going on here? We don''t have the backslash because we use that to escape this double code"},{"start":2676.96,"end":2685.28,"text":"and basically displayed here. So backslash is an escape character and backslash double code is an"},{"start":2685.28,"end":2691.2,"text":"escape sequence. In Python strings, we have a few other escape sequences that you should be aware of."},{"start":2691.2,"end":2698.88,"text":"Let me show you. So in Python, we use a hash sign to indicate a comment. A comment is like"},{"start":2698.96,"end":2706,"text":"additional note that we add to our program. It''s not executed by Python interpreter. So here are"},{"start":2706,"end":2714.16,"text":"the escape sequences. You have seen backslash double code. We also have backslash single code. So"},{"start":2714.16,"end":2722.96,"text":"we can use that to add a single code here. Let''s run the program. Here it is. Beautiful. We also"},{"start":2723.2,"end":2730.4,"text":"have double backslash. So if you want to include a backslash in your strings, you should prefix it"},{"start":2730.4,"end":2737.36,"text":"with another backslash. Let me show you. So when we run this, we get Python one backslash programming."},{"start":2738.64,"end":2746.96,"text":"And finally, we have backslash n, which is short for new line. So now if I add a backslash n here,"},{"start":2747.28,"end":2755.52,"text":"see what we get. We get a new line after Python, so programming will end up on the second line."},{"start":2756.88,"end":2759.44,"text":"So these are the escape sequences in Python."},{"start":2765.28,"end":2771.36,"text":"Here we have two variables, first and last. Let''s say we want to print my full name on the console."},{"start":2772,"end":2780.16,"text":"So we can define another variable, full, set it to first, then concatenate it with a space,"},{"start":2780.96,"end":2790.08,"text":"and one more time concatenate it with last. Now when we print full, we get my full name on the"},{"start":2790.08,"end":2797.36,"text":"console. Beautiful. Now this approach, I''m using concatenation to build a string is okay, but there"},{"start":2797.36,"end":2803.6,"text":"is a better and newer approach. We can use formatted strings. So here we can set full"},{"start":2804.56,"end":2812.24,"text":"to this string and prefix it with an f, which can be lowercase or uppercase. This formatted string"},{"start":2812.24,"end":2819.12,"text":"doesn''t have a constant value like these two strings here. It''s actually an expression that will be"},{"start":2819.2,"end":2826.64,"text":"evaluated at runtime. So here we want to add our first name. We use curly braces to print"},{"start":2827.44,"end":2834.72,"text":"the value of the first variable. After that, we add a space, and then we add curly braces one more"},{"start":2834.72,"end":2842.72,"text":"time to print the last name. So at runtime, this expression will be evaluated. What we have in"},{"start":2842.8,"end":2849.52,"text":"between curly braces will be replaced at runtime. Now let''s run this program one more time."},{"start":2850.32,"end":2857.36,"text":"We get the exact same result. Just be aware that you can put any valid expressions in between"},{"start":2857.36,"end":2864.24,"text":"curly braces. So earlier you learned about the built in lend function. We can call lend here"},{"start":2864.24,"end":2870.24,"text":"to get the length of this string. Let''s run this program one more time. So we get four."},{"start":2870.48,"end":2877.28,"text":"We can also replace last with an expression like this two plus two. Let''s run this program. We get"},{"start":2877.28,"end":2885.76,"text":"four and four. So when using formatted strings, you can put any valid expressions in between curly braces."},{"start":2892.24,"end":2896.96,"text":"In this lecture, we''re going to look at a few useful functions available to work with strings."},{"start":2897.52,"end":2903.28,"text":"So earlier you learned about this built in lend function. This function is general purpose,"},{"start":2903.28,"end":2908.08,"text":"so it''s not limited to strings. Later, I will show you how to use this function with other"},{"start":2908.08,"end":2914.08,"text":"kind of objects. But in Python, we have quite a few functions that are specific to strings."},{"start":2914.08,"end":2924.56,"text":"Let me show you. So here if we type course dot, see, all these are functions available on strings."},{"start":2925.2,"end":2932.88,"text":"Now in precise terms, we refer to these functions as methods. This is a term in object-oriented"},{"start":2932.88,"end":2938.88,"text":"programming that you will learn about later in the course. For now, what I want you to take away"},{"start":2938.88,"end":2945.36,"text":"is that everything in Python is an object and objects have functions we call methods that we"},{"start":2945.36,"end":2952.48,"text":"can access using the dot notation. So here, of course, is an object. We use the dot notation"},{"start":2952.48,"end":2958.32,"text":"to access its functions or more accurately methods. Let''s take a look at a few of these methods."},{"start":2958.96,"end":2966.32,"text":"We have upper to convert a string to uppercase. Now let''s print this and run the program."},{"start":2967.12,"end":2973.76,"text":"Here is what we get. Beautiful. Now note that the methods that you call here return a new string,"},{"start":2973.76,"end":2981.04,"text":"so the original string is not affected. Let me show you. So print course, run the program one more"},{"start":2981.04,"end":2989.36,"text":"time. Look, this is our original string. So course dot upper returns a new string, a new value."},{"start":2989.36,"end":2998,"text":"We can store it in a variable like course underline capital like this. Now to keep this demo simple"},{"start":2998,"end":3006.64,"text":"and consistent, I''m going to revert this back and use a print statement. We also have the lower method"},{"start":3006.72,"end":3013.76,"text":"to convert a string to lowercase. We also have title, which will capitalize the first"},{"start":3013.76,"end":3021.28,"text":"letter of every word. So if our string was like this, when we call the title method,"},{"start":3022,"end":3029.84,"text":"we get Python programming as you see here. Okay. Another useful method is strip, and we use it to"},{"start":3029.84,"end":3036.08,"text":"trim any white space at the beginning or end of your string. This is particularly useful when we"},{"start":3036.08,"end":3043.68,"text":"receive input from the user. Let me show you. So let''s imagine the user entered a couple of white"},{"start":3043.68,"end":3051.12,"text":"spaces at the beginning of the string. When we call course dot strip, those white spaces will be"},{"start":3051.12,"end":3058.16,"text":"removed. Take a look. So note that in the first three examples, we have those white spaces,"},{"start":3058.16,"end":3063.84,"text":"but in the last one, it is removed. So strip removed the white space from both the beginning"},{"start":3063.84,"end":3070.48,"text":"and end of a string. We also have L strip, which is short for left strip and R strip,"},{"start":3070.48,"end":3075.12,"text":"which is short for right strip. So it will remove the white space from the end of a string."},{"start":3076.16,"end":3081.68,"text":"If you want to get the index of a character or a sequence of characters in your string,"},{"start":3081.68,"end":3091.12,"text":"you should use the find method. Let me show you. So course dot find. So as an argument here, we pass"},{"start":3091.12,"end":3098.88,"text":"another string, we can pass a character or a series of characters. Let''s find the index of pro."},{"start":3100.56,"end":3107.76,"text":"Round the program. So the index of pro is nine. So if we start from zero here, all the way to nine,"},{"start":3107.76,"end":3115.36,"text":"this is the index of pro. Okay. Now, as I told you before, Python is a case sensitive language."},{"start":3115.36,"end":3122.96,"text":"So if I pass a capital P here, obviously, we don''t have these exact characters in our string."},{"start":3122.96,"end":3130,"text":"So let''s see what we get. We get negative one. That means this string was not found in the original"},{"start":3130,"end":3139.52,"text":"string. Another useful method is replace. So we call replace. With this, we can replace a character"},{"start":3139.52,"end":3146.08,"text":"or a sequence of characters with something else. So let''s say we want to replace all lowercase p''s"},{"start":3146.08,"end":3155.84,"text":"with j. With this, we get gython, gyrrogramming, whatever that means. And finally, if you want to"},{"start":3155.84,"end":3162.4,"text":"check for the existence of a character or a sequence of characters in your string, you can use the"},{"start":3162.4,"end":3172.96,"text":"in operator. Let me show you. So print, rewrite an expression like this. Pro in course. So this is"},{"start":3172.96,"end":3179.28,"text":"an expression, as I told you before, an expression is a piece of code that produces a value. So this"},{"start":3179.28,"end":3185.76,"text":"expression checks to see if you have pro in course. The difference between this expression"},{"start":3185.76,"end":3192.48,"text":"and calling the find method is that the find method returns the index of these characters"},{"start":3192.48,"end":3198.8,"text":"in our string. Whereas this expression returns a boolean. So it''s a true or false. Let me show you."},{"start":3198.8,"end":3208.32,"text":"So run the program. We get the boolean true. And finally, we have the not operator. And we use that"},{"start":3208.32,"end":3214.32,"text":"to see if our string does not contain a character or sequence of characters. So"},{"start":3216.4,"end":3225.68,"text":"let''s change this to swift, not in course. When this expression is evaluated, what do you think"},{"start":3225.68,"end":3234.16,"text":"we''re going to get? Well, we don''t have swift in this string. So not in will return true. Let''s"},{"start":3234.16,"end":3242,"text":"take a look. There you go. So these are the useful string methods. Next, we''ll look at numbers."},{"start":3248.08,"end":3253.68,"text":"In Python, we have three types of numbers. Two of these you have already seen before. They are"},{"start":3253.68,"end":3263.2,"text":"integers and floats. We also have complex numbers. So complex numbers in math are in the form a plus"},{"start":3263.28,"end":3269.6,"text":"b i, where i is the imaginary number. If you''re not familiar with this concept, don''t worry."},{"start":3269.6,"end":3275.12,"text":"This is something that is used a lot in mathematics and electrical engineering. If you want to use"},{"start":3275.12,"end":3280.32,"text":"Python to build web applications, you''re never going to use complex numbers. But let me quickly"},{"start":3280.32,"end":3288.4,"text":"show you the syntax for representing complex numbers. Instead of i, we use j. So here is an example."},{"start":3288.4,"end":3296,"text":"One plus two j. So x now is a complex number. And by the way, as I told you before, this is just a"},{"start":3296,"end":3301.68,"text":"comment or an additional note in our program. When we run this program, anything after this"},{"start":3301.68,"end":3307.92,"text":"hash sign will be ignored. So these are the three types of numbers we have in Python. For all these"},{"start":3307.92,"end":3314.88,"text":"types of numbers, we have the standard arithmetic operations that we have in math. Let me show you."},{"start":3314.88,"end":3325.12,"text":"So we have addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, but we actually have two different"},{"start":3325.12,"end":3331.92,"text":"types of divisions. Let me show you. First, let''s run this program. So with this division operator,"},{"start":3331.92,"end":3339.68,"text":"which is a slash, we get a floating point number. If you want an integer, you use double slashes."},{"start":3339.76,"end":3351.36,"text":"Let me show you. So double slash, run the program, we get three. Okay. We also have modulus, which is"},{"start":3351.36,"end":3359.36,"text":"the remainder of a division. And finally, exponent, which is left to the power of right. So 10 to the"},{"start":3359.36,"end":3367.04,"text":"power of three will be 1000. These are the standard arithmetic operators. Now for all these operators,"},{"start":3367.04,"end":3373.76,"text":"we have a special operator called augmented assignment operator. Let me show you. So let''s"},{"start":3373.76,"end":3382.64,"text":"imagine we have x set to 10. We want to increment x by, let''s say, three. We can write an expression"},{"start":3382.64,"end":3390.32,"text":"like this, x equals x plus three. Or we can use an augmented assignment operator. That is a little"},{"start":3390.32,"end":3399.36,"text":"bit shorter. So we write x plus equal three. These two statements are exactly the same. Now here I''m"},{"start":3399.36,"end":3406.48,"text":"using addition as an example. You can use any of these operators here. Next, I''m going to show you"},{"start":3406.48,"end":3416.24,"text":"some useful functions to work with numbers. In this lecture, we''re going to look at a few"},{"start":3416.24,"end":3424.16,"text":"useful functions to work with numbers. So we have this built in function round for rounding a number."},{"start":3424.16,"end":3433.04,"text":"So if we pass 2.9 here and print the result, we will get three. We have another useful built in"},{"start":3433.04,"end":3440.32,"text":"function called abs, which returns the absolute value of a number. So if we pass negative 2.9 here,"},{"start":3440.88,"end":3449.04,"text":"we''ll get positive 2.9. Now technically, we have only a handful of built in functions"},{"start":3449.04,"end":3454.88,"text":"to work with numbers. If you want to write a program that involves complex mathematical"},{"start":3454.88,"end":3461.6,"text":"calculations, you need to use the math module. A module is like a separate file with some Python"},{"start":3461.6,"end":3467.52,"text":"code. So in Python, we have this math module, which includes lots of mathematical functions"},{"start":3467.52,"end":3474.8,"text":"for working with numbers. But we need to import this module so we can use it. On the top, we type"},{"start":3474.8,"end":3484.88,"text":"import math. Now math in this program is an object, so we can use the dot notation to see all the"},{"start":3484.88,"end":3491.84,"text":"functions or more accurately all the methods available in this object. As an example, we have"},{"start":3492.56,"end":3500.88,"text":"math.seal for getting the ceiling of a number. So if we pass 2.2 here and run this program,"},{"start":3502,"end":3508.8,"text":"we get three. Now in this math module, we have lots of functions. Let me show you how to find the"},{"start":3508.8,"end":3518.56,"text":"complete list. Here on Google, search for Python 3. Make sure to add the version number math module."},{"start":3519.2,"end":3527.28,"text":"On this page, you can see all the functions in the math module. So in this lecture, we looked at"},{"start":3527.28,"end":3535.68,"text":"math.seal. We also have math.copySign, fabs, and so on. As an exercise, I encourage you to play with"},{"start":3535.68,"end":3546.4,"text":"a couple of functions in this module. All right, now let''s take a look at another useful built-in"},{"start":3546.4,"end":3554.16,"text":"function in Python. We use the input function to get input from the user. As an argument, we pass"},{"start":3554.16,"end":3559.6,"text":"a string. This will be a label that will be displayed in the terminal. You will see that in a second."},{"start":3560.32,"end":3568.64,"text":"So let''s add x colon. Now this function returns a string, so we can store it in this variable."},{"start":3569.36,"end":3578.08,"text":"Now let''s imagine that y should be x plus 1. Save the changes. Now don''t run this program using the"},{"start":3578.08,"end":3584.24,"text":"CodeRunner extension, because CodeRunner by default runs your program in the output window, which is"},{"start":3584.24,"end":3591.76,"text":"read only. So you won''t be able to enter a value. So open up the terminal using control and backspace."},{"start":3592.56,"end":3598.56,"text":"Once again, if you''re on Windows, type Python. If you''re on Mac or Linux, type Python 3. And then"},{"start":3598.64,"end":3608.16,"text":"app.py. So here''s our label. Let''s enter a value like 1. We got an error. Type error. What is going on here?"},{"start":3609.12,"end":3617.04,"text":"Well, when we receive input from the user, this input always comes as a string. So this expression"},{"start":3617.04,"end":3625.84,"text":"at runtime will look like this. String 1 plus 1. Note that the number 1 is different from string 1,"},{"start":3625.84,"end":3631.28,"text":"because these are two different types. Now when Python sees this expression, it doesn''t know what to"},{"start":3631.28,"end":3638.16,"text":"do, because two objects can be concatenated if they are of the same type. So here we need to convert"},{"start":3638.16,"end":3644.56,"text":"this string 1 to a number. In Python, we have a few built-in functions for type conversion."},{"start":3645.28,"end":3655.52,"text":"We have int for converting a number to an integer. We have float. We have bool, and stir or string."},{"start":3656.32,"end":3661.68,"text":"Now in this case, we don''t need to convert x to a string, because x is already a string. If you don''t"},{"start":3661.68,"end":3669.28,"text":"believe me, let me show you. So I''m going to comment out these few lines. Now let''s print"},{"start":3670.88,"end":3678.64,"text":"type of x. So type is another built-in function. We pass an object as an argument, and it returns"},{"start":3678.64,"end":3684.24,"text":"its type. Also, I''m going to comment out this line, because that''s the bad boy. We don''t want to execute"},{"start":3684.24,"end":3691.6,"text":"this. Save the changes. Back into terminal. Let''s run this program one more time. Enter 1. Look,"},{"start":3692.4,"end":3697.68,"text":"this is what the type function returns. Now don''t worry about the class. We''ll talk about classes"},{"start":3697.68,"end":3707.12,"text":"later in the course. So the type of x is a stir or string. So let''s delete this line. To fix this"},{"start":3707.12,"end":3715.6,"text":"problem, we need to convert x to an integer. And then we can print both x and y using a format of"},{"start":3715.6,"end":3723.84,"text":"the string. Remember, so we add an f, quotes. Now here we add a label like x, then we''ll add a filled."},{"start":3724.56,"end":3730.16,"text":"So here we want to print the value of x variable. After that, we add some more text."},{"start":3731.12,"end":3736.88,"text":"And finally, we want to print the value of y. Let''s run this program one more time."},{"start":3738.4,"end":3746.08,"text":"So here in the terminal, let''s enter 1. And here''s the result. x is 1 and y is 2. Beautiful."},{"start":3746.96,"end":3753.12,"text":"Now all these built-in functions are self-explanatory. The only tricky one is bull. Because in Python,"},{"start":3753.12,"end":3760,"text":"we have this concept of truthy and falsy values. These are values that are not exactly a Boolean"},{"start":3760,"end":3767.68,"text":"true or false, but they can be interpreted as a Boolean true or false. So here are the falsy"},{"start":3767.68,"end":3774.48,"text":"values in Python. Empty strings are considered falsy, so they''re interpreted as a Boolean false."},{"start":3775.36,"end":3782.24,"text":"Number zero is also falsy. We have an object called non, which represents the absence of a value."},{"start":3782.24,"end":3789.12,"text":"We''ll look at this later in the course. So whenever we use these values in a Boolean context,"},{"start":3789.12,"end":3794.16,"text":"we''ll get false. Anything else will be true. Let me show you a few examples."},{"start":3795.44,"end":3802.64,"text":"So in this interactive shell in Python, let''s convert number zero to bool. That''s falsy,"},{"start":3802.64,"end":3810.72,"text":"so we get false. What about bool of 1? We get true. If we pass a negative number, we''ll also get"},{"start":3810.72,"end":3818.4,"text":"true. If we pass a number larger than 1, like 5, we still get true. So we only get false when we"},{"start":3818.4,"end":3825.68,"text":"try to convert zero to a Boolean. Now with strings, I told you that an empty string is falsy, so here"},{"start":3825.68,"end":3835.28,"text":"we''ll get false. Anything else is true. So even if I have a string that is false, we''ll get true,"},{"start":3835.28,"end":3841.04,"text":"because this is not an empty string, it''s a string with a few characters. That''s why it''s evaluated"},{"start":3841.04,"end":3850.56,"text":"as true. Alright, once again, it''s time for another quiz. Let''s see if you have been really paying"},{"start":3850.56,"end":3856.32,"text":"attention to this tutorial. So here''s the first question. What are the built-in primitive types"},{"start":3856.32,"end":3869.6,"text":"in Python? We have strings, numbers, and booleans. Numbers can be integers, floats, or complex numbers."},{"start":3870.48,"end":3876.24,"text":"Here''s the second question. You have this variable fruit set to apple. What do you think we will see"},{"start":3876.24,"end":3887.76,"text":"on the terminal when we print fruit of 1? Well, using screw brackets, we can access individual"},{"start":3887.76,"end":3893.44,"text":"characters. The index of the first character is zero, so this expression returns the second"},{"start":3893.44,"end":3899.2,"text":"character, which is p. What if we add a colon and negative one here?"},{"start":3904.32,"end":3910.48,"text":"Well, using the syntax, we can slice a string. Our stored index is one, and our end index is"},{"start":3910.48,"end":3916.32,"text":"negative one, which refers to the first character from the end of the string. Now, when slicing a"},{"start":3916.32,"end":3923.2,"text":"string, the character at the end index or negative one is not included. So with this expression, we''ll"},{"start":3923.2,"end":3929.92,"text":"get all the characters starting from the second character, which is p, all the way until we get"},{"start":3929.92,"end":3937.92,"text":"to e. So the result of this expression is ppl. Here''s another question. What is the result of this"},{"start":3937.92,"end":3949.44,"text":"expression? Well, this is what we call the modulus operator, and it returns the remainder of a division,"},{"start":3949.44,"end":3956.16,"text":"which is in this case, one. And finally, the last question. What do you think we will see when we print"},{"start":3956.8,"end":3968.72,"text":"bool of false? Well, earlier I told you about false values in Python. So number zero, an empty"},{"start":3968.72,"end":3974.88,"text":"string, and the non-object, these are all false values. Anything that is not false is considered"},{"start":3974.88,"end":3980.16,"text":"truecy. Here we have a string that has five characters. It doesn''t matter what those characters"},{"start":3980.16,"end":3987.28,"text":"are. This is not an empty string. So it''s not falsey. It''s truecy. So when we convert it using the"},{"start":3987.28,"end":3993.28,"text":"bool function, we''ll get the boolean true. And this brings us to the end of this section. In the next"},{"start":3993.28,"end":3997.84,"text":"section, you''re going to learn the fundamentals of computer programming. I hope you have enjoyed"},{"start":3997.84,"end":4010.08,"text":"this section, and thank you for watching. We''re going to start this section by exploring comparison"},{"start":4010.08,"end":4017.2,"text":"operators. We use comparison operators to compare values. Here are a few examples. So 10 is greater"},{"start":4017.2,"end":4024.4,"text":"than 3. We get true. So what we have here is a boolean expression. Because when this expression is"},{"start":4024.4,"end":4031.92,"text":"evaluated, we''ll get a boolean value that is true or false. Here''s another example. 10 is greater than"},{"start":4031.92,"end":4040.48,"text":"or equal to 3. Once again, we get true. We also have less than. So 10 is less than 20. We have less"},{"start":4040.48,"end":4049.68,"text":"than or equal to. Here is the equality operator. So 10 is equal to 10. What about this expression?"},{"start":4049.76,"end":4055.12,"text":"What do you think we''re going to get? We get false. Because these values have different types,"},{"start":4055.12,"end":4062.24,"text":"and they''re stored differently in the computer''s memory. And finally, we have the not equal operator."},{"start":4062.96,"end":4068.88,"text":"So now with this expression, we should get true. Beautiful. We can also use these comparison"},{"start":4068.88,"end":4076.32,"text":"operators with strings. Let me show you. So we can check to see if bag is greater than apple."},{"start":4077.04,"end":4083.12,"text":"We get true. Because when we sort these two words, bag comes after. So it''s considered greater."},{"start":4083.76,"end":4090.72,"text":"Now what about this one? Bag equals capital bag. We get false. Here is the reason."},{"start":4091.28,"end":4096.64,"text":"Every character you see here has a numeric representation in programming. Let me show you."},{"start":4096.64,"end":4101.12,"text":"So we have this built-in function called ord. Don''t worry about memorizing this,"},{"start":4101.12,"end":4106,"text":"because you''re probably never going to use this in the future. But let me show you the numeric"},{"start":4106,"end":4115.12,"text":"representation of the letter b. So that is 98. In contrast, capital b is represented as 66."},{"start":4115.76,"end":4121.92,"text":"That is the reason these two strings are not equal. So these are the comparison operators"},{"start":4121.92,"end":4132.72,"text":"in Python. Next, we''ll look at conditional statements. In almost every program, there are"},{"start":4132.72,"end":4138.24,"text":"times you need to make decisions. And that''s when you use an if statement. Here''s an example."},{"start":4138.8,"end":4145.68,"text":"Let''s say we have a variable called temperature. We set it to 35. Now if temperature is greater"},{"start":4145.68,"end":4151.76,"text":"than 30, perhaps we want to display a message to the user. So we use an if statement. If,"},{"start":4152.56,"end":4158.56,"text":"after if, we add a condition, which is basically a Boolean expression, an expression that produces"},{"start":4158.56,"end":4165.12,"text":"a Boolean value. So if temperature is greater than 30, here we have a Boolean expression."},{"start":4165.68,"end":4171.36,"text":"If this expression evaluates to true, the following statements will be executed. Let me show you."},{"start":4172.08,"end":4177.6,"text":"Now here''s the important part that a lot of beginners miss. When you use an if statement,"},{"start":4177.6,"end":4183.76,"text":"you should always terminate your statement with a colon. Now let''s see what happens when I press"},{"start":4183.76,"end":4191.28,"text":"enter. Our cursor is indented. So here we have two white spaces. This is very important because"},{"start":4191.28,"end":4197.36,"text":"using these indentations, Python interpreter will know what statements should be executed"},{"start":4197.36,"end":4204.48,"text":"if this condition is true. Here we want to print a message like it''s warm. We can print"},{"start":4205.2,"end":4212.16,"text":"another message as well. Drink water. So we can have as many statements as we want here. As long"},{"start":4212.16,"end":4219.04,"text":"as they are indented, they belong to this if block. Now when we finish here, we should remove"},{"start":4219.04,"end":4225.84,"text":"indentation to indicate the end of this if block. So here we can add a print statement with a message"},{"start":4225.84,"end":4233.52,"text":"like done. This statement will always be executed whether this condition is true or not. Now note"},{"start":4233.52,"end":4239.76,"text":"that when I save the changes, this indentation you see here is going to be doubled up. Take a look."},{"start":4239.76,"end":4247.28,"text":"Save. There you go. So when we save the changes, auto pep 8 reformats our code and uses four white"},{"start":4247.28,"end":4254.4,"text":"spaces for indentation. So one, two, three, four. It uses four white spaces because that''s what pep 8"},{"start":4254.4,"end":4262.08,"text":"recommends. All right, now let''s run this program. So because temperature is greater than 30, we see"},{"start":4262.08,"end":4268.8,"text":"the first two messages and we see the done message regardless. So if I change the temperature to"},{"start":4268.88,"end":4276.72,"text":"let''s say 15 and run the program one more time, look, this done message is executed whether our"},{"start":4276.72,"end":4282.56,"text":"condition is true or not. So pay great attention to these indentations. That''s one of the issues I"},{"start":4282.56,"end":4287.92,"text":"see in beginners code. Let''s say they want both these print statements to be executed if the"},{"start":4287.92,"end":4294.56,"text":"condition is true. Accidentally, they remove the indentation on the fourth line. And that''s why their"},{"start":4294.56,"end":4301.2,"text":"program doesn''t work as they expect. So be careful about this. Now what if we want to have multiple"},{"start":4301.2,"end":4310,"text":"conditions? We use an L if statement. So L if that is short for L''s if. Here we can add another"},{"start":4310,"end":4318.24,"text":"condition, another expression. So temperature is greater than 20. Once again, colon, enter. Now by"},{"start":4318.24,"end":4323.76,"text":"default here, VS code is using two white spaces. So don''t worry about this. As soon as you save the"},{"start":4323.76,"end":4330,"text":"changes, those two white spaces will be converted to four white spaces. So let''s print a different"},{"start":4330,"end":4340.16,"text":"message. It''s nice. Save the changes. Now look, all these lines are indented consistently. You can"},{"start":4340.16,"end":4347.28,"text":"have as many L if statements as you want. And optionally, you can also have an L statement. So if"},{"start":4347.28,"end":4353.12,"text":"none of the previous conditions are true, then what you have in the L''s block will be executed."},{"start":4353.68,"end":4360.88,"text":"Once again, we add the colon, indentation, print. Here we can add a message like it''s called."},{"start":4362.24,"end":4369.6,"text":"Save the changes. In this case, temperature is 15. So none of these two conditions will be true."},{"start":4369.6,"end":4374,"text":"And we will see it''s called. Let''s run the program. There you go."},{"start":4374,"end":4384.96,"text":"In this lecture, I''m going to show you a technique for writing cleaner code. So let''s say we''re"},{"start":4384.96,"end":4391.12,"text":"building an application for university. And we want to check to see if the person who''s applying"},{"start":4391.12,"end":4397.68,"text":"for this university program is eligible or not. So we start by defining a variable called age,"},{"start":4398.16,"end":4407.44,"text":"set it to 22. Now, if age is greater than or equal to 18, colon, print eligible,"},{"start":4409.52,"end":4418.56,"text":"remove the indentation, else colon, print, not eligible. Let''s run the program. Make sure it"},{"start":4418.56,"end":4424.4,"text":"works. Beautiful. Now, there is nothing wrong in this piece of code, but I want to show you a"},{"start":4424.48,"end":4430.96,"text":"cleaner way to achieve the same result. Instead of having a print statement here, we can define a"},{"start":4430.96,"end":4440.32,"text":"variable like message and set it to this string. That is the first step. So message equals this"},{"start":4440.32,"end":4448.56,"text":"string. And then we will print this message. Now, when you have an if-else statement with this"},{"start":4448.56,"end":4454.4,"text":"structure, where you''re basically assigning a value to a variable, you can rewrite this in a"},{"start":4454.4,"end":4462.48,"text":"simpler way. So this is how it works. All we want to do over these few lines is to assign a value"},{"start":4462.48,"end":4471.28,"text":"to this message variable, right? So we start with message. We set it to eligible. If age is greater"},{"start":4471.28,"end":4479.68,"text":"than or equal to 18, else we set it to not eligible. This statement is almost like plain English."},{"start":4480.32,"end":4487.28,"text":"So what we have on line seven is exactly equivalent to these four lines of code. Delete,"},{"start":4488.08,"end":4494.56,"text":"save the changes, run the program. You can see this person is eligible. If I change the age"},{"start":4494.56,"end":4503.04,"text":"to 12 and run the program, we get not eligible. So what we have here is called ternary operator."},{"start":4508.8,"end":4515.44,"text":"In Python, we have three logical operators and we use these operators to model more complex"},{"start":4515.44,"end":4524.08,"text":"conditions. So these operators are and, or, and not. Let''s see a real-world example of using this"},{"start":4524.08,"end":4530.32,"text":"operators. So imagine we''re building an application for processing loans. So we need two variables,"},{"start":4531.12,"end":4540.8,"text":"high income, we can set this to true, and good underlying credit, we set it to true. Now here''s"},{"start":4540.8,"end":4547.6,"text":"the condition we want to implement. If the applicant has high income and good credit square,"},{"start":4547.6,"end":4557.76,"text":"then they are eligible for the loan. So if high income and good credit, we add the colon and print"},{"start":4558.4,"end":4565.84,"text":"eligible. Now note that here I have not compared the value of this variable with true. That is one"},{"start":4565.84,"end":4571.44,"text":"of the issues I see in a lot of beginners code. This is redundant and unprofessional because"},{"start":4571.44,"end":4577.6,"text":"high income is a boolean, so it''s either true or false. We don''t need to compare true with true."},{"start":4578.64,"end":4585.76,"text":"So if this condition is true and this second condition is true, then we will print eligible"},{"start":4585.76,"end":4592.64,"text":"in the terminal. So save the changes and run the program. Obviously this person is eligible."},{"start":4593.2,"end":4600.72,"text":"However, if one of these conditions is false, we will not see eligible in the terminal. So let''s add"},{"start":4601.52,"end":4612.64,"text":"an L statement here and print not eligible. Run the program. We see not eligible. So this is how the"},{"start":4612.64,"end":4619.04,"text":"AND operator works. With AND operator, if both conditions are true, the result will be true."},{"start":4619.68,"end":4625.76,"text":"In contrast with the OR operator, as long as at least one of the conditions is true, the result"},{"start":4625.76,"end":4634.4,"text":"will be true. So if I replace AND with OR here, we should see eligible in the terminal. Let''s run"},{"start":4634.4,"end":4640.48,"text":"it one more time. There you go. So these are the AND and OR operators. Now let''s take a look at an"},{"start":4640.48,"end":4647.2,"text":"example of the NOT operator. So I''m going to define another variable, student, set it to true."},{"start":4647.92,"end":4652.64,"text":"Temporarily, I''m going to remove this expression and simplify it. We''ll come back to this later."},{"start":4653.2,"end":4660.4,"text":"So let''s say if the person is eligible, if they are not a student, the NOT operator basically"},{"start":4660.4,"end":4667.36,"text":"inverses the value of a boolean. So in this case, student is true. When we apply the NOT operator,"},{"start":4667.36,"end":4672.8,"text":"the result will be false. So in this case, our condition will be false. And that''s why"},{"start":4673.36,"end":4680.32,"text":"this print statement will not be executed. Let me show you. So save, run the program, they are not"},{"start":4680.32,"end":4687.92,"text":"eligible. If student was false, when we apply the NOT operator, we''ll get true. So our condition"},{"start":4687.92,"end":4694.56,"text":"will be true and we''ll see eligible. Let''s run it one more time. There you go. With these operators,"},{"start":4694.56,"end":4700.56,"text":"we can model even more complex conditions. Here is an example. A person can be eligible"},{"start":4701.28,"end":4709.12,"text":"if they have either high income or good credit and they should not be a student. Let me show you"},{"start":4709.12,"end":4718.08,"text":"how to implement this condition. So if high income or good credit, we want at least one of these"},{"start":4718.08,"end":4725.04,"text":"conditions to be true. So we put these in parentheses. We want to separate these from the"},{"start":4725.04,"end":4731.68,"text":"other condition, which is NOT a student. Now the result of this should be true, which means at least"},{"start":4731.68,"end":4740.32,"text":"one of these conditions should be true. After that, we''ll add AND NOT student. And finally, call."},{"start":4741.36,"end":4745.36,"text":"So with these operators, we can model all kinds of real-world scenarios."},{"start":4751.12,"end":4756.88,"text":"So here is the example from the last lecture. A person is eligible for a loan if they have high"},{"start":4756.88,"end":4764.24,"text":"income and good credit and they are not a student. Now one thing you need to know about these Boolean"},{"start":4764.24,"end":4771.28,"text":"operators is that they are short-circuited. What do I mean by that? Well, when Python interpreter"},{"start":4771.28,"end":4777.44,"text":"wants to evaluate this expression, it starts from the first argument. If this is true,"},{"start":4777.44,"end":4782.88,"text":"it continues the evaluation to see if the second argument is also true. So it continues the"},{"start":4782.88,"end":4790.24,"text":"evaluation all the way to the end of this expression. However, as soon as one of these arguments is"},{"start":4790.24,"end":4796.56,"text":"false, the evaluation stops. Let me show you what I mean. So if I change high income to false,"},{"start":4797.12,"end":4803.92,"text":"when Python interpreter sees this expression, it starts here. It knows that high income is"},{"start":4803.92,"end":4810.96,"text":"false. So it doesn''t matter what comes after the result of this entire expression will always be"},{"start":4810.96,"end":4817.6,"text":"false because at least one of the arguments or one of the operands is false. This is what we call"},{"start":4817.6,"end":4823.6,"text":"short-circuiting, just like the short-circuit concept we have in electronics. So the evaluation"},{"start":4823.6,"end":4831.52,"text":"stops as soon as one of these arguments evaluates to false. We have the same concept with the OR"},{"start":4831.52,"end":4839.76,"text":"operator. So if I change these AND operators to OR, let''s see what happens. With the OR operator,"},{"start":4839.76,"end":4845.84,"text":"we know that at least one of the arguments should be true. So the evaluation stops as soon as we find"},{"start":4845.84,"end":4851.6,"text":"an argument that evaluates to true. In this case, when Python interpreter evaluates this expression,"},{"start":4852.24,"end":4858.24,"text":"it sees that high income is false. So it continues the evaluation, hoping that the next argument"},{"start":4858.24,"end":4865.44,"text":"will be true. Here, good credit is true. So evaluation stops and the result of this entire"},{"start":4865.44,"end":4871.76,"text":"expression will be true. So in Python, logical operators are short-circuited."},{"start":4877.52,"end":4882.64,"text":"In this lecture, I''m going to show you how to chain comparison operators. This is a very powerful"},{"start":4882.64,"end":4888,"text":"technique for writing clean code. Here''s an example. Let''s say we want to implement a rule"},{"start":4888,"end":4896.48,"text":"that says age should be between 18 and 65. Here''s how we can implement it. So we define a variable"},{"start":4896.48,"end":4906.08,"text":"like age, set it to 22. Now, if age is greater than or equal to 18, and age is less than 65,"},{"start":4906.08,"end":4912.64,"text":"then we print eligible. Now, here''s a question for you. How do we write this rule in math?"},{"start":4913.28,"end":4914.48,"text":"We can write it like this."},{"start":4917.36,"end":4924.96,"text":"Well, more accurately, we should have an equal sign here. So age should be between 18 and 65."},{"start":4924.96,"end":4930.64,"text":"This is how we write this rule in math. Now, I''ve got some good news for you. We can write the exact"},{"start":4930.64,"end":4940.08,"text":"same expression in Python. So I''m going to move this up, put an if statement here. Line 4 and line"},{"start":4940.08,"end":4947.36,"text":"3 are exactly equivalent. But as you can see, line 4 is cleaner and easier to read. So let''s get rid"},{"start":4947.36,"end":4961.28,"text":"of line 3. This is what we call chaining comparison operators. All right, here''s a little quiz for"},{"start":4961.28,"end":4967.6,"text":"you. I want you to pause the video and think about this quiz for 10 to 20 seconds. What do you think"},{"start":4967.6,"end":4973.6,"text":"we''ll see on the terminal when we run this program? So pause the video, figure out the answer when you''re"},{"start":4973.6,"end":4981.28,"text":"ready, come back, continue watching. All right, let''s see what happens when we run this program."},{"start":4982.08,"end":4987.6,"text":"First, we get this if statement. In this case, we''re comparing two different objects for equality,"},{"start":4987.6,"end":4993.84,"text":"and these objects have different types. We have a number compared with a string. So number 10 and"},{"start":4993.92,"end":5000.4,"text":"string 10 are not equal. That is why A will not be printed on the terminal. So the control moves"},{"start":5000.96,"end":5007.92,"text":"to the L if part. Here we have two Boolean expressions. Here''s the first one. Here''s the second one."},{"start":5008.64,"end":5014.96,"text":"And they are combined using the logical and. So if both these expressions are evaluated to true,"},{"start":5015.52,"end":5021.84,"text":"then this entire expression will be true and we will see B on the terminal. Let''s see if both these"},{"start":5021.84,"end":5029.04,"text":"expressions are evaluated to true. Here''s the first part. Bag is greater than Apple. That is true"},{"start":5029.04,"end":5036.08,"text":"because when we sort these words, bag comes after Apple. But look at the second part. This expression"},{"start":5036.08,"end":5043.04,"text":"is evaluated to false because bag is not greater than cat. So when we apply the logical and between"},{"start":5043.04,"end":5050.08,"text":"true and false, the result will be false. That is why this statement will not be executed. So"},{"start":5050.16,"end":5056.72,"text":"the control moves to the else part. And when we run this program, the letter C will be printed on the terminal."},{"start":5062.64,"end":5067.44,"text":"There are times that we may want to repeat a task a number of times. For example,"},{"start":5067.44,"end":5072.32,"text":"let''s say we send a message to a user. If that message cannot be delivered,"},{"start":5072.32,"end":5078.32,"text":"perhaps we want to retry three times. Now for simplicity, let''s imagine this print statement"},{"start":5078.32,"end":5084.8,"text":"is equivalent to sending a message in a real world program to send the message to a user."},{"start":5084.8,"end":5089.44,"text":"We have to write five to 10 lines of code. Now if you want to retry three times,"},{"start":5089.44,"end":5095.2,"text":"we don''t want to repeat all that code. That is ugly. That''s when we use a loop. We use loops to"},{"start":5095.2,"end":5103.76,"text":"create repetition. So here''s how it works. We start with four, number in, we have a built-in"},{"start":5103.76,"end":5109.44,"text":"function called range. Now how many times we want to repeat this task? Let''s say three times."},{"start":5110.08,"end":5116.64,"text":"So we call range and pass three as an argument. Now similar to our if statements, we need to"},{"start":5116.64,"end":5124.08,"text":"terminate this line with a colon, enter, we get indentation. So in this block, we can write all"},{"start":5124.08,"end":5131.28,"text":"the statements that should be repeated three times. Let''s do a print a message like attempt. Save the"},{"start":5131.28,"end":5138.16,"text":"changes, run the program. So we have attempt, print it three times, beautiful. Now what is this"},{"start":5138.16,"end":5146.48,"text":"number? Let''s take a look. It''s a variable of type integer. So let''s pass it as the second argument"},{"start":5146.48,"end":5154.96,"text":"to the print function, number, run the program. This is what we get, zero, one, two. So here we"},{"start":5154.96,"end":5161.92,"text":"have a for loop. This for loop is executed three times. In each iteration, number will have a"},{"start":5161.92,"end":5167.2,"text":"different value. Initially it will be zero. In the second iteration, it will be one. And finally in"},{"start":5167.2,"end":5174.56,"text":"the last iteration, it will be two. Now here we can do something fun. We can add one to this,"},{"start":5175.28,"end":5181.52,"text":"run the program. And now the messages that the print are kind of more meaningful or more user-friendly,"},{"start":5181.6,"end":5187.12,"text":"like attempting number one, attempting number two and so on. We can take this to the next level."},{"start":5187.12,"end":5193.2,"text":"So we can pass another argument. Here I''m going to add an expression one more time, number plus one."},{"start":5193.92,"end":5200.4,"text":"So we''ll get one, two, three. Now I want to put this expression in parentheses. So let''s select this,"},{"start":5201.2,"end":5209.76,"text":"put it in parentheses, and then multiply it by a dot. So here we have a string that is multiplied"},{"start":5209.76,"end":5216.56,"text":"by a number. The result will be that string repeated that number of times. Let''s take a look. So run the"},{"start":5216.56,"end":5222.88,"text":"program. See, that''s pretty cool, isn''t it? Now let me show you one more thing before we finish this"},{"start":5222.88,"end":5229.36,"text":"lecture. As you saw, this range function generates numbers starting from zero all the way up to this"},{"start":5229.36,"end":5235.52,"text":"number here. But it doesn''t include this number. Here we can pass another argument, say start from one"},{"start":5236.24,"end":5242.48,"text":"and finish before four. With this change, we don''t need to add one to number every time,"},{"start":5243.12,"end":5248.56,"text":"because in the first iteration, this number variable will be set to one. So we can simplify"},{"start":5248.56,"end":5256.16,"text":"our code and make it cleaner. Let''s run it one more time. We get the exact same result. We can also"},{"start":5256.16,"end":5263.52,"text":"pass a third argument as a step. So I''m going to change the second argument to 10 and pass two as"},{"start":5263.52,"end":5271.28,"text":"a step. Look at the result. These are the numbers we get, one, three, five, and so on. So pretty useful,"},{"start":5271.28,"end":5274.24,"text":"you''re going to use this function a lot in real-world applications."},{"start":5280.08,"end":5284.64,"text":"Continuing with the example from the last lecture, let''s imagine the scenario where"},{"start":5284.64,"end":5290.24,"text":"after the first attempt, we can successfully send the message. In that case, we want to jump out of"},{"start":5290.24,"end":5296.56,"text":"this loop. We don''t want to repeat this task of sending a message three times. Let me show you how"},{"start":5296.56,"end":5302.16,"text":"to implement this. So in this demo, I''m going to simulate the scenario where we can successfully"},{"start":5302.16,"end":5310.88,"text":"send a message. So we define a variable, successful, and set it to true. Now here, after this print"},{"start":5310.88,"end":5319.36,"text":"statement, we''ll have an if statement, if successful, colon, then perhaps we can print"},{"start":5320.56,"end":5326.96,"text":"successful. Now here, we want to jump out of this loop. For that, we use the break statement."},{"start":5327.76,"end":5333.44,"text":"Let''s run this program and see what happens. So there you go. After the first attempt,"},{"start":5334.08,"end":5340.48,"text":"we''re successful and there are no more attempts. So once again, I want you to pay great attention"},{"start":5340.48,"end":5346.08,"text":"to the indentation here because that''s one of the common issues amongst beginners. So here''s our"},{"start":5346.08,"end":5353.6,"text":"for loop. These two lines are indented with four spaces and they belong to our for loop. In every"},{"start":5353.6,"end":5360.72,"text":"iteration, these two lines will be executed. Now, when we get to line four, if this condition is true,"},{"start":5360.72,"end":5368.64,"text":"then these two lines will be executed because both these lines are indented below this if statement."},{"start":5369.36,"end":5375.12,"text":"Now let''s take this program to the next level. What if we attempt three times and we still cannot"},{"start":5375.12,"end":5379.84,"text":"send an email? Perhaps we want to display a different message to the user. We say, hey,"},{"start":5379.84,"end":5388.8,"text":"we tried three times but it didn''t work. So I''m going to change successful to false. Now at the end,"},{"start":5388.8,"end":5395.76,"text":"here we can add an L statement. This is what we call a for L statement. What we put under this"},{"start":5395.76,"end":5402.4,"text":"L statement will only be executed if this loop completes without an early termination. So if we"},{"start":5402.4,"end":5409.2,"text":"never break out of this loop, then the L statement will be executed. So here we can print a message"},{"start":5409.2,"end":5420.64,"text":"like attempted three times and failed. So run the program. See what we get three attempts"},{"start":5420.72,"end":5427.12,"text":"followed by this message attempted three times and failed. In contrast, if we change"},{"start":5427.12,"end":5432.72,"text":"successful to true, because we terminate this loop using this break statement, what we have"},{"start":5433.36,"end":5440.56,"text":"in the else block will not be executed. Take a look. Run the program. We have one attempt successful done."},{"start":5440.56,"end":5452,"text":"In programming, we have this concept called nested loops. So we can put one loop inside of"},{"start":5452,"end":5457.28,"text":"another loop. And with this, we can get some interesting results. Let me show you. So I''m"},{"start":5457.28,"end":5466.48,"text":"going to start with this loop for x in range five colon. Now inside of this loop, I''m going to add"},{"start":5466.48,"end":5476.16,"text":"another loop. So for y in range three colon. And then in our second loop, I''m going to add"},{"start":5476.16,"end":5483.04,"text":"a print statement. Here we can use formatted strings to display coordinates. Remember,"},{"start":5483.04,"end":5489.44,"text":"formatted strings. So we have F followed by quotes. Now here we add parentheses for our"},{"start":5489.44,"end":5497.76,"text":"coordinates. First we want to display x and then comma followed by y. Let''s run this program and"},{"start":5497.76,"end":5505.2,"text":"see what happens. There you go. Pretty cool, isn''t it? So we get zero and zero, zero and one, zero"},{"start":5505.2,"end":5512,"text":"and two, then we get one and zero, one and one, one and two, and so on. Now let me explain how"},{"start":5512,"end":5518.32,"text":"exactly Python interpreter executes this code. So here we have two loops. This is what we call"},{"start":5518.32,"end":5525.68,"text":"the outer loop and this is the inner loop. So the execution of our program starts here. In the first"},{"start":5525.68,"end":5533.84,"text":"iteration of this loop, x is zero. Now we get to this statement, which is a child of this four"},{"start":5533.84,"end":5541.36,"text":"statement because it''s indented four times. This statement itself is a loop. So what we have inside"},{"start":5541.36,"end":5549.12,"text":"of this loop will be executed three times. In the first iteration, x is zero because we''re still in"},{"start":5549.12,"end":5555.44,"text":"the first iteration of the outer loop and y is also zero because we''re in the first iteration"},{"start":5555.44,"end":5562.48,"text":"of the inner loop. That is why we get zero and zero. Now we go to the second iteration of this"},{"start":5562.48,"end":5569.52,"text":"inner loop. In this iteration, y will be one, whereas x is still zero. That is why we get zero"},{"start":5569.52,"end":5575.76,"text":"and one. And similarly, in the third iteration of our inner loop, we''ll get zero and two in the"},{"start":5575.76,"end":5581.52,"text":"terminal. Now we''re done with the execution of the inner loop. So the control moves back"},{"start":5581.52,"end":5588.32,"text":"to our outer loop. Here will be in the second iteration. So x will be one. And then we start"},{"start":5588.32,"end":5595.6,"text":"here again. So we have to execute this inner loop three times. In the first iteration, y will be zero"},{"start":5595.6,"end":5600.96,"text":"and x is one. So here we have one and zero, then we''ll get one and one and one and two."},{"start":5600.96,"end":5604.56,"text":"You got the point. So this is all about nested loops."},{"start":5610.56,"end":5616.16,"text":"So you have learned how to use four loops to repeat one or more statements in your programs."},{"start":5616.16,"end":5622.64,"text":"Now let''s dive deeper and see what this range function returns. So earlier you learned about"},{"start":5623.36,"end":5629.84,"text":"the built-in type function. With this function, we can get the type of an object. So if I pass"},{"start":5629.84,"end":5637.52,"text":"five here and run this program, this is what we get. So the type of this number or this object is"},{"start":5637.52,"end":5644.64,"text":"int or integer. Now let''s look at the type of the value that we get from the range function."},{"start":5644.72,"end":5653.6,"text":"So as an argument, we pass range of a number. Let''s run this program. So this range function"},{"start":5653.6,"end":5661.04,"text":"returns an object of type range. So in Python, we have primitive types like numbers,"},{"start":5661.04,"end":5667.44,"text":"strings and booleans. But we also have complex types. Range is an example of one of those complex"},{"start":5667.44,"end":5673.44,"text":"types. Throughout this course, you''re going to learn about a lot of other complex types. Now what"},{"start":5673.44,"end":5680.48,"text":"is interesting about this range object is that it''s iterable, which means we can iterate over it"},{"start":5680.48,"end":5690.32,"text":"or use it in a for loop. That is why we can write code like this. So this range function returns"},{"start":5690.32,"end":5696.64,"text":"a range object which is iterable, which means we can iterate over it. In each iteration,"},{"start":5696.64,"end":5703.28,"text":"x will have a different value. Now, range objects are not the only iterable objects in Python."},{"start":5703.84,"end":5713.36,"text":"Strings are also iterable. So here, we can add a string like Python. Now in each iteration,"},{"start":5713.36,"end":5721.12,"text":"x will hold one character in this string. Let me show you. So print x and I''m going to delete"},{"start":5721.12,"end":5729.04,"text":"these two lines here. Let''s run this program. So in each iteration, we''ll get one character and"},{"start":5729.04,"end":5736.16,"text":"print it. We have another complex type called list, which we use to store a list of objects."},{"start":5736.16,"end":5742.96,"text":"So we add square brackets. This indicates a list. Now we can add a list of numbers or a list of"},{"start":5742.96,"end":5749.36,"text":"strings like a list of names. You will learn about lists later in the course. So let''s run this one"},{"start":5749.36,"end":5756.48,"text":"more time. As you can see, we can iterate over lists. In each iteration, we''ll get one object in"},{"start":5756.48,"end":5763.04,"text":"this list. Now later in the course, I will show you how to create your own custom objects that are"},{"start":5763.04,"end":5772.64,"text":"iterable. For example, you will learn how to write code like this. For item in shopping cart, print"},{"start":5772.64,"end":5778.24,"text":"item. So shopping cart is going to be a custom object that you will create. It''s not going to be"},{"start":5778.24,"end":5784.24,"text":"an integer or a string or Boolean. It''s a custom object. It has a different structure. And we''ll"},{"start":5784.24,"end":5790.08,"text":"make it iterable. So we can use it in a for loop. And in each iteration, we can get one item in the"},{"start":5790.08,"end":5801.68,"text":"shopping cart and print it on the terminal. So you have learned that we use for loops to iterate over"},{"start":5801.68,"end":5808,"text":"iterable objects. In Python, we have another kind of loop that is a while loop. And we use that to"},{"start":5808,"end":5814.24,"text":"repeat something as long as a condition is true. Here''s an example. So let''s define a variable"},{"start":5814.24,"end":5823.12,"text":"number and set it to 100. Now we use while. And here we add a condition. As long as number is"},{"start":5823.12,"end":5830.4,"text":"greater than zero, we add a colon. Once again, we have indentation. So we can repeat one or more"},{"start":5830.4,"end":5838.96,"text":"statements. We can print this number. And then we can divide it by half. So number equals number."},{"start":5840.32,"end":5847.28,"text":"Use the integer division to divide it by two. Or we can use the augmented assignment operator"},{"start":5847.28,"end":5856.72,"text":"to shorten this code. Like this. Now let''s run this program. So here''s what we get. Initially,"},{"start":5856.72,"end":5864.32,"text":"our number is 100. We divide it by half. We get 50, then 25, and so on. So as you can see,"},{"start":5864.32,"end":5870.32,"text":"in this example, we are not iterating over an iterable, like a range object or a string or a"},{"start":5870.32,"end":5878.16,"text":"list. We are evaluating a condition and repeating a task. Let me show you a real-world example of a"},{"start":5878.16,"end":5884,"text":"while loop. In this interactive shell, Python is waiting for an input. We can type something like"},{"start":5884,"end":5890.64,"text":"2 plus 2. It will evaluate it and ask for the next input. We can add another expression like 10 is"},{"start":5890.64,"end":5899.28,"text":"greater than 2. So these steps will continue until we press ctrl D. So behind the scene, we have a"},{"start":5899.28,"end":5906.48,"text":"while loop that continues execution until we press ctrl D. That is the condition that causes the"},{"start":5906.48,"end":5912.8,"text":"while loop to terminate. Let me show you how to build something like this in Python. So let''s"},{"start":5912.8,"end":5919.68,"text":"define a variable, command, and set it to an empty string. Now here we need a while loop."},{"start":5920.32,"end":5927.6,"text":"We want this while loop to execute as long as command does not equal to quit. So command does"},{"start":5927.6,"end":5936.48,"text":"not equal to quit. Call in. In this loop, we want to continuously get input from the user. So we use"},{"start":5936.48,"end":5945.12,"text":"the built-in input function. We add a label like this. Get the result and store it in the command"},{"start":5945.12,"end":5951.12,"text":"variable. Now at this point, Python interactive shell will evaluate this command. We are not"},{"start":5951.12,"end":5956.32,"text":"going to do that in this lecture because that''s way too complex. For simplicity, we can just echo"},{"start":5956.32,"end":5965.92,"text":"back what the user entered. So print, echo, and as a second argument, we pass this command. So this"},{"start":5965.92,"end":5972.72,"text":"is our while loop. It will execute until we type quit. Now as I told you before, don''t run this"},{"start":5972.72,"end":5977.92,"text":"program using the code runner extension because by default, it will run your program in the output"},{"start":5977.92,"end":5985.68,"text":"window, which is read only. So open up the terminal using ctrl and back tick and run Python or Python"},{"start":5985.68,"end":5995.52,"text":"3 app.py. So here''s our command prompt. Let''s type 2 plus 2. It echoes back. Let''s type 3 times 2."},{"start":5995.6,"end":6001.68,"text":"There you go. If we type quit, our program terminates. Now let''s try it one more time."},{"start":6002.64,"end":6009.44,"text":"What if we type quit in uppercase? The program doesn''t terminate because as you learned before,"},{"start":6009.44,"end":6015.76,"text":"lowercase and uppercase characters have different numeric representations. So quit in lowercase is"},{"start":6015.76,"end":6022.96,"text":"different from quit in uppercase. Now to solve this problem, an amateur programmer may do something"},{"start":6022.96,"end":6034.16,"text":"like this. And command does not equal to capital quit. So while command does not equal quit in"},{"start":6034.16,"end":6040.48,"text":"lowercase and quit in uppercase, continue getting input from the user. Let''s run this program in"},{"start":6040.48,"end":6049.28,"text":"terminal and see what happens. So one more time, Python app.py. We type quit. Beautiful. It works."},{"start":6049.28,"end":6056.48,"text":"We type quit in uppercase. That would work too. But what if I type quit with an uppercase q and"},{"start":6056.48,"end":6064.32,"text":"lowercase uit? Our program doesn''t terminate. So this is a poor way of checking for the quit command."},{"start":6064.88,"end":6071.6,"text":"What is a better way? Let me show you. So we don''t need this and operator here. Instead,"},{"start":6072.4,"end":6079.44,"text":"because command is a string, we can call the lower method. So whatever the user types in,"},{"start":6079.44,"end":6086.24,"text":"first we''ll convert it to lowercase and then compare it with quit in lowercase. With this"},{"start":6086.24,"end":6091.52,"text":"change, it doesn''t matter how the user types the word quit. We''ll always terminate the program."},{"start":6091.84,"end":6102.64,"text":"Now the last thing I want to discuss in this section is the concept of infinite loops. An infinite"},{"start":6102.64,"end":6112.08,"text":"loop is a loop that runs forever. So if I change this condition to true, because true is always true,"},{"start":6112.08,"end":6118.8,"text":"this while loop will run forever. So to jump out of this, we need a break statement. So after we get"},{"start":6118.8,"end":6127.12,"text":"the input from the user, we can get the command, convert it to lowercase, and see if it equals to"},{"start":6127.12,"end":6134.08,"text":"quit. If that''s the case, we want to break. Now with this change, we no longer need to initialize"},{"start":6134.08,"end":6140.88,"text":"command to an empty string. Previously, we needed this because we had a wild statement like this."},{"start":6140.88,"end":6148.48,"text":"While command does not equal quit. So we had to define this command variable and that''s why we"},{"start":6148.48,"end":6154.88,"text":"have set it to an empty string. Without this line, when Python interpreter tries to execute this code,"},{"start":6154.88,"end":6161.2,"text":"it doesn''t know what command is. So now that we have an infinite loop, we no longer need to define"},{"start":6161.2,"end":6167.12,"text":"command and set it to an empty string. So in terms of functionality, this program is exactly the same"},{"start":6167.12,"end":6172.72,"text":"as the program we wrote in the last lecture. Just be aware of these infinite loops, because they"},{"start":6172.72,"end":6179.92,"text":"run forever, you should always have a way to jump out of them. Otherwise, your program will run forever."},{"start":6179.92,"end":6185.44,"text":"And this can sometimes cause issues, because if you''re executing operations that consume memory,"},{"start":6185.44,"end":6188.4,"text":"at some point, your program may run out of memory and crash."},{"start":6194.88,"end":6200.88,"text":"All right, time for an exercise. I want you to write a program to display the even numbers"},{"start":6200.88,"end":6207.2,"text":"between one to 10. So when you run this program, you should see two, four, six, and eight. And after"},{"start":6207.2,"end":6214,"text":"these, I want you to print this message, we have four even numbers. Now here''s a quick hint before"},{"start":6214,"end":6220,"text":"you get started. You should call the range function with one and 10. Do not use the third argument,"},{"start":6220,"end":6225.6,"text":"which is called step. So basically, I want you to iterate over all the numbers between one to 10."},{"start":6226.16,"end":6232.32,"text":"Check if each number is an even number and then print it on the terminal. So pause the video,"},{"start":6232.32,"end":6236.08,"text":"spend two minutes on this exercise, when you''re done, come back, continue watching."},{"start":6240.56,"end":6245.84,"text":"So we start with a for loop for number in range one to 10 colon."},{"start":6247.6,"end":6254.48,"text":"We check to see if the remainder of division of this number by two equals zero. So if number"},{"start":6254.48,"end":6260.48,"text":"modulus two equals zero, then reprint this number."},{"start":6262.64,"end":6269.68,"text":"Now let''s run this program. So we get two, four, six, eight, beautiful. Now to count the even numbers,"},{"start":6270.48,"end":6276.64,"text":"we need a separate variable. So let''s call that count. Initially, we set it to zero. Now in this"},{"start":6276.64,"end":6283.76,"text":"if block, every time we find an even number, we need to increment count. So we set count plus"},{"start":6283.76,"end":6293.36,"text":"equals one. And finally, after our for loop, we can print a formatted string. We have count"},{"start":6294.08,"end":6302,"text":"even numbers. Let''s run the program. And here''s the result. So that brings us to the end of this"},{"start":6302,"end":6306.88,"text":"section. In the next section, you''re going to learn how to create your own functions. I hope"},{"start":6306.88,"end":6319.92,"text":"you enjoyed the section and thank you for watching. So far, you have learned how to use some of the"},{"start":6319.92,"end":6326.48,"text":"built-in functions in Python, such as print, round, and so on. In this section, you''re going to learn"},{"start":6326.48,"end":6331.52,"text":"how to write your own functions. Now you might ask, but why do we even need to write our own"},{"start":6331.6,"end":6338.32,"text":"functions? Well, when you build a real program, that program is going to consist hundreds or"},{"start":6338.32,"end":6343.84,"text":"thousands of lines of code. You shouldn''t write all that code in one file like we have done so far."},{"start":6343.84,"end":6349.76,"text":"You should break that code into smaller, more maintainable, and potentially more reusable"},{"start":6349.76,"end":6356,"text":"chunks. You refer to these chunks as functions. So let me show you how to create your own custom"},{"start":6356,"end":6362.64,"text":"functions. We start with the def keyword, which is short for define. Next, we need to give our"},{"start":6362.64,"end":6368.56,"text":"function a name. So let''s call this greet. All the best practices you learned about naming your"},{"start":6368.56,"end":6374.64,"text":"variables also apply to naming your functions. So make sure your function names are meaningful,"},{"start":6374.64,"end":6381.44,"text":"descriptive, use lowercase letters to name your functions, and an underscore to separate multiple"},{"start":6381.44,"end":6387.52,"text":"words. Now, after the name, we need to add parentheses. You will see why shortly. And then"},{"start":6387.52,"end":6394,"text":"we''ll add a colon. Now, what is going to happen? You know it. We''re going to get indentation,"},{"start":6394,"end":6400.08,"text":"which means the following statements will belong to this function. So here I''m going to add two"},{"start":6400.08,"end":6409.84,"text":"statements. Hi there, and welcome aboard. Both designs belong to this function because they''re"},{"start":6409.84,"end":6416.8,"text":"indented. Now we''re done with this function. We need to call it. So we remove the indentation,"},{"start":6416.8,"end":6423.36,"text":"and we add two line breaks after this function. This is what pep8 recommends to keep our code"},{"start":6423.36,"end":6428.48,"text":"clean and maintainable. Now, if you forget to add two line breaks, don''t worry. As soon as you save"},{"start":6428.48,"end":6433.92,"text":"the changes, auto pep8 will automatically add these line breaks for you. Let me show you. So I''m"},{"start":6433.92,"end":6440.88,"text":"going to remove these line breaks and call this function greet with parentheses, just like how we"},{"start":6440.88,"end":6448.48,"text":"call the built-in functions. Now save the changes. There you go. So we get two line breaks after our"},{"start":6448.48,"end":6455.52,"text":"function. Now let''s run this program. So we get these two messages on the terminal."},{"start":6456.48,"end":6467.44,"text":"Now here''s a question for you. What is the difference between the greet and print functions?"},{"start":6468.08,"end":6473.84,"text":"The difference is that this print function takes an input, whereas our greet function"},{"start":6473.84,"end":6479.44,"text":"doesn''t take any inputs. So let me show you how to pass inputs like first name and last name to"},{"start":6479.44,"end":6485.44,"text":"this function. When defining a function, in between parentheses, we list our parameters."},{"start":6486,"end":6493.28,"text":"So here we add two parameters, like first underline name and last underline name. Now,"},{"start":6493.28,"end":6500,"text":"when calling this function, we need to supply two values for those parameters. We refer to them as"},{"start":6500,"end":6508.08,"text":"arguments. So, mosh, hamidani, these are the arguments to the greet function. That''s one of the"},{"start":6508.08,"end":6511.92,"text":"terms that a lot of developers out there don''t know. They don''t know the difference between"},{"start":6511.92,"end":6518.56,"text":"parameters and arguments. A parameter is the input that you define for your function, whereas an"},{"start":6518.56,"end":6526.32,"text":"argument is the actual value for a given parameter. Okay, now let''s change line two. And instead of"},{"start":6526.32,"end":6532.32,"text":"saying hi there, we can greet a person by their full name. So we can convert this to a formatted"},{"start":6532.32,"end":6541.44,"text":"string and pass two fields here, first name as well as last name. Save the changes, run the"},{"start":6541.44,"end":6548,"text":"program, and this is what we get in terminal. Now this function is more useful, we can reuse it and"},{"start":6548,"end":6557.12,"text":"call it with different arguments. So let''s greet john smith as well, run the program, so we get"},{"start":6557.12,"end":6563.6,"text":"hi mosh hamidani and hi john smith. Now, note that by default, all the parameters that you define"},{"start":6563.6,"end":6570.8,"text":"for a function are required. So here our greet function takes two parameters. If I exclude"},{"start":6570.8,"end":6576.8,"text":"one of these arguments and save the changes, you can see we have this red underline. So,"},{"start":6576.8,"end":6583.2,"text":"pilot is complaining and saying there is no value for argument last name. Also, if we run the program,"},{"start":6583.2,"end":6592.48,"text":"we get this type error, greet missing one required positional argument. So let''s put this back. Now,"},{"start":6592.48,"end":6603.28,"text":"later I will show you how to define optional parameters. So this is the simplified version"},{"start":6603.28,"end":6609.2,"text":"of this greet function we created earlier. Now in programming, we have two types of functions."},{"start":6609.92,"end":6618.96,"text":"Functions that perform a task and functions that calculate and return a value. Here are some examples."},{"start":6619.52,"end":6626.08,"text":"Both the print and greet functions are examples of type one. They''re performing a task which is"},{"start":6626.08,"end":6634.16,"text":"printing something on the terminal. In contrast, the round function is an example of a function that"},{"start":6634.16,"end":6640.4,"text":"calculates and returns a value. So the functions that you create fall into these two categories."},{"start":6641.04,"end":6646.48,"text":"Now, let me show you how to rewrite this greet function, but in the second form. So instead of"},{"start":6646.48,"end":6653.12,"text":"printing this string on the terminal, we simply return it. Let me show you. So I''m going to delete"},{"start":6653.12,"end":6662.16,"text":"all this code, define a new function, but call it get underline greeting. We add the name parameter"},{"start":6662.88,"end":6670.8,"text":"and simply return this formatted string, high name. That''s all we have to do. So we use the return"},{"start":6670.8,"end":6678.16,"text":"statement to return a value from this function. Now we can call this function, get underline greeting,"},{"start":6678.88,"end":6686.24,"text":"pass a name, like mosh, because it returns a value, we can store that value in a separate"},{"start":6686.24,"end":6692.24,"text":"variable like message. Now you might be curious, which form of this greeting functions is better?"},{"start":6692.8,"end":6698.24,"text":"Well, with this first implementation, we are locked to printing something in the terminal."},{"start":6698.24,"end":6704,"text":"In the future, if you want to write that message in a file or send it in an email, we have to create"},{"start":6704,"end":6711.52,"text":"another function. So we cannot reuse this great function in other scenarios. In contrast, this"},{"start":6711.6,"end":6717.28,"text":"second form is not tied to printing something on the terminal, it simply returns a value."},{"start":6717.92,"end":6723.28,"text":"Now we get this value and we can do whatever we want with it. We can print it on the terminal,"},{"start":6724.32,"end":6732,"text":"or we can use the built in open function to write this message to a file. So we can create a file"},{"start":6732,"end":6739.52,"text":"like content.txt, open it for writing, this returns a file object and then we can call"},{"start":6739.52,"end":6745.84,"text":"file.write message. Now don''t worry about these two lines, later in the course I''m going to talk"},{"start":6745.84,"end":6750.88,"text":"about working with files. But what I want you to take away here is that we have this message"},{"start":6750.88,"end":6756.56,"text":"variable and we can do whatever we want with it. We can print it on the terminal, write it to a file,"},{"start":6756.56,"end":6762.24,"text":"send it in an email and so on. And one more thing before we finish this lecture. So here''s our greet"},{"start":6762.24,"end":6770.24,"text":"function and as you can see we''re simply printing a string. Now if we call greet, give it a name,"},{"start":6770.8,"end":6777.12,"text":"run the program, we get this message, hiMarsh. But what if we put this inside of a call"},{"start":6777.84,"end":6785.44,"text":"to the print function? Let''s see what we get. We get hiMarsh followed by none. What is this?"},{"start":6786.08,"end":6793.2,"text":"None is the return value of the greet function. So in Python all functions by default return"},{"start":6793.2,"end":6799.04,"text":"the non value. None is an object that represents the absence of a value. Later in the course you''re"},{"start":6799.04,"end":6804.96,"text":"going to learn more about none. What matters now is that all functions return none by default"},{"start":6804.96,"end":6812.56,"text":"unless you specifically return a value. So here if we return some string,"},{"start":6813.12,"end":6818.72,"text":"none will no longer be returned. Now I just want to clarify something. Earlier I told you that we"},{"start":6818.72,"end":6823.84,"text":"have two types of functions in programming, functions that carry out a task or functions"},{"start":6823.84,"end":6830.88,"text":"that calculate and return a value. So back to the code we previously had. So even though this"},{"start":6830.88,"end":6837.68,"text":"function returns none by default, it is still classified as a function that carries out a task."},{"start":6843.52,"end":6849.76,"text":"Let''s create another function. We call it increment. We want to use this function to"},{"start":6849.76,"end":6857.84,"text":"increment a number by a given value. So here we simply return number plus by."},{"start":6859.36,"end":6866.64,"text":"Now we can call this function like this. Increment two and one. This returns a value so we can store it"},{"start":6867.36,"end":6872.96,"text":"in a variable like result and then print it on the terminal. Let''s run the program."},{"start":6873.52,"end":6879.76,"text":"We get three, beautiful. Now we can simplify this code. We have used this result variable"},{"start":6879.76,"end":6887.28,"text":"only in a single place. That is line six. So we don''t really need it. So on line six we can replace"},{"start":6887.28,"end":6895.76,"text":"result with a call to increment function like this. So when Python interpreter executes this code,"},{"start":6896.32,"end":6902,"text":"first it will call the increment function. It will get the result and temporarily store it in a"},{"start":6902,"end":6907.44,"text":"variable for us. We don''t see that variable and then it will pass that variable as an argument"},{"start":6907.44,"end":6914.96,"text":"to the print function. Now if we run this program we get the exact same result. Beautiful. Now we"},{"start":6914.96,"end":6922,"text":"can make this code more readable. If someone else looks at line five they may not know exactly what"},{"start":6922,"end":6928.88,"text":"these arguments are for. We can use a keyword argument to make this code more readable. So this"},{"start":6928.88,"end":6937.2,"text":"one here is the value of this by parameter. We can prefix it with the name of the parameter like this."},{"start":6938.4,"end":6945.36,"text":"Now we can read this code almost like plain English. Increment two by one. So if you''re calling a"},{"start":6945.36,"end":6951.2,"text":"function with multiple arguments and it''s not quite clear what these arguments are for, you can make"},{"start":6951.28,"end":6958.24,"text":"your code more readable by using keyword arguments. So here by equals one is a keyword argument."},{"start":6964,"end":6968.08,"text":"Earlier I told you that all the parameters that you define for a function"},{"start":6968.08,"end":6974.24,"text":"are required by default. In this lecture I''m going to show you how to make the by parameter optional."},{"start":6974.88,"end":6981.92,"text":"So let''s say we don''t want to explicitly pass by equals one every time we want to call this"},{"start":6981.92,"end":6988.64,"text":"increment function. We want to use this function to increment a value by one. So we remove the"},{"start":6988.64,"end":6995.92,"text":"second argument. Now we need to give this parameter a default value. So we set it to one. Now if we"},{"start":6995.92,"end":7002.24,"text":"call this function and don''t supply the second argument this default value will be used. Otherwise"},{"start":7002.24,"end":7009.04,"text":"the value that we specify here will be used. Let me show you. So we run this program. The result is"},{"start":7009.04,"end":7017.12,"text":"three but if we pass the second argument here we''ll increment two by five so we will get seven."},{"start":7018.24,"end":7024.16,"text":"So you can see it''s pretty easy to make a parameter optional. Just be aware that all these optional"},{"start":7024.16,"end":7032.4,"text":"parameters should come after the required parameters. In other words I cannot add another"},{"start":7032.4,"end":7039.04,"text":"required parameter here. Let''s call that another. I cannot add that here. If I save the changes"},{"start":7039.04,"end":7046.56,"text":"you can see we get a red underline here. So all the optional parameters should come after the"},{"start":7046.56,"end":7052.8,"text":"required parameters. Now obviously in this case we don''t need the second parameter so let''s delete it."},{"start":7055.12,"end":7064.24,"text":"There are times that you may want to create a function that takes a variable number of arguments."},{"start":7064.24,"end":7071.36,"text":"Here is an example. Let''s define this function multiply that takes two parameters x and y"},{"start":7071.92,"end":7078.56,"text":"and simply returns x times y. Now we can call this function like this."},{"start":7079.36,"end":7086.16,"text":"So far so good but what if we want to pass one or two more arguments here? That doesn''t work"},{"start":7086.16,"end":7091.84,"text":"because our multiply function takes only two parameters. To solve this problem we need to"},{"start":7091.84,"end":7098.16,"text":"replace these two parameters with a single parameter. We use a plural name here to indicate"},{"start":7098.16,"end":7104.88,"text":"that this is a collection of arguments and then we prefix it with an asterisk. This is the magical"},{"start":7105.12,"end":7111.04,"text":"part. Let me show you what happens when you use an asterisk here. So temporarily let''s"},{"start":7111.04,"end":7117.28,"text":"delete this line and simply print numbers. Let''s see what we get here. So run the program."},{"start":7118.24,"end":7125.92,"text":"You can see all our arguments and they''re packed in parentheses. What is this? Well earlier you"},{"start":7125.92,"end":7132.32,"text":"learned about lists. I briefly mentioned that you can use square brackets to create a list of"},{"start":7133.28,"end":7138.64,"text":"objects like two, three, four, five. Now later in the course we have a comprehensive section about"},{"start":7138.64,"end":7144.88,"text":"lists so don''t worry about the details of lists and how they work. But what I want you to note here"},{"start":7144.88,"end":7151.68,"text":"is that the only difference between this list and what we have here is in the notation. So we use"},{"start":7151.68,"end":7158.24,"text":"square brackets to create lists and parentheses to create tuples. Some people call it tuples or"},{"start":7158.32,"end":7164.72,"text":"tuples. So a tuple is similar to a list in that it''s a collection of objects. The difference is"},{"start":7164.72,"end":7170.88,"text":"that we cannot modify this collection. We cannot add a new object to this tuple. Once again later"},{"start":7170.88,"end":7176.24,"text":"in the course we''re going to have a comprehensive section about lists, tuples and other data"},{"start":7176.24,"end":7183.6,"text":"structures. What matters now is that these tuples just like lists are iterable. So we can iterate"},{"start":7183.6,"end":7192.4,"text":"over them which means we can use them in loops. Let me show you. So let''s write for number in"},{"start":7192.4,"end":7200.96,"text":"numbers colon. Let''s just print one number at a time. Actually we don''t need this line so delete"},{"start":7201.52,"end":7208.32,"text":"and run the program. So we iterate over this tuple and in each iteration we get one number and print"},{"start":7208.48,"end":7214.32,"text":"it on the terminal. So now with a simple change we can calculate the product of all these numbers."},{"start":7214.88,"end":7222.08,"text":"All we have to do is to define a variable like total. Initially we set it to one and then in each"},{"start":7222.08,"end":7230.8,"text":"iteration we get total and multiplied by the current number. Or we can rewrite this statement"},{"start":7230.8,"end":7240.72,"text":"using an augmented assignment operator. So total times equal number. Line five and four are exactly"},{"start":7240.72,"end":7247.84,"text":"identical. So I''m going to use line five because it''s shorter and cleaner. Delete. And finally we''ll"},{"start":7247.84,"end":7255.36,"text":"return the total. Now one of the issues I see often in beginner''s code is that they don''t use this"},{"start":7255.36,"end":7261.12,"text":"indentation properly. So they put the return statement here and then they wonder why their"},{"start":7261.12,"end":7266.8,"text":"function doesn''t work properly. If you put the return statement here it will be part of the for loop"},{"start":7267.6,"end":7274.08,"text":"so it will be executed in each iteration. In this case after the first iteration because of this"},{"start":7274.08,"end":7279.84,"text":"return statement will return from this multiply function. So the total will not be calculated"},{"start":7279.84,"end":7286.72,"text":"properly. We need to put this at the same level of indentation as other statements in this function."},{"start":7287.36,"end":7293.76,"text":"So here we have our for statement. We loop over all the numbers, we calculate the total and then"},{"start":7293.76,"end":7301.2,"text":"finally return it. So with this implementation we can get the result and print it on the terminal."},{"start":7301.84,"end":7308,"text":"Let''s run the program and you can see the product of these numbers is 120."},{"start":7308.24,"end":7313.12,"text":"Hey guys I just wanted to let you know that this tutorial is actually the first two hours of my"},{"start":7313.12,"end":7318.56,"text":"complete Python mastery course. If you''re finding this helpful and want to dive even deeper the full"},{"start":7318.56,"end":7323.2,"text":"course covers everything from beginner basics to advanced concepts like machine learning, web"},{"start":7323.2,"end":7328.72,"text":"development and automation. You also get hands-on projects to build your skills step by step. I"},{"start":7328.72,"end":7333.28,"text":"put the link in the description box if you''re ready to take your Python knowledge to the next level."}]'::jsonb
) AS segment
WHERE l.youtube_video_id = 'K5KVEU3aaeQ';

