CROSS JOIN jsonb_array_elements(
    '[{"start":0,"end":3.76,"text":"Hey everybody, in this video I''m going to teach you everything you need to know to start working"},{"start":3.76,"end":8.64,"text":"with pandas. So I encourage you to sit back, relax, and enjoy the show."},{"start":11.44,"end":17.04,"text":"Pandas is a Python library built on top of NumPy. It''s widely used in data analysis,"},{"start":17.04,"end":21.76,"text":"data science, and machine learning. The name pandas comes from the term panel data."},{"start":21.76,"end":26.48,"text":"Unfortunately, it has nothing to do with pandas, the animal. Using this library, you typically"},{"start":26.48,"end":32.96,"text":"work with objects known as series and data frames. A series is like a one-dimensional labeled column."},{"start":32.96,"end":38.64,"text":"A data frame is like a two-dimensional labeled grid or table. With this library, you can import,"},{"start":38.64,"end":45.52,"text":"display, manipulate, and export tabular data. Think of pandas as Python''s version of Microsoft Excel,"},{"start":45.52,"end":50.32,"text":"but on steroids. Before getting started with this series, I would recommend learning everything"},{"start":50.32,"end":54.96,"text":"up to Python lists. I do have a free one-hour course on YouTube to catch you up to speed if"},{"start":54.96,"end":62,"text":"you''re interested. Here''s how we can start working with pandas. Within your IDE, at the top,"},{"start":62,"end":70.4,"text":"we''re going to import the library of pandas, then give it an alias as pd, meaning pandas."},{"start":71.12,"end":76.64,"text":"You''ll likely need to download this package, and honestly the easiest way to do that, if pandas is"},{"start":76.64,"end":82.32,"text":"underlined red, you can just simply install this package. That should clear up that warning."},{"start":83.12,"end":88.88,"text":"Otherwise, what you could do is go to your left toolbar and open up a terminal. You can also use"},{"start":88.88,"end":98.56,"text":"the shortcut of Alt plus F12. You can use pip to install pandas. If you have multiple versions of"},{"start":98.56,"end":104.8,"text":"Python downloaded, you''ll need to use a different command if that doesn''t work. Python dash m,"},{"start":105.04,"end":111.68,"text":"then pip install pandas. One of those should work for you. Then hit enter."},{"start":114.56,"end":117.44,"text":"To check the current version of pandas, we can print"},{"start":118.72,"end":126.88,"text":"access pandas as pd, double underscore, also known as dunder, version, double underscore again."},{"start":127.68,"end":135.2,"text":"And the current version of pandas that I''m running is 2.3.2. Alright, and we are ready for our first"},{"start":135.2,"end":148,"text":"lesson. Alright, everybody, to kick off this pandas series, I got to talk about, well, series. A"},{"start":148,"end":154.48,"text":"series is a pandas one dimensional labeled array. Think of it like a single column in a spreadsheet."},{"start":154.48,"end":160.72,"text":"It''s one dimensional. A good analogy would be a single hallway with apartments. Each apartment"},{"start":160.72,"end":167.44,"text":"holds some data. Each apartment also has some sort of label or number. A series is a one dimensional"},{"start":167.44,"end":171.76,"text":"labeled array. Here''s how we can create one. We''ll start with the Python list."},{"start":172.96,"end":179.36,"text":"Let''s say we have some data, then we''ll add a few numbers 100, 102, 104."},{"start":180.32,"end":188,"text":"I can convert this list to be a series. Here''s how. I will create a series object equals access"},{"start":188,"end":197.2,"text":"pandas, spd, call the series constructor. Now this is a constructor, not a function. The s is uppercase."},{"start":198.08,"end":203.92,"text":"As an argument, we will pass in our data. And then if I were to print my series object,"},{"start":204.24,"end":212,"text":"here''s what it would say. There''s a couple things going on here. All of our data is arranged in a"},{"start":212,"end":220.24,"text":"single column, 100, 102, 104. The left hand side has an index. The index has labels starting with"},{"start":220.24,"end":228.64,"text":"zero, zero, one, two. And on the bottom, we have metadata about this series. The data type of what"},{"start":228.8,"end":235.36,"text":"we''re storing are 64 bit integers, 100, 102, 104. If we were to change the data type,"},{"start":235.92,"end":246.48,"text":"the metadata is going to change too. I''ll add some decimal portions, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3. And let''s see what changes."},{"start":247.52,"end":254.48,"text":"Now the data type is 64 bit floating point numbers. Or we could use letters or strings."},{"start":255.04,"end":275.36,"text":"A, B, C. Now the data type of what we''re storing are objects. Or even booleans. True, false, true."},{"start":275.68,"end":287.6,"text":"The data type of this series is bool, meaning boolean. True or false. But let''s change these back to be"},{"start":287.6,"end":298.16,"text":"numbers. 100, 102, 104. Now when you construct a series object, you can set an index with custom"},{"start":298.16,"end":304.4,"text":"labels. The default behavior for each label is to start at zero and increment by one. But we can"},{"start":304.4,"end":309.52,"text":"pass in something custom. This will be another argument within our series constructor. We''ll pass"},{"start":309.52,"end":317.68,"text":"in a keyword argument for readability. Index equals. We can pass in a list, a tuple, a dictionary,"},{"start":317.68,"end":324.48,"text":"a numpy array, or even another series. To keep it simple, let''s set the first label to be A,"},{"start":325.2,"end":334,"text":"then B, then C. Here we go. Here are the new labels. With our index, we have new labels."},{"start":334,"end":341.44,"text":"A, B, C. But the values are still the same. 100, 102, 104. You could get creative with your labels."},{"start":341.44,"end":348.96,"text":"For example, going back to our apartment analogy, let''s say apartment number one, that apartment"},{"start":348.96,"end":359.2,"text":"number two, then apartment number three. We have apartment one is 100, apartment number two is"},{"start":359.2,"end":370.16,"text":"102, apartment number three is 104. We''ll change that back. If at any time you need to access a value"},{"start":370.16,"end":377.84,"text":"directly within a series, you''ll take your series, access the lock property. Lock means location by"},{"start":377.84,"end":384.72,"text":"label, but people just say lock. Use the subscript operator, which is a set of straight brackets,"},{"start":385.52,"end":392.16,"text":"then you will select a label. For example, A. Return the value where the label is A."},{"start":394,"end":406.4,"text":"This will return a value whatever is at this label. A is 100, B is 102, C is 104. If there''s a label"},{"start":406.4,"end":412.32,"text":"that doesn''t exist, like D, we get a key error. Let''s change that back."},{"start":412.64,"end":417.68,"text":"To update one of these values, we''ll have to access that lock property. Take our series,"},{"start":418.96,"end":425.28,"text":"access the lock property within the subscript operator, locate the value at label C."},{"start":426.56,"end":432.48,"text":"Then let''s set this to be 200. Then we will print our series."},{"start":432.72,"end":439.68,"text":"C is now 200. So to print or access a value, you access the lock property. We''re locating a value"},{"start":439.68,"end":452.88,"text":"by label. Now you can also locate by integer position. That''s iLock, series.the letter i, lock."},{"start":454.32,"end":461.6,"text":"If I need the first value, the integer location is going to be zero. That returns 100."},{"start":462.48,"end":472.24,"text":"100. One is 102. And two is 104. It''s pretty similar to accessing an array in other programming"},{"start":472.24,"end":480.64,"text":"languages. So you got iLock for integer location or lock location by label. Okay, now we''re going"},{"start":480.64,"end":488.64,"text":"to filter by value. We''ll need a few more values. Let''s say we have 200 and 202. We''ll need a few"},{"start":488.72,"end":494.88,"text":"more labels though. Currently there''s a mismatch. Value error length of values five does not match"},{"start":494.88,"end":508.24,"text":"the length of index three. We''ll add a few more. We have abcde. There we go. Let''s filter by values."},{"start":508.24,"end":516.56,"text":"We will return any values that are 200 or greater. Here''s how. Take our series, use the subscript"},{"start":516.56,"end":525.2,"text":"operator, and here we''ll write a condition. Return any values within our series that are greater than"},{"start":525.2,"end":535.76,"text":"or equal to 200. This will print the label of D has a value of 200. The label of E has a value of"},{"start":535.76,"end":548.4,"text":"202. Let''s switch this to be less than 200. A is 100. B is 102. C is 104. All right, here''s a more"},{"start":548.4,"end":554.4,"text":"complex example. Rather than using a Python list for this next example, we''ll be using a dictionary."},{"start":557.36,"end":562.56,"text":"As you guys might know, I really like pizza. And well, I need to go on a diet because I''ve"},{"start":562.56,"end":567.92,"text":"eaten too much pizza. I''m going to use a Python dictionary to record how many calories I''ve"},{"start":567.92,"end":575.04,"text":"eaten per day. I''ll create a dictionary. We''ll name it calories. Calories equals a Python dictionary."},{"start":575.6,"end":581.12,"text":"A dictionary is made of key value pairs. For the key of day one,"},{"start":583.92,"end":591.6,"text":"for the value within this key value pair, I''ll set this to be 1750, meaning 1750 calories."},{"start":592.56,"end":596.88,"text":"I''m trying to eat less than 2000 calories per day. If you would like, feel free to pick different"},{"start":596.88,"end":608.88,"text":"numbers. For day two, I didn''t stick to my diet on day two. I had 2100 calories. Then for day three,"},{"start":612.64,"end":620.72,"text":"I had 1700 calories. Now to create a series again, we will type series equals"},{"start":621.2,"end":627.36,"text":"acts as pandas as PD, call the series constructor, then pass in our dictionary."},{"start":630.8,"end":636.24,"text":"Since our dictionary is made of key value pairs, we''ll use the keys as the labels."},{"start":637.44,"end":640.64,"text":"So you don''t need to pass in an index like this."},{"start":641.04,"end":651.68,"text":"If we were to print our series, here''s the output. This single column represents the calories I''ve"},{"start":651.68,"end":658.48,"text":"eaten each day. And on the left hand side is each label for this column. We have day one,"},{"start":658.48,"end":664.8,"text":"day two, day three. Let''s access the lock property to see how many calories I''ve eaten on a certain"},{"start":664.8,"end":680.24,"text":"day. Day one, 1750, day two, 2100, day three, 1700. Now let''s update day three. Perhaps I cheated on"},{"start":680.24,"end":686.32,"text":"my diet and I had a cookie. Well, to update a value, we''ll access our series, access the lock"},{"start":686.32,"end":696.48,"text":"property we''re locating by label. At the label of day three, we''ll add 500 calories. We''ll say"},{"start":696.48,"end":705.44,"text":"plus equals 500 to add 500. Now on day three, the total amount of calories I''ve eaten is 2200."},{"start":706.4,"end":707.84,"text":"If I were to print my series,"},{"start":708.56,"end":720,"text":"here''s what my chart looks like. 1750, 2100, 2200. Let''s delete this line of code."},{"start":721.6,"end":727.44,"text":"Now we''ll filter by value. Let''s find any days where I''ve eaten more than 2000 calories."},{"start":728.24,"end":734.48,"text":"Which days have I not followed my diet plan? We''ll access our series, use the subscript operator,"},{"start":735.04,"end":742.08,"text":"return any values within our series. That''s greater than 2000. We''ll say greater than or equal to 2000."},{"start":743.92,"end":749.68,"text":"All right, on day two, I did not stick to my diet. I had 2100 calories."},{"start":751.68,"end":758.56,"text":"Now on which days did I stick to my diet? Return any values within my series that are under 2000."},{"start":759.28,"end":768,"text":"There are two days which I followed my diet, where the calories is under 2000. Day one and day three."},{"start":768.96,"end":773.92,"text":"All right, everybody, that''s a series. It''s a panda''s one-dimensional labeled array."},{"start":773.92,"end":779.92,"text":"Think of it like a single column in a spreadsheet. Now your homework is to post a series in the"},{"start":779.92,"end":785.2,"text":"comment section down below. If you can, try and think of a unique example. All right, everybody,"},{"start":785.2,"end":787.44,"text":"and those are series using pandas."},{"start":794.24,"end":799.44,"text":"All right, let''s do this, everybody. We got to talk about data frames. In pandas, a data frame"},{"start":799.44,"end":806.24,"text":"is a tabular data structure with rows and columns. It''s two-dimensional, similar to an excel spreadsheet."},{"start":806.8,"end":812.08,"text":"Here''s a beginner-friendly way in which we can create a data frame. Let''s start with a dictionary."},{"start":812.08,"end":820.16,"text":"We''ll say data equals a dictionary. For our data, we''ll have some employees. For the key of name,"},{"start":821.04,"end":828.56,"text":"this will be a column. Instead of just having a single value, we''ll use a list, a Python list."},{"start":828.56,"end":833.28,"text":"Here we can list a few different names. I''m going to use Spongebob characters because most people"},{"start":833.28,"end":844.88,"text":"know who Spongebob is. We''ll have Spongebob, Patrick, and Squidward. Then we''ll add another column."},{"start":847.28,"end":853.68,"text":"This column will be for the age. How old is each employee? The value will be another Python list."},{"start":854.32,"end":861.12,"text":"I''m going to say that Spongebob is around 30. Patrick will be 35. Squidward will be 50."},{"start":861.76,"end":866.64,"text":"Let me do a little bit of organizing. There, that looks pretty good."},{"start":867.76,"end":873.52,"text":"Now we''re going to convert our dictionary into a data frame. Here''s how. We will assign"},{"start":873.52,"end":880.88,"text":"data frame, but most people shorten this to just DF, meaning data frame. Our data frame object"},{"start":880.88,"end":890.64,"text":"equals access pandas, spd, call the data frame constructor. Now the d is capital, not lower case."},{"start":891.28,"end":897.52,"text":"That''s because this is a constructor rather than a function. We''re going to pass in our data,"},{"start":897.52,"end":905.44,"text":"our dictionary, and then we will print our data frame, which we have named DF for short."},{"start":905.44,"end":916.64,"text":"And here''s our data frame. It''s tabular data. It''s made of rows and columns."},{"start":918.96,"end":924.16,"text":"We''re also given an index. This index has a label for each row, starting with zero."},{"start":924.8,"end":931.2,"text":"But you can set that to be something custom. To do so, when we construct a data frame object,"},{"start":931.28,"end":939.44,"text":"we will set an index by passing in a keyword argument. Index equals a Python list. We''ll say"},{"start":939.44,"end":951.84,"text":"employee one, then employee two, then employee three. And we should have some new labels. There we go."},{"start":952.56,"end":960.32,"text":"Employee one is SpongeBob H 30. Employee two is Patrick H 35. Employee three is Squidward H 50."},{"start":961.2,"end":968.88,"text":"If you need to select a single row, you can access the lock property. DF.lock subscript operator."},{"start":969.52,"end":977.68,"text":"Lock means location by label. Give me all the data for employee one. That''s the label."},{"start":978.4,"end":986.48,"text":"We are given SpongeBob H 30. Here''s the label and the data type of this row. It''s an object."},{"start":987.52,"end":995.76,"text":"Let''s select employee two. Patrick H 35. The label is employee two. The data type for this row"},{"start":995.76,"end":1004.08,"text":"is an object. And employee three. We have Squidward H 50. Employee three. Data type is an object."},{"start":1004.88,"end":1010.72,"text":"Now you can also select by integer location by using the iLock property. iLock."},{"start":1012.48,"end":1020.56,"text":"So the index zero will give you the first row, which is against SpongeBob. One is for Patrick."},{"start":1021.44,"end":1030.48,"text":"Two is for Squidward. Let''s just print the entire data frame. Now if you need to add a new column,"},{"start":1030.48,"end":1041.6,"text":"here''s how. I''ll just add a comment. Add a new column. And I''m just going to zoom out a little bit."},{"start":1042.8,"end":1048.64,"text":"To create a new column, we''ll access our data frame. Use the subscript operator. Then we''ll"},{"start":1048.64,"end":1054.4,"text":"need to think of a new column name. Let''s say job or position. What does everybody do?"},{"start":1055.04,"end":1062.16,"text":"We will assign this to be a Python list. The number of values must match the number of rows."},{"start":1062.16,"end":1069.12,"text":"We have three rows. One for SpongeBob, Patrick, and Squidward. In that order, what is the job"},{"start":1069.12,"end":1075.68,"text":"of SpongeBob? He is a cook. That''s the first value. Let''s say Patrick is a new employee."},{"start":1075.68,"end":1080.8,"text":"He doesn''t have a position quite yet. For the time being, we''ll say na for not available."},{"start":1081.12,"end":1089.28,"text":"And then Squidward is a cashier. Now let''s print our data frame. And we should have a new column."},{"start":1090.4,"end":1096.24,"text":"Employee one is a cook. Employee two, their job is not available yet. And employee three,"},{"start":1096.88,"end":1103.52,"text":"employee three is a cashier. That''s how to make a new column. Now how do we add a new row? Here''s how."},{"start":1103.6,"end":1113.2,"text":"Add a new row. An easy way to create a new row is to create a new data frame, then concatenate it."},{"start":1114,"end":1120.08,"text":"We''ll say new underscore row equals access pandas, spd,"},{"start":1120.72,"end":1127.76,"text":"call the data frame constructor again. Now we''re going to pass in a list. For this list,"},{"start":1127.76,"end":1132.88,"text":"you can add a dictionary for each new row you want to add. For example, if I need to add three rows,"},{"start":1132.88,"end":1136.96,"text":"I''ll need three dictionaries within this list. But for now, we''ll just add one."},{"start":1138.4,"end":1146.32,"text":"This dictionary needs key value pairs. For the key of name, we''ll add, let''s say Sandy."},{"start":1149.28,"end":1157.44,"text":"For the key of age, we''ll add a value of 28. Then for the key of job,"},{"start":1157.68,"end":1164,"text":"we''ll add a value of, I would say that Sandy is some sort of scientist or engineer, but we''ll just say engineer."},{"start":1165.44,"end":1172.16,"text":"This is a separate data frame. It only contains a single row, a new record for Sandy. We''re going"},{"start":1172.16,"end":1178.64,"text":"to concatenate it to our existing data frame. We will reassign our data frame, df equals"},{"start":1178.64,"end":1185.76,"text":"access pandas, spd, call the concat function for concatenate. You may see people use append, but"},{"start":1185.76,"end":1192.64,"text":"that''s now depreciated. We''ll be using concat for concatenation. We will pass in a Python list,"},{"start":1193.36,"end":1198.88,"text":"then include all of the data frames we want to concatenate. We want to include our existing"},{"start":1198.88,"end":1206.16,"text":"data frame and the new row. And then let''s print our data frame, and we should have a new row."},{"start":1206.96,"end":1214.08,"text":"Yes, we have a new row for Sandy. However, we have not set an index. The index was set to zero."},{"start":1214.08,"end":1220.4,"text":"Well, we can manually update that. When we create a new data frame, you can pass in an index as a"},{"start":1220.4,"end":1228.32,"text":"keyword argument. We''ll do that for Sandy. So comma, space, and just for readability, I''ll put this on a new line."},{"start":1228.56,"end":1235.6,"text":"Index equals a Python list with a new label for her of employee four."},{"start":1237.6,"end":1244.24,"text":"And here we go. Employee four is Sandy, age 28. Her job is an engineer."},{"start":1245.84,"end":1253.92,"text":"Now you can add more than one row. Let''s add new rows. This variable will be new"},{"start":1254.72,"end":1264.48,"text":"rows. So within our list, we can add more than one dictionary. Let''s add another row."},{"start":1265.76,"end":1268.56,"text":"I''ll do some copying and pasting just to save a little bit of time."},{"start":1269.44,"end":1273.44,"text":"Copy all the key value pairs and paste it within the new dictionary."},{"start":1274.64,"end":1279.84,"text":"Let''s say the new employee is Mr. Krabs. His first name is Eugene Krabs."},{"start":1280.48,"end":1293.44,"text":"He seems like he''s about 60. His job is that he is a manager. We''ll assign him to be employee five."},{"start":1294.56,"end":1299.68,"text":"And then we are adding new rows to our data frame. All right, let''s take a look."},{"start":1301.68,"end":1308.48,"text":"There they are. We have two new rows. One for Sandy and another for Eugene. Sandy is 28."},{"start":1308.64,"end":1315.12,"text":"Sandy is 28. She''s an engineer. Eugene is 60. He''s a manager. All right, everybody, those are data"},{"start":1315.12,"end":1323.12,"text":"frames. Data frames are a tabular data structure. They contain rows and columns. Your homework is in"},{"start":1323.12,"end":1328.56,"text":"the comment section to post the output of a data frame. Try and think of a unique example if you"},{"start":1328.56,"end":1332.32,"text":"can. And while everybody, those are data frames using pandas."},{"start":1339.2,"end":1344,"text":"Okay, let''s do this, everybody. So in this video, I''m going to show you how we can import"},{"start":1344,"end":1350.88,"text":"CSV and JSON files using pandas. You will need some data to work with. For this demonstration,"},{"start":1350.88,"end":1358.24,"text":"on my desktop, I have two files. One is a CSV file, meaning comma separated values. And the other"},{"start":1358.24,"end":1365.76,"text":"is a JSON file. .json. For this demonstration, you''ll need some data to work with. I looked online,"},{"start":1365.76,"end":1372.48,"text":"and I did find a CSV file that contains the stats for the original 150 Pokemon. For this video series,"},{"start":1372.48,"end":1377.6,"text":"I''ll be using Pokemon because many of us have grown up with Pokemon. We can relate to it. But"},{"start":1377.6,"end":1381.68,"text":"feel free to use any kind of data that you would like to work with. Just make sure that it''s in a"},{"start":1381.68,"end":1391.6,"text":"CSV format. So for my data, for number one, we have Bulbasaur all the way to number 150,"},{"start":1392.16,"end":1398.24,"text":"where we have Mewtwo. But again, the data you want to use is up to you. If you would like a copy of"},{"start":1398.24,"end":1403.92,"text":"this data, I''ll post it in the comment section on YouTube. You can just copy and paste it, like so."},{"start":1405.12,"end":1408.56,"text":"Then to create a CSV file, wherever you would like to place this file,"},{"start":1409.36,"end":1415.76,"text":"right click, go to new, text document, open it, paste your CSV data,"},{"start":1417.04,"end":1422.48,"text":"save it, then be sure you save it as a CSV file, for example, data.csv."},{"start":1425.6,"end":1430.48,"text":"Then once you have your CSV file, for convenience, I''ll move it to my Python project folder."},{"start":1432.16,"end":1437.84,"text":"My CSV file is right next to my main Python file. We''re going to create a data frame using our"},{"start":1437.84,"end":1449.12,"text":"CSV data. DF meaning data frame equals access pandas as PD, call the read underscore CSV function."},{"start":1449.92,"end":1453.44,"text":"And then we have to pass in either a relative or absolute file path."},{"start":1454.56,"end":1459.76,"text":"This file is right next to my main Python file. I just need the file name, including the extension."},{"start":1460.4,"end":1468.24,"text":"In this case, it''s data.csv. Let''s take a look at our data frame. I will print my data frame."},{"start":1469.2,"end":1475.6,"text":"And here''s what we have. I have 150 rows and seven columns."},{"start":1477.36,"end":1481.92,"text":"The data we''re outputting, it''s truncated. If you print the data frame directly,"},{"start":1481.92,"end":1486.48,"text":"you''ll be given the first five rows and the last five rows."},{"start":1487.12,"end":1491.68,"text":"Here I have the Pokemon from Bulbasaur to Charmeleon, numbers one through five,"},{"start":1491.68,"end":1497.04,"text":"and the last five, Moltres to Mewtwo, numbers 146 and 150."},{"start":1498.4,"end":1504,"text":"If you need to print all the data in your data frame, to print the entire data frame, all the rows and"},{"start":1504,"end":1510.08,"text":"columns, and not a truncated version, following our data frame, we will call the a two string"},{"start":1510.08,"end":1514.8,"text":"function. Be careful when working with a very large file. You''ll print everything."},{"start":1517.12,"end":1523.68,"text":"This file isn''t that big. We only have 150 rows. So now we display all the data for our Pokemon."},{"start":1524.96,"end":1530.96,"text":"A few of the columns include their number in the Pokedex, their name, their first type,"},{"start":1530.96,"end":1535.84,"text":"such as grass, fire, water, their second type if they have one. Bulbasaur,"},{"start":1535.84,"end":1540.56,"text":"Ivysaur, Venusaur are also a poison type, but many of them are missing a second type,"},{"start":1540.56,"end":1546.08,"text":"such as Charmander. Charmander doesn''t have a second type, so the value here is not a number,"},{"start":1546.08,"end":1553.12,"text":"NAN. There''s a height in meters, a weight in kilograms, and a legendary status, which is either"},{"start":1553.12,"end":1559.68,"text":"zero or one. If this Pokemon is not legendary, they have a legendary value of zero. If they are"},{"start":1559.68,"end":1566.64,"text":"legendary, for example Mewtwo, Mewtwo has a legendary status of one, meaning that there''s"},{"start":1566.64,"end":1574.72,"text":"only ever one Mewtwo. That''s what it means by legendary. Now to read a JSON file, here''s a"},{"start":1574.72,"end":1581.68,"text":"JSON file that contains the same data. JSON means JavaScript object notation. For entry number one,"},{"start":1581.68,"end":1589.52,"text":"we have Bulbasaur, Ivysaur, Venusaur, all the way to Mewtwo, which has a number of 150. For"},{"start":1589.52,"end":1596.16,"text":"convenience, I''ll place this JSON file within my project folder, and then to read a JSON file,"},{"start":1597.12,"end":1605.52,"text":"to read a JSON file, we will call the read JSON function, and then pass in the name of that file,"},{"start":1605.52,"end":1614.24,"text":"including the extension data.json. And here''s what we have. We have our same data again,"},{"start":1615.04,"end":1620.88,"text":"all the original 150 Pokemon. All right, that''s how we can read a file using Pandas. I couldn''t"},{"start":1620.88,"end":1626,"text":"think of any homework for you to do, so to increase engagement with this video, post the name of your"},{"start":1626,"end":1630.4,"text":"favorite Pokemon down in the comment section. All right everybody, and that is how to read both"},{"start":1630.4,"end":1642.48,"text":"CSV and JSON files using Pandas. Why hello again everybody, in this video I''m going to show you"},{"start":1642.48,"end":1648.16,"text":"different selection techniques using Pandas. In the previous lesson, we''ve loaded a CSV file."},{"start":1648.16,"end":1654.4,"text":"Here''s what my data frame looks like. My data frame contains the original 150 Pokemon, all the way"},{"start":1654.4,"end":1660.16,"text":"from Bulbasaur to Mewtwo. All right, so we have a data frame. To make a selection by column,"},{"start":1660.96,"end":1667.68,"text":"I''ll just have this as a comment, selection by column. What we''ll do is print,"},{"start":1668.56,"end":1674.08,"text":"access our data frame, use the subscript operator, then we will pass in a column name."},{"start":1675.04,"end":1682.16,"text":"We are going to pass in the name column, and here''s what we have. As a single column,"},{"start":1682.16,"end":1687.92,"text":"we have all the names, and this is actually a series. If you have a lot of data to print,"},{"start":1687.92,"end":1694.4,"text":"the default behavior for Pandas is to print the first five rows and the last five rows. What you"},{"start":1694.4,"end":1700.24,"text":"see here is a truncated version. If you need to print the entire thing, follow this with the"},{"start":1700.24,"end":1705.36,"text":"two string function. Do be careful if you have a lot of data you''re working with."},{"start":1707.12,"end":1711.44,"text":"And here are the names of the original 150 Pokemon."},{"start":1712.72,"end":1714.88,"text":"Let''s say we need the height, the height column."},{"start":1717.2,"end":1722.8,"text":"Well, I''m going to do a search for height. I will place that within the subscript operator."},{"start":1724.88,"end":1729.28,"text":"And here''s the height of every Pokemon in meters, or the weight."},{"start":1733.36,"end":1735.52,"text":"We are searching for the column of weight."},{"start":1735.6,"end":1743.36,"text":"And here are all the weights. This one''s heavy, whatever it is. I think that''s Venusaur."},{"start":1743.92,"end":1751.28,"text":"100 kilograms. Now to select multiple columns, we are going to print, access our data frame,"},{"start":1751.28,"end":1757.36,"text":"then within the subscript operator, we''ll pass in a Python list. A list of all the columns we"},{"start":1757.36,"end":1766.56,"text":"would like to output. Let''s output the name column, the height column, and the weight."},{"start":1773.04,"end":1779.68,"text":"We have three columns, the name, the height, and the weight. Then to display all the data,"},{"start":1779.68,"end":1785.12,"text":"all the rows, you can follow this with the two string function. Two string."},{"start":1787.68,"end":1795.2,"text":"And we get all the rows. And these three specific columns, name, height, weight."},{"start":1796.16,"end":1798.16,"text":"All right, that is selection by column."},{"start":1802.24,"end":1808.88,"text":"Now we''ll make a selection by row, or rows. Let''s take a look at our data frame."},{"start":1808.88,"end":1817.36,"text":"I''m going to print my data frame. Each of these rows has a label. The default"},{"start":1817.36,"end":1822.24,"text":"behavior for pandas is to give each row a number for the label, starting with zero."},{"start":1822.24,"end":1828.72,"text":"They''re in ascending order. Well, we can access the lock property, then pass in a label."},{"start":1829.92,"end":1834.96,"text":"So since I didn''t set a label for each of these rows, zero would correspond with the first row,"},{"start":1834.96,"end":1844.4,"text":"where we have Bulbasaur. One would be Ivysaur. But optionally, what you could do,"},{"start":1845.76,"end":1851.44,"text":"I can set one of the columns to serve as the index, so that you can access one of the names"},{"start":1851.44,"end":1857.44,"text":"by label using the lock property. You''re probably not going to remember which Pokemon is 145,"},{"start":1857.44,"end":1863.68,"text":"but you''ll remember it by its name. So it''s easier to look up. So what you could do is that when we"},{"start":1863.68,"end":1870.56,"text":"read our CSV file, we can pass in a second argument, a keyword argument, index underscore"},{"start":1870.56,"end":1877.84,"text":"C-O-L, meaning column, index column equals name. Then let''s take a look at our data frame."},{"start":1881.2,"end":1886.8,"text":"Now we''re setting the label of each row to be the Pokemon''s name. We can do a search by name"},{"start":1886.8,"end":1893.28,"text":"pretty easily. So to set that up, you just pass in a keyword argument of index column, index call,"},{"start":1893.28,"end":1899.12,"text":"for short, then set which column you would like to serve as the index. So then when we access"},{"start":1899.12,"end":1905.76,"text":"our data frame, we will access the lock property, meaning location by label. Then let''s do a search"},{"start":1905.76,"end":1913.04,"text":"for Pikachu. We''ll pass in a string of Pikachu. And here''s all the data for Pikachu. Pikachu is"},{"start":1913.04,"end":1920.4,"text":"number 25. Type one is electric. Pikachu doesn''t have a second type. That''s NAN, not a number."},{"start":1920.4,"end":1926.4,"text":"The height of Pikachu is 0.4 meters. Weight, 6 kilograms. Pikachu is not a legendary Pokemon."},{"start":1927.04,"end":1931.12,"text":"Here you have the name and the data type of what Pikachu is. It''s an object."},{"start":1932.48,"end":1941.04,"text":"All right, let''s do a search for Charizard. Charizard. And here''s Charizard. Charizard is"},{"start":1941.04,"end":1948.32,"text":"number six. Type one is fire. Type two is flying. Height, 1.7 meters. Weight, 90.5 kilograms."},{"start":1948.32,"end":1954.64,"text":"Not legendary. If you don''t want all the data when displaying your row, when locating by label,"},{"start":1955.36,"end":1960.48,"text":"we could pass in a second argument. We could pass in a pipe on list of all the columns we would"},{"start":1960.48,"end":1972.64,"text":"like to select. So with Charizard, I would just like the height and the weight. So we will pass in"},{"start":1972.64,"end":1977.04,"text":"a pipe on list as the second argument that contains the columns we would like to display."},{"start":1978.56,"end":1983.52,"text":"There we go. With Charizard, we only have the height and the weight, those two columns."},{"start":1984.88,"end":1990.4,"text":"Now you also can select a range of rows as well. After the Pokemon''s name, you''re going to use the"},{"start":1990.4,"end":1998.64,"text":"slice operator, which is a colon. Give me everything between Charizard and let''s say Blastoise."},{"start":2000.32,"end":2007.6,"text":"Blastoise. There we go. We have Charizard, Squirtle, War Tortle, Blastoise."},{"start":2008.64,"end":2014.96,"text":"You can also use Integer-based indexing if you so choose. We''re going to print,"},{"start":2015.6,"end":2020,"text":"access our data frame, access by integer location."},{"start":2022.8,"end":2029.92,"text":"Let''s say you need the first 10. You would pass in those indices. 0, colon, 11. Remember that the"},{"start":2029.92,"end":2036.56,"text":"second number is exclusive. You would then be given the first 10 rows between Bulbasaur"},{"start":2037.44,"end":2043.6,"text":"and Metapod. Maybe you need every second row, then add a step of two."},{"start":2045.2,"end":2049.28,"text":"Now we''re given every second row. You can see that the number is going up by two."},{"start":2050.24,"end":2055.2,"text":"As a second argument, you can select the indices of which columns you would like."},{"start":2055.2,"end":2063.68,"text":"I would like the first three columns, 0, 3. With the range of 10 indices that I''ve selected,"},{"start":2063.68,"end":2068.96,"text":"I specified I would only like the first three columns. Besides our index with all of our"},{"start":2068.96,"end":2074.48,"text":"unique labels, we have the first three columns, each Pokemon''s number in the Pokedex,"},{"start":2074.48,"end":2077.04,"text":"their first type, and their second type if they have one."},{"start":2079.04,"end":2084.48,"text":"All right, now we''ll go over an exercise. We''ll have a user type in the name of a Pokemon,"},{"start":2084.48,"end":2088.48,"text":"and then do a search for it. We''ll create a variable of Pokemon,"},{"start":2089.28,"end":2097.12,"text":"equals, call the input function to ask for some user input, enter a Pokemon name."},{"start":2100.16,"end":2104.96,"text":"Using this technique, if the Pokemon''s name doesn''t exist, it''s going to cause a key error."},{"start":2106.32,"end":2114.8,"text":"Using a tri block, we will try and print, access our data frame, access the location property,"},{"start":2115.76,"end":2119.68,"text":"then instead of placing a string here with Pokemon''s name, such as Pikachu,"},{"start":2120.56,"end":2126.48,"text":"we''ll place in the string variable of Pokemon. We''ll do a search for whatever the user types in."},{"start":2127.68,"end":2133.04,"text":"Now, if that Pokemon doesn''t exist, we will catch an exception if it happens."},{"start":2133.28,"end":2145.12,"text":"Accept key error, where we will print, I''ll use enough string, we''ll say that Pokemon''s name,"},{"start":2146.48,"end":2152.16,"text":"Pokemon not found. And now we can do a search for a Pokemon. Let''s test it."},{"start":2153.04,"end":2157.52,"text":"Enter a Pokemon name, I''ll type in Pikachu, make sure that the first letter is capital,"},{"start":2158.48,"end":2164.72,"text":"and here''s the stats for Pikachu. Let''s do a search for Snorlax,"},{"start":2168.48,"end":2173.36,"text":"and here''s the stats for Snorlax. What if there''s a Pokemon that doesn''t exist, like"},{"start":2174.4,"end":2182.16,"text":"whatever that is? Well, this Pokemon was not found. I couldn''t think of any homework for you to do,"},{"start":2182.16,"end":2187.36,"text":"so let me know what your favorite non-coding hobby is. Post it down in the comment section."},{"start":2187.76,"end":2189.76,"text":"And that is selection using pandas."},{"start":2196.72,"end":2201.2,"text":"Hey, what''s going on everybody? I''m going to explain filtering using pandas. If I could"},{"start":2201.2,"end":2207.28,"text":"summarize what filtering is, it''s basically keeping the rows that match a condition when"},{"start":2207.28,"end":2212.08,"text":"working with the data frame. In the previous lessons, we''ve been working with the data frame"},{"start":2212.08,"end":2217.2,"text":"that contains the original 150 Pokemon. Make sure that you have some data to work with before"},{"start":2217.2,"end":2222.72,"text":"starting this lesson. Let''s say I would like to create a new data frame and filter any Pokemon"},{"start":2222.72,"end":2228.88,"text":"that have a height above two meters. We would have to access this height column and return any rows"},{"start":2228.88,"end":2235.12,"text":"where the height is two meters or above. Here''s how we can do that. Let''s create a new data frame."},{"start":2235.12,"end":2243.76,"text":"We''ll call it tall Pokemon equals, we will access our data frame, use the subscript operator,"},{"start":2243.76,"end":2249.04,"text":"let me zoom in a little bit. We''re going to return a series, access our data frame,"},{"start":2249.76,"end":2257.76,"text":"use the subscript operator. We will select the column of height. Then we will write a condition,"},{"start":2258.64,"end":2267.6,"text":"return any rows where the height is greater than or equal to two. And then we will output our new"},{"start":2267.6,"end":2275.36,"text":"data frame, tall Pokemon. And here''s what we have. We have filtered out any Pokemon that have less"},{"start":2275.36,"end":2279.84,"text":"than two meters for height. You can see that with the height column, all the heights are two meters"},{"start":2279.84,"end":2285.76,"text":"or above. So really with filtering, we''re just keeping the rows that match condition."},{"start":2286.88,"end":2290.32,"text":"Let''s apply another filter. Let''s say heavy Pokemon."},{"start":2290.72,"end":2301.12,"text":"Heavy Pokemon equals, access our data frame, use the subscript operator, we will select the column"},{"start":2301.12,"end":2308,"text":"of weight. Access our data frame, subscript operator, we will select the column of weight."},{"start":2310,"end":2315.44,"text":"Return any Pokemon that have a weight that''s greater than, let''s say greater than 100."},{"start":2315.52,"end":2325.44,"text":"And then we will print our heavy Pokemon, that new data frame. And here we go. We''ve returned all the"},{"start":2325.44,"end":2335.2,"text":"rows where the weight is over 100. Now let''s return any Pokemon that are legendary. If a Pokemon is"},{"start":2335.2,"end":2345.36,"text":"not legendary, this value is zero. If it is legendary, it''s one. We''re creating a data frame of legend"},{"start":2345.52,"end":2354.8,"text":"dairy Pokemon equals access our data frame, use the subscript operator, we will select the column"},{"start":2355.44,"end":2362.4,"text":"of legendary. Now I set this equal to be one if it is legendary."},{"start":2365.52,"end":2372.24,"text":"We have four legendary Pokemon, Articuno, Zapdos, Moltres, Mewtwo. Now what you could do for"},{"start":2372.24,"end":2381.04,"text":"readability, the Boolean value of true also equals one. That would work too. If your CSV data"},{"start":2381.04,"end":2387.36,"text":"contains Booleans, mine doesn''t. You don''t necessarily need double equals true, that''s redundant."},{"start":2388.16,"end":2393.04,"text":"Since my original CSV data contains zeros and ones, I would need that double equals."},{"start":2393.04,"end":2404,"text":"Let''s find any water Pokemon. Water Pokemon equals access our data frame, subscript operator."},{"start":2405.36,"end":2414.16,"text":"We will select the column of type one. If type one is equal a string of water,"},{"start":2414.96,"end":2422.32,"text":"then we will return any water Pokemon. Now this is only for type one. We have Squirtle all the way"},{"start":2422.4,"end":2430.08,"text":"down to Vaporeon. But what if their second type is water and not their first type? Well we could"},{"start":2430.08,"end":2435.52,"text":"use the OR logical operator. If you''re going to use a logical operator, be sure to enclose your"},{"start":2435.52,"end":2442.64,"text":"first condition within a set of parentheses. With the OR logical operator, this is a C style"},{"start":2442.64,"end":2449.84,"text":"operator. With Python it would be OR, but we''re going to be using the C style operator which"},{"start":2449.84,"end":2457.28,"text":"is a vertical bar for OR. We''ll write another condition, access our data frame, select the"},{"start":2457.28,"end":2468.56,"text":"column of type two, where the second type is equal to water. If the first type is water or the second"},{"start":2468.56,"end":2477.36,"text":"type is water, return that row. See we have more rows. There''s a few Pokemon that have a first"},{"start":2477.36,"end":2484.16,"text":"type that''s not water, but their second type is water. Now we''ll use the AND logical operator."},{"start":2486.32,"end":2492.8,"text":"Let''s find any Pokemon that are fire and flying. We''ll name this new data frame just FF for short,"},{"start":2492.8,"end":2500.32,"text":"fire flying. Fire flying Pokemon equals access our data frame. We''ll do a search for any fire"},{"start":2500.32,"end":2510.08,"text":"Pokemon. Select the column of type one, check to see if that''s equal to a string of fire."},{"start":2511.04,"end":2517.76,"text":"Let''s see what we have currently. Here''s all the fire Pokemon, starting with Charmander,"},{"start":2517.76,"end":2525.52,"text":"all the way to Maltrace. Now we''ll see if their second type is flying. We''ll be using a C style"},{"start":2525.52,"end":2530.8,"text":"AND logical operator, which is an ampersand. Be sure you''re not using the Python AND."},{"start":2532.56,"end":2536.64,"text":"If we''re using a logical operator, enclose your conditions within a set of parentheses."},{"start":2538.4,"end":2544.8,"text":"Now for my second condition, access our data frame, subscript operator, select the column"},{"start":2544.8,"end":2550.4,"text":"of type two. Let''s check to see if type two is equal to flying."},{"start":2550.72,"end":2560.48,"text":"Now we''re returning any fire and flying Pokemon. And there''s two, Charizard and Maltrace. Their"},{"start":2560.48,"end":2567.76,"text":"type one is fire, their type two is flying. Alright everybody, that is filtering. Basically,"},{"start":2567.76,"end":2573.36,"text":"you''re keeping the rows that match a condition. For your homework to help increase engagement"},{"start":2573.36,"end":2578.24,"text":"with this video, in the comments section post a data frame where you search for two different types."},{"start":2578.8,"end":2583.04,"text":"Try and pick some different types that we haven''t used yet. And while everybody that is filtering,"},{"start":2583.04,"end":2594.56,"text":"using pandas. In this video, I''m going to explain aggregate functions using pandas."},{"start":2594.56,"end":2601.36,"text":"Aggregate functions, they reduce a set of values into a single summary value. Basically,"},{"start":2601.36,"end":2607.84,"text":"we''re reducing a bunch of values into one. We use aggregate functions to summarize and analyze data."},{"start":2607.84,"end":2613.44,"text":"In this demonstration, I have a data frame that contains the original 150 Pokemon. Let''s say"},{"start":2613.44,"end":2619.36,"text":"for some of these columns, such as the number, the height, the weight, and legendary status,"},{"start":2619.36,"end":2624.24,"text":"I would like to find the mean or the average. To find the mean for all numeric columns,"},{"start":2624.24,"end":2631.04,"text":"we can do the following. When we output our data frame, we will call the mean aggregate function."},{"start":2631.04,"end":2637.52,"text":"But there''s one thing we''re missing. We can''t use the mean function on any columns that are"},{"start":2637.52,"end":2643.28,"text":"non numeric. We can''t find the mean for anything that''s non numeric, such as Pokemon names."},{"start":2644.08,"end":2649.44,"text":"They''re alphabetical characters. What we could do is that when we call the mean function,"},{"start":2649.44,"end":2656.64,"text":"we can pass in a keyword argument numeric underscore only equals true."},{"start":2658.32,"end":2664.32,"text":"We''re telling pandas find the mean of any columns that are numeric. And here''s what we have."},{"start":2665.2,"end":2673.84,"text":"The average number is 75.5. The average height is 1.2 meters. The average weight is 46.2 kilograms."},{"start":2673.84,"end":2683.28,"text":"The average amount of legendaries is 0.02, 2%. So we have mean. Let''s do some copying and pasting."},{"start":2684.32,"end":2691.76,"text":"Another aggregate function is sum. Let''s sum all the numeric columns. And here''s the sum,"},{"start":2691.76,"end":2696.4,"text":"the sum of all the numbers, the sum of all the heights, the sum of all the weights,"},{"start":2696.4,"end":2701.28,"text":"and the sum of the numbers of all the legendaries. Let''s find the minimum."},{"start":2703.52,"end":2711.6,"text":"We will use the mean aggregate function. The minimum number is 1. The minimum height is 0.2 meters."},{"start":2711.6,"end":2718.24,"text":"The minimum weight is 0.1 kilograms. And the minimum legendary status is 0. Then we have max."},{"start":2718.56,"end":2723.12,"text":"We will call the max aggregate function."},{"start":2725.52,"end":2734.64,"text":"Here are the max values 150, 8.8, 460, 1. We also have count."},{"start":2738.48,"end":2741.04,"text":"With the count function, we don''t need to pass in a keyword argument."},{"start":2742.08,"end":2747.44,"text":"We are counting the number of values within each column, 150, 150, 150."},{"start":2747.44,"end":2754.4,"text":"Now, not every Pokemon has a type 2. That''s why this is only 67. Count won''t include any null values."},{"start":2754.4,"end":2757.68,"text":"That''s why this number is 67, and the rest is 150."},{"start":2760.48,"end":2765.76,"text":"That''s using aggregate functions with an entire data frame. These aggregate functions would apply"},{"start":2765.76,"end":2773.04,"text":"to the whole data frame. The next set of aggregate functions will be for a single column."},{"start":2774,"end":2777.28,"text":"Alright, just to save a little bit of time, let''s do some copying and pasting."},{"start":2777.92,"end":2780.88,"text":"We''ll copy our five previous print statements and paste them."},{"start":2782.8,"end":2786.96,"text":"Now, rather than selecting the entire data frame, we will select a single column"},{"start":2787.68,"end":2792.4,"text":"by using the subscript operator. Then selecting a column. Let''s pick height."},{"start":2793.6,"end":2798.24,"text":"What is the average height? Since height is a numeric column, we don''t have to pass in this"},{"start":2798.24,"end":2806,"text":"keyword argument. What is the mean of the height column? That is 1.2, 1.2 meters."},{"start":2807.68,"end":2814,"text":"Then let''s do this with sum. Subscript operator. Select the column of height,"},{"start":2814,"end":2820.24,"text":"and we don''t need to pass in that keyword argument. What is the sum of all the heights? 180 meters."},{"start":2821.84,"end":2827.84,"text":"Then let''s do this with min. What is the minimum value? What is the minimum height in this column?"},{"start":2828.8,"end":2832.72,"text":"That is 0.2 meters."},{"start":2835.52,"end":2838.24,"text":"Subscript operator. We will select the column of height,"},{"start":2838.88,"end":2840.96,"text":"and we don''t need to pass in this keyword argument."},{"start":2842.08,"end":2845.76,"text":"With our column of height, the maximum value is 8.8 meters."},{"start":2847.12,"end":2854.16,"text":"And what''s the count? Select our column of height, and the count"},{"start":2854.48,"end":2863.52,"text":"is 150. That''s 150 non-null values. But if I was to pick a different column, like type 2,"},{"start":2864.4,"end":2870.16,"text":"well, if we remember, that was only 67. All right, that''s how to use aggregate functions"},{"start":2870.16,"end":2875.6,"text":"with a single column. Select your data frame, then select the column using the subscript operator."},{"start":2876.72,"end":2881.28,"text":"Now there''s also something called group by. Group by is a function."},{"start":2881.52,"end":2886.56,"text":"Now if I was to print my data frame, I will print my data frame."},{"start":2888.08,"end":2892.8,"text":"We can arrange our data frame into different groups. We can group together rows by something"},{"start":2892.8,"end":2898,"text":"that they have in common. Let''s group our data frame by each creature''s type, their type 1."},{"start":2898.56,"end":2903.68,"text":"We''ll put all the grass types in one group, all the fire types in another group,"},{"start":2903.68,"end":2905.2,"text":"and we''ll do this with all the different types."},{"start":2905.2,"end":2916.32,"text":"We will do this by creating a group by object. Group equals, access our data frame,"},{"start":2916.32,"end":2922,"text":"call the group by function. Then we''re going to pass in the name of a column"},{"start":2922,"end":2927.52,"text":"by which we want to group these records by. We''ll group by type 1."},{"start":2928.8,"end":2932.88,"text":"Now if you were to output your group directly, here''s what you would see."},{"start":2936,"end":2940.4,"text":"Group is an object. When you apply an aggregate function,"},{"start":2940.4,"end":2943.92,"text":"the group object will return a series for you to work with in display."},{"start":2944.56,"end":2950.72,"text":"Let''s take our group, select the height column, then call an aggregate function."},{"start":2951.36,"end":2958,"text":"What is the average height for each group? And we are grouping by type 1."},{"start":2959.44,"end":2964.88,"text":"Here''s what we have. Here are the average heights. For bug types, the average height is 0.9 meters."},{"start":2965.44,"end":2972,"text":"Dragon types have an average height of 2.6. So we are grouping by each Pokemon''s type,"},{"start":2972,"end":2972.88,"text":"their type 1."},{"start":2976,"end":2981.28,"text":"Let''s find the sum. We are grouping by type 1. Let''s find the sum."},{"start":2984.08,"end":2987.68,"text":"All of the bug types have a combined height of 10.8 meters."},{"start":2988.32,"end":2991.28,"text":"All the dragon types have a combined height of 8 meters."},{"start":2992.24,"end":2994.72,"text":"It seems like water types have the greatest combined height."},{"start":2998.16,"end":3003.52,"text":"Let''s find the minimum value from each type. We will call the min function."},{"start":3005.36,"end":3009.28,"text":"And here''s the minimum values for each type. Or the max."},{"start":3017.36,"end":3019.52,"text":"Here are all the max values for each type."},{"start":3022.24,"end":3023.36,"text":"And the count."},{"start":3030,"end":3036.64,"text":"Here''s the total number of bug types, 12. Dragon types, 3. Electric types, 9. So on and so forth."},{"start":3037.76,"end":3039.36,"text":"There''s a lot of water types I noticed."},{"start":3041.68,"end":3044.16,"text":"Alright everybody, so those are aggregate functions."},{"start":3044.8,"end":3048.88,"text":"They reduce a set of values into a single summary value."},{"start":3049.44,"end":3054.72,"text":"They''re used to summarize and analyze data. And while everybody, those are aggregate functions"},{"start":3054.72,"end":3055.6,"text":"using pandas."},{"start":3059.92,"end":3064.88,"text":"Guess what? It''s me again. So today I''m going to explain data cleaning using pandas."},{"start":3064.88,"end":3071.84,"text":"Data cleaning is the process of fixing or removing incomplete, incorrect, or irrelevant data."},{"start":3071.84,"end":3077.68,"text":"Approximately 75% of the work that is done with pandas is specifically for data cleaning."},{"start":3077.68,"end":3083.52,"text":"You do a lot of it. In this demonstration, I have a data frame that contains the original 150"},{"start":3083.52,"end":3087.92,"text":"Pokemon. Now let''s say you would like to drop a column because it''s not relevant."},{"start":3088.72,"end":3092.08,"text":"We''re going to take our data frame, call the drop function."},{"start":3092.96,"end":3098.88,"text":"As a keyword argument, we''re going to pass in columns equals, then within a Python list,"},{"start":3098.88,"end":3104.32,"text":"you can list all the columns you would like to drop. I would like to drop that column of legendary."},{"start":3105.28,"end":3110.16,"text":"This function of drop does return a new data frame. So we''re going to reassign our current data frame."},{"start":3111.04,"end":3116,"text":"Data frame equals, then call the drop function of the previous data frame."},{"start":3116.72,"end":3120.4,"text":"And let''s take a look. We should be missing that column, which we are."},{"start":3121.2,"end":3122.56,"text":"Now let''s say you don''t want the number."},{"start":3123.92,"end":3128.16,"text":"Well, we can add that to the Python list. Drop, I think it was NO."},{"start":3130.96,"end":3133.44,"text":"Yes, that column is also gone."},{"start":3134.8,"end":3139.76,"text":"That''s how to drop irrelevant columns. Here''s how to handle missing data."},{"start":3140.88,"end":3145.44,"text":"In my data frame, there are many Pokemon that don''t have a second type,"},{"start":3145.44,"end":3150.88,"text":"but all Pokemon do have a first type. For example, Charmander. Charmander is a fire type."},{"start":3151.52,"end":3155.68,"text":"But Charmander doesn''t have a second type. It''s a pure fire type."},{"start":3156.48,"end":3161.52,"text":"If a row is missing a value within type two, we''re going to drop that entire row."},{"start":3161.52,"end":3165.12,"text":"Here''s how to do that. We''re going to reassign our data frame,"},{"start":3166.48,"end":3170.8,"text":"access our data frame, call the drop NA method."},{"start":3172.96,"end":3178.4,"text":"We''re going to pass on a keyword argument of subset equals a Python list."},{"start":3179.2,"end":3184.24,"text":"Any columns we place within this list will drop those rows if they''re missing a value."},{"start":3185.76,"end":3189.36,"text":"Within type two, drop any rows that are missing a value."},{"start":3190.24,"end":3194.4,"text":"When I display my data frame, I''m going to call the two string function just so we can see the whole thing."},{"start":3194.4,"end":3197.92,"text":"Two string function."},{"start":3200.64,"end":3204.4,"text":"There should be no rows for Pokemon that are missing type two."},{"start":3204.4,"end":3210.08,"text":"You can see that they''re numbered here. One, two, three, we go to six because four through five are missing."},{"start":3210.08,"end":3213.2,"text":"And then we jump up to 12 where we have Butterfree."},{"start":3213.2,"end":3217.44,"text":"We have removed any rows where there are null values within type two."},{"start":3218.16,"end":3222.32,"text":"In place of dropping any rows where the values are not available,"},{"start":3222.32,"end":3225.12,"text":"let''s replace them instead with a different function."},{"start":3225.12,"end":3233.92,"text":"We will reassign our data frame, data frame equals, access our data frame, call the fillNA function."},{"start":3233.92,"end":3237.04,"text":"Fill any not available values."},{"start":3237.04,"end":3240.64,"text":"Within this function, we''re going to pass on a dictionary."},{"start":3240.64,"end":3244.64,"text":"Within this dictionary, we''ll select a column. We''ll select a column."},{"start":3244.64,"end":3248.4,"text":"Within this dictionary, we''ll select a column. We''ll select type two again."},{"start":3251.36,"end":3257.84,"text":"Replace any not available values within the column of type two with the following value."},{"start":3257.84,"end":3263.2,"text":"Instead of not a number, NAN, we''ll replace those values with none."},{"start":3264.64,"end":3265.68,"text":"And let''s take a look."},{"start":3270.32,"end":3273.2,"text":"For type two, for any Pokemon that don''t have a second type,"},{"start":3273.84,"end":3278.56,"text":"we''ve replaced any missing values such as not a number with the word none."},{"start":3280.24,"end":3282.32,"text":"That''s how to replace any missing values."},{"start":3284.4,"end":3287.84,"text":"Number three, we''re going to fix any inconsistent values."},{"start":3289.76,"end":3292.8,"text":"We can replace any instance of a value with another one."},{"start":3293.6,"end":3296.72,"text":"Within type one, let''s select any grass types."},{"start":3296.72,"end":3300.08,"text":"We''ll change any instance of grass to be all uppercase letters."},{"start":3300.72,"end":3303.92,"text":"Here''s how you can do that. We''re going to take our data frame,"},{"start":3304.48,"end":3308.08,"text":"then select a column. Within the column of type one,"},{"start":3309.36,"end":3312.56,"text":"this will be a series that we''re selecting. We''re going to"},{"start":3313.28,"end":3318.72,"text":"access that column using the subscript operator. We are selecting the column of type one."},{"start":3320.16,"end":3324.48,"text":"Call the replace function, and then we will pass in a dictionary."},{"start":3325.2,"end":3329.6,"text":"Let''s replace any instance of grass with the following value."},{"start":3329.6,"end":3333.12,"text":"This is a dictionary. We need a colon, then space."},{"start":3333.12,"end":3337.84,"text":"We''ll replace grass with all capital grass to test it."},{"start":3338.72,"end":3342.96,"text":"And that should replace any instance of grass within type one."},{"start":3343.92,"end":3347.28,"text":"There we are. Let''s find a few more."},{"start":3349.76,"end":3353.2,"text":"There''s more grass types, oddish, gloom, vile, plume."},{"start":3353.76,"end":3356.4,"text":"This won''t change any instance of grass for type two,"},{"start":3356.4,"end":3358.56,"text":"because we''ve only selected the type one column."},{"start":3359.84,"end":3362.48,"text":"Let''s change a few more. Within our dictionary,"},{"start":3362.48,"end":3364.88,"text":"we can pass in more than one key value pair."},{"start":3364.88,"end":3370.48,"text":"Let''s replace any instance of fire with fire all caps."},{"start":3372.48,"end":3373.92,"text":"Let''s do the same with water."},{"start":3374.8,"end":3379.76,"text":"Replace any instance of water within type one with water all uppercase."},{"start":3380.48,"end":3381.76,"text":"Yeah, it looks good."},{"start":3381.76,"end":3383.36,"text":"Grass is all uppercase."},{"start":3383.36,"end":3385.2,"text":"Fire is all uppercase."},{"start":3386.48,"end":3388.24,"text":"Water is all uppercase."},{"start":3389.84,"end":3391.92,"text":"No other types are all uppercase."},{"start":3391.92,"end":3393.92,"text":"They''re capitalized normally."},{"start":3396.16,"end":3396.96,"text":"Moving on."},{"start":3397.76,"end":3399.68,"text":"We can standardize text."},{"start":3399.68,"end":3402.64,"text":"Just to demonstrate, within our name column,"},{"start":3403.44,"end":3406.64,"text":"let''s take all the individual names of the names of the names."},{"start":3406.64,"end":3410.32,"text":"Within our name column, let''s take all the individual names"},{"start":3410.32,"end":3411.84,"text":"and make them lowercase."},{"start":3411.84,"end":3412.8,"text":"Here''s how you can do that."},{"start":3414.24,"end":3416.08,"text":"We will select the column of name."},{"start":3416.64,"end":3420.4,"text":"DataFrame subscript operator, we are selecting the column of name."},{"start":3420.4,"end":3421.28,"text":"This is a series."},{"start":3421.84,"end":3422.4,"text":"Equals."},{"start":3423.2,"end":3424.4,"text":"Select that column again."},{"start":3424.96,"end":3428.08,"text":"DataFrame subscript operator, we are selecting name."},{"start":3428.72,"end":3429.44,"text":"That series."},{"start":3430.88,"end":3432,"text":"Access string."},{"start":3432.96,"end":3434.8,"text":"Call the lower function."},{"start":3434.8,"end":3436.96,"text":"And that''s going to take our column of name"},{"start":3437.6,"end":3439.84,"text":"and make all of the characters lowercase."},{"start":3441.44,"end":3443.44,"text":"So that''s how you can standardize some text."},{"start":3444.48,"end":3447.92,"text":"Number five, I''m going to show you how we can fix or change data types."},{"start":3448.96,"end":3454.48,"text":"With my column of legendary, non-legendary Pokemon have a value of zero."},{"start":3454.48,"end":3456.8,"text":"Legendary Pokemon have a value of one."},{"start":3457.6,"end":3459.84,"text":"I think Booleans would make more sense to use."},{"start":3460.48,"end":3462.88,"text":"We''ll change these values to be Booleans."},{"start":3462.88,"end":3463.44,"text":"Here''s how."},{"start":3464.32,"end":3465.36,"text":"We''ll select a column."},{"start":3466,"end":3467.36,"text":"Access our data frame."},{"start":3467.36,"end":3468.72,"text":"Subscript operator."},{"start":3468.72,"end":3470.8,"text":"Select the column of legendary."},{"start":3471.6,"end":3472.48,"text":"This is a series."},{"start":3473.04,"end":3474.56,"text":"We''re going to reassign it."},{"start":3474.56,"end":3476.16,"text":"Access that column again."},{"start":3476.16,"end":3477.84,"text":"DataFrame subscript operator."},{"start":3478.56,"end":3479.52,"text":"Legendary."},{"start":3479.52,"end":3481.44,"text":"And I''m just going to copy this because I''m lazy."},{"start":3482.64,"end":3485.52,"text":"We''ll call the as type function."},{"start":3485.52,"end":3487.44,"text":"And then pass in a new data type."},{"start":3487.44,"end":3489.28,"text":"For Booleans, you type bool."},{"start":3490.24,"end":3493.36,"text":"And now for the legendary status, it should all be Booleans."},{"start":3494.4,"end":3496.72,"text":"Dritini, Dragonair, Dragonite."},{"start":3496.72,"end":3498.48,"text":"They''re not legendary Pokemon."},{"start":3498.48,"end":3499.44,"text":"That''s false."},{"start":3499.44,"end":3501.92,"text":"But Mewtwo is a legendary Pokemon."},{"start":3501.92,"end":3502.56,"text":"That''s true."},{"start":3503.2,"end":3506.32,"text":"Same thing applies to Articuno, Zavdos, Miltrace."},{"start":3508.88,"end":3510.72,"text":"Here''s how to remove duplicate values."},{"start":3512.08,"end":3513.6,"text":"Going to our CSV data."},{"start":3514.32,"end":3516.72,"text":"Let''s add a few extra copies of Pokemon."},{"start":3516.72,"end":3518.8,"text":"Let''s add a few more copies of Bulbasaur."},{"start":3520.16,"end":3520.88,"text":"I don''t know."},{"start":3520.88,"end":3522,"text":"A total of four is good."},{"start":3522.96,"end":3525.2,"text":"And then a couple for Mewtwo."},{"start":3528.16,"end":3529.6,"text":"We have duplicate entries."},{"start":3532.72,"end":3535.76,"text":"Let''s print our data frame just to be sure that we do have the duplicates."},{"start":3537.2,"end":3539.52,"text":"Yeah, we got four entries for Bulbasaur."},{"start":3540.8,"end":3544.8,"text":"And then at the bottom, we have three entries for Mewtwo."},{"start":3545.92,"end":3549.76,"text":"To remove any duplicate values, we will reassign our data frame."},{"start":3549.76,"end":3555.36,"text":"Data frame equals access our data frame called the drop duplicates function."},{"start":3556.96,"end":3557.84,"text":"Duplicates."},{"start":3559.04,"end":3560.08,"text":"And that''s all you got to do."},{"start":3561.36,"end":3563.52,"text":"And now we should be missing those extra entries."},{"start":3564.16,"end":3565.68,"text":"Yeah, there''s only one Bulbasaur."},{"start":3566.88,"end":3568.16,"text":"And there''s only one Mewtwo."},{"start":3569.52,"end":3570.16,"text":"All right, everybody."},{"start":3570.16,"end":3571.6,"text":"So that is data cleaning."},{"start":3571.6,"end":3578.16,"text":"It''s the process of fixing or removing incomplete, incorrect, or irrelevant data."},{"start":3578.24,"end":3582.56,"text":"On average, 75% of the work done in Pandas is data cleaning."},{"start":3582.56,"end":3584.08,"text":"It''s an important topic."},{"start":3584.08,"end":3586.4,"text":"I couldn''t really think of any homework for you to do."},{"start":3586.4,"end":3588.56,"text":"So to increase engagement with this video,"},{"start":3588.56,"end":3591.36,"text":"I don''t know, post your favorite anime in the comment section."},{"start":3592,"end":3595.36,"text":"And while everybody, that is data cleaning using Pandas."}]'::jsonb
) AS segment
WHERE l.youtube_video_id = 'VXtjG_GzO7Q';

