INSERT INTO transcript_chunks (lesson_id, chunk_text, start_time, end_time)
SELECT
    l.id AS lesson_id,
    segment.value->>'text' AS chunk_text,
    (segment.value->>'start')::numeric AS start_time,
    (segment.value->>'end')::numeric AS end_time
FROM lessons l
CROSS JOIN jsonb_array_elements(
    '[{"start":0,"end":5.6,"text":"Well, hello everybody. Today I will be explaining a few different types of collections in Python."},{"start":5.6,"end":11.2,"text":"There''s four general purpose collections. Three of them are lists, sets, and tuples."},{"start":11.2,"end":15.44,"text":"There are also dictionaries, but I''ll save that for the next topic because they can be kind of"},{"start":15.44,"end":21.52,"text":"tricky. A collection, I would think of them as a single variable, and I''m saying that within quotes,"},{"start":21.52,"end":27.12,"text":"that is used to store multiple values. That''s how I would explain a collection to a beginner."},{"start":27.12,"end":33.68,"text":"For example, let''s say we have a variable, variable fruit, fruit equals some value, like apple,"},{"start":34.48,"end":41.6,"text":"and then I can print this fruit, which is apple. I could turn this variable into a collection"},{"start":41.6,"end":47.92,"text":"by surrounding my values with either a set of square brackets for a list, curly braces for a set,"},{"start":47.92,"end":53.52,"text":"or parentheses for a tuple. Let''s begin with the list. If I would like to store more than one value"},{"start":53.52,"end":59.6,"text":"in this variable, I will surround my values with a set of square brackets. This variable is now a"},{"start":59.6,"end":65.36,"text":"list. I can store multiple values separated with a comma. Not only do we have an apple in this"},{"start":65.36,"end":75.92,"text":"variable, but we have an orange, a banana, and coconut. One naming convention that I like to use,"},{"start":75.92,"end":81.2,"text":"if I declare a collection, such as a list, set, or tuple, I like to take the variable name and make"},{"start":81.2,"end":86.56,"text":"it plural, just so that it''s more obvious that this is a collection of values. Technically,"},{"start":86.56,"end":92.88,"text":"in the English language, fruit would still be plural. English is a weird language. We now have a list"},{"start":92.88,"end":101.52,"text":"of fruit named fruits. If I were to print my list, this is the result. We have all of our values"},{"start":101.52,"end":107.12,"text":"enclosed with a set of square brackets. To access one of these elements found within your list,"},{"start":107.12,"end":112.48,"text":"you can use the index operator, much like what we can do with strings. The first element would"},{"start":112.48,"end":122.24,"text":"have an index of zero. That would print my value apple. Index of one would be my orange. Two is banana."},{"start":122.24,"end":131.92,"text":"Three coconut. What about four? We don''t have a value there. List index out of range. Each value"},{"start":131.92,"end":137.6,"text":"in a collection is also known as an element. If we attempt to access an element that''s not found"},{"start":137.6,"end":143.92,"text":"within our collection, you''ll run into an index error. With the index operator, you could set a"},{"start":143.92,"end":150.64,"text":"beginning index, an ending index, and a step. I would like the first three elements. You could say"},{"start":150.64,"end":158.08,"text":"zero, colon, three. That would give me apple, orange, banana. Technically, you don''t even need the"},{"start":158.08,"end":162.88,"text":"zero. You need that colon, though. We can even use a step. I would like every second element,"},{"start":164.48,"end":170,"text":"apple, banana. It''s every second element beginning from index zero. Maybe I would like my fruit"},{"start":170,"end":175.52,"text":"backwards. I''ll set the step to be negative one. Coconut, banana, orange, apple. You can use the"},{"start":175.52,"end":181.04,"text":"index operator with collections, much like you can use with strings. Another cool thing you can do"},{"start":181.04,"end":188.64,"text":"too with collections is that you can iterate over them with the for loop. For x in my collection,"},{"start":188.64,"end":197.6,"text":"fruits. What would we like to do? I will print whatever x is. So we have iterated over our list,"},{"start":197.6,"end":203.68,"text":"apple, orange, banana, coconut. Now x isn''t really too descriptive. What you''ll see some people do"},{"start":203.68,"end":208.56,"text":"is that with their collection name, it''s plural. Their counter will be the singular version of"},{"start":208.64,"end":213.84,"text":"that word. If our collection name is fruits, let''s rename x as fruit, singular."},{"start":216.16,"end":222.32,"text":"It''s not mandatory, but that''s a common convention. It''s more readable that way. For every fruit in"},{"start":222.32,"end":229.28,"text":"fruits. If this were cars, you could say for car in cars. Our counter is storing whatever value is"},{"start":229.28,"end":233.76,"text":"within our collection. So what are all the different methods that we can use with collections?"},{"start":234.72,"end":240.48,"text":"To list the different methods that are available to a collection, you can use the dur function."},{"start":241.2,"end":247.68,"text":"Within this function, add your collection, fruits. But we would need to print this. Let''s surround"},{"start":247.68,"end":255.12,"text":"this function with a print statement. These are all in alphabetical order. We have attributes,"},{"start":255.12,"end":259.84,"text":"which I have not explained yet, but I will in a future topic. But if we scroll to the end,"},{"start":260.56,"end":265.76,"text":"we have a bunch of different methods that this list can perform. Append, clear, copy, count,"},{"start":265.76,"end":271.04,"text":"extend, index, insert, pop, remove, reverse, and sort. If you would like a description of each"},{"start":271.04,"end":276.4,"text":"of these methods, there is a help function. Help, add your collection to the parentheses,"},{"start":277.12,"end":287.28,"text":"then we would need to print this. Here''s the description of all the methods and attributes."},{"start":287.28,"end":290.64,"text":"For example, we have our sort method. And here''s a description."},{"start":291.28,"end":295.76,"text":"Sort the list in ascending order and return none. And then a bunch of other stuff."},{"start":295.76,"end":299.04,"text":"If you ever forget what you''re capable of with a list or other collection,"},{"start":299.04,"end":304,"text":"you can always use the help function to print a description of the attributes and methods available."},{"start":304.56,"end":308,"text":"If you need the length of how many elements are within a collection,"},{"start":308.72,"end":316.64,"text":"there is the length function. Return the length of my list fruits, then let''s print it."},{"start":317.84,"end":322,"text":"There''s four elements within my list. The length function returns four."},{"start":322.88,"end":329.04,"text":"If I were to add an extra element, like a pineapple, then that number would be five."},{"start":330.32,"end":336.24,"text":"Let''s remove that. Using the in operator, we can find if a value is within a collection."},{"start":337.36,"end":346.32,"text":"Is our value apple in fruits? But then we would need to print this. This operator will return a"},{"start":346.32,"end":354.96,"text":"Boolean. So let''s print whatever that is. Is apple in fruits? That is true. But is pineapple?"},{"start":357.2,"end":362.72,"text":"Pineapple is not. It''s false. You can use the in operator to find if a value is within a list."},{"start":362.72,"end":368.72,"text":"And that applies for your other collections too. With lists, they''re ordered and changeable."},{"start":368.72,"end":373.68,"text":"Duplicates are okay. We can change one of these values after we create our list."},{"start":374.48,"end":380.88,"text":"Let''s take fruits at index of zero. I will set the sequel to be a pineapple."},{"start":382.24,"end":387.68,"text":"Then let''s iterate over our fruit. Using a for loop."},{"start":389.52,"end":394.88,"text":"Okay, the first element is no longer an apple. It''s a pineapple. Then orange banana coconut."},{"start":394.88,"end":399.68,"text":"Using an index, you can reassign one of the values. Bower to change zero to one."},{"start":400.64,"end":403.68,"text":"Well, now we have an apple pineapple banana coconut."},{"start":405.6,"end":409.84,"text":"Let''s cover some of the methods that are found within a list. We can append an element."},{"start":410.96,"end":416.8,"text":"Type the name of the list dot append. What would we like to append to the end of this list?"},{"start":417.36,"end":424.16,"text":"Let''s append a pineapple. I''m going to get rid of this for loop. I''m just going to display my list."},{"start":424.16,"end":429.44,"text":"There we have an apple and orange banana coconut pineapple. To add an element to the end of a list,"},{"start":429.76,"end":436.8,"text":"use the append method. To remove an element, you can use the remove method fruits.remove."},{"start":437.6,"end":443.36,"text":"Let''s remove our apple. Our apple is no longer there. We have an orange banana coconut."},{"start":444.32,"end":450.88,"text":"Using the insert method, we can insert a value at a given index fruits.insert"},{"start":452.24,"end":457.2,"text":"List an index zero would be the beginning, then a value pineapple."},{"start":460.56,"end":467.52,"text":"Now we have a pineapple apple orange banana coconut. The sort method will sort a list fruits.sort."},{"start":469.52,"end":473.68,"text":"These are all in alphabetical order now. Apple banana coconut orange."},{"start":475.36,"end":479.6,"text":"To reverse a list, you would use the reverse method fruits.reverse"},{"start":482.48,"end":487.92,"text":"coconut banana orange apple. However, these are not in reverse alphabetical order. These"},{"start":487.92,"end":492.4,"text":"elements are reversed based on the order in which we place them. If you would like reverse"},{"start":492.4,"end":500.32,"text":"alphabetical order, you can first sort and then reverse. Now we have orange coconut banana apple."},{"start":501.6,"end":507.68,"text":"To clear a list, use the clear method fruits.clear. All of the elements are gone."},{"start":510.4,"end":514.88,"text":"We can return the index of a value. Let''s return the index of apple"},{"start":515.28,"end":527.52,"text":"fruits.index list an element. Then we will need to print this. Let''s print the index that is returned."},{"start":529.84,"end":539.36,"text":"The index of apple is zero. Coconut that would be three. What if we don''t find a value like a pineapple?"},{"start":540.08,"end":545.68,"text":"Well, we have an error. Pineapple is not in list. You could count the amount of times that a value is"},{"start":545.68,"end":553.76,"text":"found within a list because duplicates are okay. Fruits.count. Let''s count how many bananas are in"},{"start":553.76,"end":569.12,"text":"this list. Banana. Then print it. One banana is found within this list. How about pineapples?"},{"start":570.08,"end":576.32,"text":"There are zero. Now those are lists. Surround your values with a set of square brackets. These"},{"start":576.32,"end":582.4,"text":"values are ordered and changeable. Duplicates are okay. Now let''s talk about the next collection"},{"start":582.4,"end":587.76,"text":"which is a set. To create a set, surround your values instead with a set of curly braces."},{"start":588.72,"end":595.36,"text":"Our collection of fruits is now a set. A set has different benefits. The values are unordered and"},{"start":595.36,"end":601.68,"text":"immutable, meaning we can''t alter these values. However, we can add and remove elements. A set"},{"start":601.68,"end":608.8,"text":"does not include any duplicates. I''m going to delete these methods. Then print fruits. We have"},{"start":608.8,"end":615.76,"text":"all of the same values, but they''re not in the same order as they were originally. A set is unordered."},{"start":615.76,"end":620.32,"text":"If I were to run this again, they will likely be in a different order. See, now we have a banana,"},{"start":620.32,"end":625.44,"text":"apple, coconut, orange. To display all of the different attributes and methods of a set,"},{"start":626.64,"end":633.84,"text":"you can use the dur function. And here''s all of them. Some of these methods are a little more"},{"start":633.84,"end":639.84,"text":"advanced, but there''s a few we might recognize like add, clear, copy. For an in-depth description of"},{"start":639.84,"end":647.12,"text":"these methods, you can use the help function. Much like what we did before. To find the length of our"},{"start":647.12,"end":655.2,"text":"set, we can use the length function, which is 4. We can use the in operator to find if a value is"},{"start":655.2,"end":662.08,"text":"found within this set. Unfortunately, pineapples are not within our set. Now, if I was to use the"},{"start":662.08,"end":670.16,"text":"index operator of my set, this is what would happen. We have an error. Set object is not"},{"start":670.16,"end":675.44,"text":"subscriptable. We''re not able to use indexing on a set because they''re unordered, much like what we"},{"start":675.44,"end":681.36,"text":"can do with a list or a string. We can''t change the values of a set, but we could add a remove"},{"start":681.36,"end":691.92,"text":"elements. Let''s use the add method to add, guess what, a pineapple. That is okay. Orange, apple,"},{"start":691.92,"end":700.56,"text":"pineapple, coconut, banana. We can remove an element, fruits.remove. Let''s remove our apple."},{"start":701.28,"end":707.84,"text":"Our apple is gone. Coconut, orange, banana. We can pop."},{"start":711.04,"end":715.52,"text":"The pop method will remove whatever element is first, but it''s going to be random though."},{"start":717.04,"end":722.96,"text":"Orange, coconut, banana. Apple, coconut, banana. Apple, banana, coconut."},{"start":723.76,"end":731.52,"text":"We can add a set. You can clear fruits.clear. The elements of our set are gone. Those are a"},{"start":731.52,"end":737.2,"text":"few of the more useful methods for beginners. As a summary, a set is a collection that is"},{"start":737.2,"end":742.8,"text":"unordered and immutable. You can''t change the values, but adding and removing elements is okay."},{"start":742.8,"end":747.36,"text":"No duplicates are allowed. Let''s try that real quick. I''m going to add a second coconut."},{"start":747.92,"end":755.28,"text":"Yeah, see, we only still have one coconut. Sets may work well if you''re working with constants."},{"start":755.92,"end":759.68,"text":"Maybe colors, for example. You need to find if a color is within a set."},{"start":760.4,"end":765.2,"text":"All right, now lastly, let''s talk about tuples. A tuple is a collection that is surrounded with a"},{"start":765.2,"end":772.96,"text":"set of parentheses. Tuples are ordered and unchangeable. Duplicates are okay. One benefit"},{"start":772.96,"end":778.64,"text":"of a tuple over a list is that tuples are faster than lists. If you''re working with a collection,"},{"start":778.64,"end":782.64,"text":"and it''s okay if the collection is ordered and unchangeable, you might as well use a tuple"},{"start":782.64,"end":788,"text":"because it''s faster. When I print our tuple, all of these values are surrounded with a set of parentheses."},{"start":788.72,"end":793.68,"text":"Again, we have the dir function to display the attributes and methods. There''s not as many for"},{"start":793.68,"end":801.68,"text":"a tuple for methods. We only have count and index. Again, there''s also help to display a description"},{"start":801.68,"end":806.88,"text":"of these attributes and methods. You can find the length of a tuple with the length function."},{"start":807.52,"end":813.04,"text":"We have five elements within here. Using the in operator, we can find if a value is found within"},{"start":813.04,"end":820.56,"text":"our tuple. Our pineapple is not within our fruits. So there''s only two methods we have access to."},{"start":820.56,"end":828.4,"text":"Let''s find the index of apple fruits.index apple. Then I will print whatever is returned."},{"start":828.72,"end":838.8,"text":"Apple is found at index zero. There''s also count fruits dot count. How many coconuts are found"},{"start":838.8,"end":850.08,"text":"within our tuple fruits? Count the coconuts, then print this. How many coconuts we have two coconuts?"},{"start":850.8,"end":855.12,"text":"And then again, with any of these collections, they''re iterable. So you can iterate over them"},{"start":855.12,"end":862.4,"text":"using a for loop for fruit and fruits. Yep, apple, orange, banana, coconut, coconut."},{"start":863.28,"end":868.64,"text":"All right, everybody. So those are collections. Think of them as a single variable used to"},{"start":868.64,"end":875.04,"text":"store multiple values. There''s four general purpose collections for beginners lists, sets,"},{"start":875.04,"end":880.56,"text":"tuples, and then dictionaries, which we''ll talk about next. Each of them has unique benefits."},{"start":880.56,"end":887.2,"text":"Lists are ordered and changeable. Duplicates are okay. A set is unordered and immutable,"},{"start":887.2,"end":893.6,"text":"but adding and removing elements is okay. No duplicates allowed. A tuple is ordered and unchangeable."},{"start":894.24,"end":900.08,"text":"Duplicates are okay, and they are faster than lists. Use tuples if you can over a list."},{"start":900.08,"end":903.2,"text":"But yeah, those are a few collections in Python."}]'::jsonb
) AS segment
WHERE l.youtube_video_id = 'gOMW_n2-2Mw';

