INSERT INTO transcript_chunks (lesson_id, chunk_text, start_time, end_time)
SELECT
    l.id AS lesson_id,
    segment.value->>'text' AS chunk_text,
    (segment.value->>'start')::numeric AS start_time,
    (segment.value->>'end')::numeric AS end_time
FROM lessons l
CROSS JOIN jsonb_array_elements(
    '[{"start":0,"end":5.16,"text":"Imagine you just open an electronic store. You''re hiring some employees, you need to"},{"start":5.16,"end":8.68,"text":"make sure your clients have a good experience as they walk into the store, hopefully purchase"},{"start":8.68,"end":13.9,"text":"more products and you need to standardize all of it. How do you go about doing that?"},{"start":13.9,"end":17.84,"text":"As part of this video, we''re going to go over the fundamentals that will empower you to"},{"start":17.84,"end":23,"text":"make the right decisions when it comes to updating and tweaking your LLMs for your requirement."},{"start":23,"end":29.8,"text":"We will do this from a perspective of context optimization and LLM optimization."},{"start":29.8,"end":33.88,"text":"Context optimization is essentially the window or the text that the model is going to take"},{"start":33.88,"end":39.32,"text":"into account when it generates the text. And the model optimization is actually updating"},{"start":39.32,"end":45.88,"text":"the model based on specific requirements. Now, let''s go back to our store."},{"start":45.88,"end":51.52,"text":"We have hired our first employee, a generalist, polite enough, but you won''t just let him"},{"start":51.52,"end":56.32,"text":"lose on the store. You want to give some guidelines to this person. So always greet"},{"start":56.32,"end":60.64,"text":"the prospective clients, make sure you''re polite and based on the question they''re asking,"},{"start":60.64,"end":64.72,"text":"give them the top three options. Maybe there''s some sales going on that may be relevant to"},{"start":64.72,"end":72.52,"text":"the client, etc., etc. Similarly, in the context of an LLM, we have this thing called prompt"},{"start":72.52,"end":77.08,"text":"engineering. Prompt engineering is giving very clear guidelines on what you expect"},{"start":77.08,"end":81.52,"text":"from the model. You can do so by giving some text. You can also give some examples like"},{"start":81.52,"end":86.28,"text":"input and output so that a model can understand what are you really looking for. You can also"},{"start":86.48,"end":91.64,"text":"help the model break down a complex problem into sub points and make sure it''s kind of"},{"start":91.64,"end":94.8,"text":"understanding what you''re going after in the long run, which is called chain of thought"},{"start":94.8,"end":102.36,"text":"prompting. Now, our employee is doing well but getting inundated by new information coming"},{"start":102.36,"end":107.36,"text":"from all the new devices. That smile can turn into a frown really quickly because it''s"},{"start":107.36,"end":112.4,"text":"hard to be up to speed with all the technology changes coming in. So you have come up with"},{"start":112.44,"end":117.92,"text":"a strategy where you''ve created this manual and this manual has all the updates for all"},{"start":117.92,"end":122.2,"text":"the different gadgets coming in so you''re good. But you can''t expect the employee to"},{"start":122.2,"end":128.84,"text":"read the document every time a user asks a question. So you have devised a strategy based"},{"start":128.84,"end":132.8,"text":"on the question. You report some of the pages from the manual, give it to the employee,"},{"start":132.8,"end":138.8,"text":"read the answer, comes back to it. That in a way is like rag, retrieval augmented generation,"},{"start":139.4,"end":144.36,"text":"which allows you to connect this LLM to your data sources to make sure that you''re getting"},{"start":144.36,"end":148.8,"text":"the right answers. This can address things like hallucination as well because you can"},{"start":148.8,"end":152.64,"text":"really in the prompting you can say you need to give the answer only from these specified"},{"start":152.64,"end":159.44,"text":"documents. So it''s a really powerful tool as well. Now, going back to our store, business"},{"start":159.44,"end":166.08,"text":"is doing really well and we need to hire more employees. That''s great but it was already"},{"start":166.36,"end":169.88,"text":"hard with one employee. How do you make sure you standardize the behavior for all three"},{"start":169.88,"end":175.08,"text":"of them? Being polite can mean different things to different people. Secondly, your customers"},{"start":175.08,"end":178.28,"text":"are getting more savvy. They''re asking more specialized questions. They''re asking things"},{"start":178.28,"end":183,"text":"like how to fix things. So just reading off a guide is not going to do it. What you realize"},{"start":183,"end":189.44,"text":"is you need them to go through a training school, be it from a sales perspective or"},{"start":189.44,"end":193.96,"text":"technical perspective to really make sure that questions are answered. That is like fine"},{"start":194.04,"end":200.04,"text":"tuning. Fine tuning allows you to actually update the model parameters based on your"},{"start":200.04,"end":205.4,"text":"data to ensure that you influence the behavior of the model and also make it specialize in"},{"start":205.4,"end":211.04,"text":"a specific domain as well. Now remember in the beginning I mentioned we are doing this"},{"start":211.04,"end":218.04,"text":"in the lens of context optimization and LLM optimization. So all that means is that drag"},{"start":224.04,"end":230.04,"text":"in and PE are essentially taking all the information you need the model to know beforehand,"},{"start":230.04,"end":234.4,"text":"passing it over for the model to make its deduction, generate the text and come back"},{"start":234.4,"end":239.36,"text":"to it. Fine tuning is actually optimizing the model to ensure that you''re getting the"},{"start":239.36,"end":243.96,"text":"right responses with the right kind of behavior that you would need. This addresses the two"},{"start":243.96,"end":249.8,"text":"key problems we keep hearing from practitioners on why they reluctant to move LLMs into production."},{"start":249.8,"end":255.92,"text":"How do you really moderate the model output both from a text perspective as well from"},{"start":255.92,"end":260.2,"text":"kind of the vernacular and the qualitative aspects if you will. And then the real-time"},{"start":260.2,"end":264.92,"text":"data access, how quickly can you get the model to answer a question from a real-time data"},{"start":264.92,"end":269.16,"text":"as well as ensure that it''s accurate and relevant to the user."},{"start":269.16,"end":274,"text":"So let''s summarize our discussion so far with five points. First one is this whole"},{"start":274,"end":278.88,"text":"technique or set of techniques is additive. So they''re all three working and complimenting"},{"start":278.88,"end":285.24,"text":"each other. The first two rag and PE are done in the context of the context window optimization."},{"start":285.24,"end":290.32,"text":"Fine tuning actually updates the model parameters. This is important because the token window"},{"start":290.32,"end":295.28,"text":"is limited. So the more text you add to it, they can be more noise. So you need to be"},{"start":295.28,"end":300.6,"text":"careful about what you''re passing to the model. Secondly on the model, while it may be expensive,"},{"start":300.6,"end":305.04,"text":"the more you spend on the data and actually update the model with good quality data, you"},{"start":305.04,"end":310.56,"text":"can then use a smaller LLM, insert a bigger LLM and save costs in the long run as well."},{"start":310.56,"end":315.36,"text":"The second one is always start with prompt engineering. This is one of the most powerful"},{"start":315.36,"end":320.64,"text":"and agile tools that you have in your repository to ensure that A, you understand whether even"},{"start":320.64,"end":326.12,"text":"having an LLM based solution is right. Two, the kind of data that you have, the end users"},{"start":326.12,"end":330.56,"text":"is the baseline model accurate and all the work that you do in even the trial and error"},{"start":330.56,"end":335.88,"text":"can actually be used for fine tuning. So it''s really, really worth it. The third one is"},{"start":335.88,"end":340.88,"text":"also important. People start worrying about the context window optimization too soon."},{"start":340.88,"end":350.08,"text":"So focus more on the accuracy versus the optimization. So what I mean by that is as you get closer"},{"start":350.08,"end":355.52,"text":"to the right answer, especially in the context of again the window optimization, keep looking"},{"start":355.52,"end":359.24,"text":"into the right answers and then start seeing different strategies on how you can reduce"},{"start":359.24,"end":365.68,"text":"the window. The fourth one is people say that data quantity is really key for fine tuning."},{"start":365.68,"end":372.2,"text":"Yes, that''s important, but I would take the data quality, DQ, better than honestly the"},{"start":372.2,"end":380,"text":"data quantity. This is really valuable because you can really start a good example of a fine"},{"start":380,"end":384.8,"text":"tuning by just 100 examples. Of course that differs from every use case, but really focus"},{"start":384.8,"end":388.72,"text":"in the quality. Some of the output that we get from prompt engineering is also going"},{"start":388.72,"end":396.8,"text":"to be very important. This brings me to my last point. You need to be able to quantify"},{"start":396.8,"end":404.04,"text":"and baseline your success. Just saying that the answer is good enough is not going to"},{"start":404.04,"end":408.32,"text":"cut it, especially when you try these techniques and try the nuances. The permutations between"},{"start":408.32,"end":413.48,"text":"these three can be huge. So you need to make sure from an accuracy perspective, precision"},{"start":413.48,"end":418.76,"text":"perspective, again going back to the context optimization, if you''re using RAG, not only"},{"start":418.76,"end":422.6,"text":"is the answer important, it''s also important what kind of documents you got from the vector"},{"start":422.6,"end":428,"text":"database. This will help you reduce latency. So a lot of really good solutions that you"},{"start":428,"end":432.36,"text":"can get if you can start really quantifying everything and what success looks like for"},{"start":432.36,"end":438.72,"text":"you. So going to a diagram here, the two key commonalities between all three is you''re"},{"start":438.84,"end":444.96,"text":"going to have increased accuracy, reducing hallucinations, so not making up answers."},{"start":444.96,"end":449.52,"text":"Start with your PE. Prompt engineering will help you really ensure that you have the right"},{"start":449.52,"end":454.88,"text":"solution. So really quick iteration, super valuable. RAG is going to help you connect"},{"start":454.88,"end":459.2,"text":"your context window to external data sources. You can give it some guidance as well. And"},{"start":459.2,"end":464.56,"text":"fine tuning actually changes the model behavior. You can control it more and can become a specialized"},{"start":464.56,"end":469.92,"text":"model in a specific domain that you have. In terms of the commonality between RAG and"},{"start":469.92,"end":475.2,"text":"prompt engineering, context window optimization is key, of course. It is constrained by that."},{"start":475.2,"end":480.36,"text":"So as you look for accuracy, you need to focus on how can you optimize that as well. Between"},{"start":480.36,"end":484.8,"text":"prompt engineering and fine tuning, whilst they both are kind of influencing some model,"},{"start":484.8,"end":488.68,"text":"they do it in different ways. So prompting can give some guidance, only respond in three"},{"start":488.68,"end":494.08,"text":"points. Fine tuning almost guarantees it in the vernacular that you wanted. Finally, between"},{"start":494.12,"end":498.6,"text":"RAG and fine tuning, both can incorporate the data sources, but really think of RAG as the"},{"start":498.6,"end":503.24,"text":"short-term memory and fine tune as the long-term memory for what you''re trying to do."},{"start":503.24,"end":508.6,"text":"So if I were to summarize, context optimization is super valuable. It is one of the easiest"},{"start":508.6,"end":513.52,"text":"in the first route that you should take to how to optimize an LLM model. The second one"},{"start":513.52,"end":517.44,"text":"is once you have decided, okay, you have optimized it, but you''re seeing you''re getting more"},{"start":517.44,"end":522.56,"text":"and more end users, latency is becoming a problem. And now you know, okay, you know what,"},{"start":522.56,"end":527.56,"text":"I can fine tune my use case a bit more. That''s where you use fine tuning. This will help"},{"start":527.56,"end":532.32,"text":"you really specialize the model. It will not be a general list. So there''s a risk there,"},{"start":532.32,"end":537.24,"text":"but as you focus your use case more, fine tuning is the right way to go."},{"start":537.24,"end":541.12,"text":"So if I were to summarize the discussion, as you know, all three techniques are really"},{"start":541.12,"end":546.4,"text":"powerful. But if you see it from the lens of context optimization, focusing on all the"},{"start":546.4,"end":551,"text":"words and things you want to send to the model before it generates text, it is limited by"},{"start":551,"end":556.44,"text":"the number of tokens. So the more you increase there, there''s going to be more latency, there''s"},{"start":556.44,"end":560.48,"text":"going to be hope, maybe more downtime. And the more documents you bring in, it could"},{"start":560.48,"end":564.04,"text":"actually create more noise for the model because it really doesn''t understand that specific"},{"start":564.04,"end":570.32,"text":"data. However, on the other hand, if you have a model and you know you have specific monocular,"},{"start":570.32,"end":576.52,"text":"very specialized domain, medical, financial, legal, etc., etc., fine tuning is an option"},{"start":576.56,"end":581.4,"text":"where you can actually update the parameters of the model using your data. As I mentioned"},{"start":581.4,"end":585.68,"text":"before, you can look at the input and output you got from prompt engineering and make the"},{"start":585.68,"end":590.96,"text":"model a more specialized expert. It can also help you control the model behavior, which"},{"start":590.96,"end":596.48,"text":"is super important when you talk about corporations and them using LLMs for their end user solutions"},{"start":596.48,"end":598.44,"text":"as well."},{"start":598.44,"end":603,"text":"Prompt engineering and RAG, again, the context window is the best way to kind of start and"},{"start":603,"end":607.64,"text":"really ensure that you understand if LLMs are the right way to go and you can augment"},{"start":607.64,"end":609.88,"text":"it with fine tuning at their appropriate stage as well."}]'::jsonb
) AS segment
WHERE l.youtube_video_id = 'pZjpNS9YeVA';

-- File: qg4PchTECck.json
-- YouTube Video ID: qg4PchTECck

INSERT INTO transcript_chunks (lesson_id, chunk_text, start_time, end_time)
SELECT
    l.id AS lesson_id,
    segment.value->>'text' AS chunk_text,
    (segment.value->>'start')::numeric AS start_time,
    (segment.value->>'end')::numeric AS end_time
FROM lessons l
CROSS JOIN jsonb_array_elements(
    '[{"start":0,"end":4.64,"text":"Gradient descent is the process by which machines learn how to generate new faces,"},{"start":4.64,"end":9.16,"text":"play hide and seek, and even beat the best humans at games like Dota."},{"start":9.16,"end":11.76,"text":"But what exactly is gradient descent?"},{"start":11.76,"end":15.92,"text":"To answer that question, let''s say you are trying to train your computer"},{"start":15.92,"end":21.76,"text":"to listen to an audio file and recognize three spoken commands based on a labeled data set."},{"start":21.76,"end":27.28,"text":"The first step is to formulate this machine learning task as a mathematical optimization problem."},{"start":28,"end":32.8,"text":"For example, you can work with a neural network whose weights are unknown variables,"},{"start":33.92,"end":40.4,"text":"whose input is an audio data, and whose output is a vector of size 3 where each entry represents"},{"start":40.4,"end":44.32,"text":"how much the neural network thinks the audio corresponds to each command."},{"start":44.32,"end":49.36,"text":"Then, for each example in the data set, you can pair the output of the neural network"},{"start":49.36,"end":54,"text":"to the ideal output. Take the difference, the square and then the sum,"},{"start":54.08,"end":58.48,"text":"and you get the cost of a single training example. By taking the sum over all training"},{"start":58.48,"end":63.84,"text":"examples, you get the overall cost function. And the problem now becomes, how do we find"},{"start":63.84,"end":68.24,"text":"the right value of theta that makes this cost function as small as possible?"},{"start":69.44,"end":73.76,"text":"And this is where the second step, or gradient descent, comes in."},{"start":73.76,"end":77.36,"text":"And you might ask, why do we need to invent an algorithm for this at all?"},{"start":77.36,"end":81.04,"text":"Can''t we just plot the function and point to the minimizer?"},{"start":81.04,"end":86.08,"text":"Well, theta usually has many more entries than just two. And in that set in,"},{"start":86.08,"end":89.6,"text":"it''s hard to see what the function looks like. So what can we do?"},{"start":90.64,"end":95.52,"text":"The insight of gradient descent is that, while we cannot get a look at the whole function all at"},{"start":95.52,"end":102.4,"text":"once, we can easily evaluate the cost function at an arbitrary point. And with a process called"},{"start":102.4,"end":107.12,"text":"back propagation, we can also evaluate the negative gradient of this cost function,"},{"start":107.12,"end":112.32,"text":"and take a small step in that direction. Gradient descent continues in an iterative fashion."},{"start":112.32,"end":117.6,"text":"It computes the negative gradient at the new point, takes a step in that direction, and so on and so"},{"start":117.6,"end":122.88,"text":"forth. The intuition behind every step is that the gradient of a function gives you the direction"},{"start":122.88,"end":127.84,"text":"that increases that function the most. So by taking a small step in the opposite direction,"},{"start":127.84,"end":132.72,"text":"you can hope to make the function decrease at each iteration. Gradient descent, as I just"},{"start":132.72,"end":137.04,"text":"presented it, is known as vanilla gradient descent, because several variants have been"},{"start":137.04,"end":142.32,"text":"developed throughout the years to improve it. In stochastic gradient descent, instead of taking"},{"start":142.32,"end":147.2,"text":"the sum over all training examples when taking the gradient of the cost function, which can be"},{"start":147.2,"end":152.56,"text":"expensive when the number of examples is big, we can take a small random subset at each iteration."},{"start":153.6,"end":159.52,"text":"Adaptive gradient descent picks a different step size for each component of theta. And this can be"},{"start":159.52,"end":165.6,"text":"extremely useful when data is sparse, like text data and image data. Momentum gradient descent"},{"start":165.6,"end":170.8,"text":"keeps track of previously computed gradients to build up momentum and accelerate conversions"},{"start":170.8,"end":174.96,"text":"to the minimizer. This was gradient descent in under three minutes. If you like the video,"},{"start":174.96,"end":185.84,"text":"like and subscribe, and see you next time."}]'::jsonb
) AS segment
WHERE l.youtube_video_id = 'qg4PchTECck';

